text: I would say that I accidentally discovered this place, but having walked past it a few times in a number of days, I decided that it might be an idea to step in and check it out. Anyway, I hadn&#39;t had much in the way of breakfast yet and I was starting to feel hungry. Well, if you happen to be in that position, then this place is certainly a place worth checking out. The staff were excellent, and the food wasn&#39;t all that pricey either. They made a decent pot of tea, and there was a reasonable range on the menu as well, It is certainly a decent place to check out.

text: Get away from the hustle &#39;n&#39; bustle!<br><br>This funky little craft brew joint caters to all types and offers chillaxing vibes after a hard day at the salt mines.<br><br>Stone &amp; Wood&#39;s Pacific Ale offers a crisp clean and easy drinker starter to get the night going; A red apple cider from Zeffer and Sunday&#39;s sweet malt pilsner liven up the party before the hammer comes down with Stone&#39;s IPA (6.4%).<br><br>Another one would seemingly be a good idea before you realise you have a marketing pitch the next day.<br><br>Time to put these plans (and yourself) to bed!

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/GtGDLFOQ9xGprgOF_q0M3w/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/fish-soup-at-alexandra-village-singapore?reviewid=nF2kRTG181Z0ieaMXCYCQQ&select=GtGDLFOQ9xGprgOF_q0M3w', 'altText': 'Photo of Fish Soup at Alexandra Village - Singapore, Singapore', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': ''}]
text: This fish soup store that is situated in the same coffee shop as the famous Keng Eng Kee Seafood Restaurant has no store name. Instead its signboard just display the different items that they sell and the prices. Regardless of the lack of a store name, it has become famous - drawing long queues during lunch hour on weekdays. In fact, all the tables of the coffee shop are occupied by patrons of the fish soup store, leaving little room for the other stores in the coffee shop.<br><br>The soup is amazingly sweet and delicious but not too salty. This is one of the few fish soup stores where I dare to order sliced fish instead of fried fish because their fish is really fresh and has no fishy smell at all! The thick beehoon is cooked just right too - not clumpy or soggy. <br><br>They also sell pig&#39;s organ soup, pork porridge and yam rice to go with your soup. My suggestion is to skip the yam rice which is not very special. Try the fish soup and if you have space left, get the pig&#39;s organ soup too.

text: It&#39;s a nett priced restaurant! Which is a plus for a budget Melissa! And the egg florentine were delicious! The spinach with the smoked salmon and the baguette! :) great breakfast/lunch/dinner :) it says that it&#39;s meant for the weekends but I managed to order it on a weekday! It&#39;s a very quiet cafe facing china street with chill background music, rustic wooden tables and chalk boards with their menu written all over with colourful chalks :) it&#39;s a very charming place :) we also had the rustic burger which was very fresh. The tomatoes were sweet and you can tell that the meat isn&#39;t frozen :)

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/54DPMhZpuSWW7QzUW4epuA/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/yu-kee-duck-rice-singapore-2?reviewid=MmT5k4vhVwjEBwhBU7x56Q&select=54DPMhZpuSWW7QzUW4epuA', 'altText': 'Photo of Yu Kee Duck Rice - Singapore, Singapore. #1', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': '#1'}]
text: I came here on my first night at Singapore. Man, it was such a sad first meal here. I had #1, which I think is the duck with rice and an egg and some marinated tofu. The duck rice I had back at home in NY was so much better. #1 was overly sweet and the rice just tasted sweet in general with no flavor. I like to think an egg can make it or break a dish. Surely, this tea egg broke the dish. Where is the tea flavor? Or like any soy sauce flavor ? <br><br>Such a huge disappointment. But if you&#39;re hungry and not picky, this 5 SGD dish may do for you. You won&#39;t feel full though.

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/tXNwufxDftMtD28XRrlcYQ/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/yu-kee-duck-rice-singapore-2?reviewid=qS5pi1X1OrlbNLTaa0u51g&select=tXNwufxDftMtD28XRrlcYQ', 'altText': 'Photo of Yu Kee Duck Rice - Singapore, Singapore. Duck rice $4.50', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Duck rice $4.50'}]
text: Rice cooked in a dark sauce, a moreish sauce poured over, half of a stewed hard boiled egg, duck chopped so thin I could barely taste it, some stewed peanuts, salted veggies and soy puffs. <br><br>I don&#39;t get the hype, and neither is the taste really great. I thought the rice would be yam rice, but really it is just dark soy sauce rice. It isn&#39;t a bad-tasting plate, but it isn&#39;t fantastic either. For a duck rice, really ought to have more duck.
Soso place to dine here... nothing good about their food here.... if fill up your hunger, is ok. Don&#39;t come here in purpose for good food. Not worth it.

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/7Zrau54iSxEe4vJ__fbEsg/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/yu-kee-duck-rice-singapore-2?reviewid=frIOm8_izDLM9y05W0dd1w&select=7Zrau54iSxEe4vJ__fbEsg', 'altText': 'Photo of Yu Kee Duck Rice - Singapore, Singapore', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': ''}]
text: Yu Kee Duck Rice has been around for over sixty years now and the main branch is found here at Liang Seah Street just across Bugis Junction. These days though, thanks to the power of franchising, its actually everywhere, even in food courts.<br><br>Sadly, its one of those old favourites that has lost its lustre. First off, service standards is really poor and the staff is exceptionally rude. The quality of the food has also dropped significantly from being one of the best duck rice in Singapore to one of the worst. <br><br>The ultimate death knell for me though is the chilli. Yu Kee used to be very famous for their ikan bilis mixed chilli. These days it just taste really salty and oily. <br><br>Dont get me wrong though, its still decent duck rice overall but not worth the hype. So unless you got a craving for duck rice, there are much better other food options in the area.

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/t_fURXi1bPpzMnZSgGuhdQ/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/yu-kee-duck-rice-singapore-2?reviewid=CBFh0mQ-dVXvSDciokyYmA&select=t_fURXi1bPpzMnZSgGuhdQ', 'altText': 'Photo of Yu Kee Duck Rice - Singapore, Singapore', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': ''}]
text: We decided to try this supposedly famous stall one day. Upon eating the food, we found the duck relatively nice but not outstandingly good.<br><br>Given that it was relatively crowded at that time, we assumed that the food would be freshly prepared and so the chances of contamination arising from stale food were minimal. Boy, were we wrong. We ended up having food poisoning - and the attendant consequences - for the next two days.

It&#39;s an old famous duck rice stall. I think it used to be much better. The duck rice is still ok and the yam rice is yummy. But overall, it lacks the same punch from yesteryear. Nonetheless still a decent meal.

Yu Kee is known for its stew sauce recipe, which has been used and improved on for over 60 years. I ordered the Specialty Duck Rice ($3.80) that comes with a plate of brown stewed rice, duck, stewed bean curd and hardboiled egg and a bowl of soup. <br><br>Their rice has been known to be stewed in a special sauce, which turns in brown. It was great because the rice was tasty enough to be eaten alone. The duck meat was tender and very lean. Together with the sauce that it was covered in, it was delightful without an overpowering herbal flavor. This dish is great when eaten with their ikan bilis chili. The soup was flavorful with an herbal taste to it, but it was a tad too salty. <br><br>Overall, the duck rice was enjoyable but slightly salty. In a coffee shop atmosphere, it is also a place that is more suitable more a quick meal.

text: Yu Kee duck rice sells very delicious duck rice. I have been eating their brand of duck rice for many years and I&#39;m still not bored of it.<br><br>They may produce really good food but definetly not good service. The store assistant have changed to a new guy and the new guy provides really bad service. Not that I want a 5 star service quality but at least give customers basic respect. This new store assistant looks young, wears glasses and has a face with many &#39;pimple hole&#39;. He provides very bad service. I was once served by him. I said I want an additional egg, and he questioned me in a very rude way saying &#39; There is already an egg in the set, you still want another one ?&#39; I thought he was being judgemental and rude. <br><br>How can he be in the service line when he belittles his customers and question what they want ??

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/gkdFCWCCcSxzeY7wLP-1Rw/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/project-a%C3%A7ai-singapore?reviewid=uonDHem_nJg9bdxRcNJafA&select=gkdFCWCCcSxzeY7wLP-1Rw', 'altText': 'Photo of Project Açai - Singapore, Singapore', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': None}]
text: Love this place!! The Açai bowls are amazing and tastes so fresh and not too sweet at all. It&#39;s refreshing on a hot day in Singapore and the toppings include great fruits and a granola mix. I tried two different types, as can be seen in the photos. Prices are reasonable and the serving size is perfect. There&#39;s a single serve and a larger bowl size. I think I could easily eat a larger bowl, but the small individual size is perfect for a quick snack. I could see it also being a meal substitute! <br><br>The location is also extremely convenient to the gardens. Not a lot of space in terms of parking and seating, but there a couple locations in town and it&#39;s a very popular place. Don&#39;t hesitate to try the Açai bowls, they are very good! There&#39;s also a small unisex restroom.

If I get the craving, they also have a stall in the Takashimaya shopping center.<br>I do like the holland v atmosphere because it&#39;s larger and more conducive for hanging out. text: I can&#39;t comment on the açaí bowls because i never had them, but my boyfriend says they&#39;re pretty good - on par with açaí bowls we&#39;ve had in LA and Australia. <br><br>The shop is (dangerously) just around the corner from our apartment, so we&#39;ve visited 4 days in a row. I always get the Coffee America-No smoothie, which was spot on and amazing the first time I tried it. I feel like since our first visit, the quality of the smoothie has declined on the following days (hence the 3 stars). Today&#39;s was the worst. We ordered 2 smoothies and both of them came out super watery and mine had a lot of banana chunks. <br><br>Using Day 1&#39;s 5 star-quality smoothie as a reference, today and yesterday&#39;s smoothies tasted like some ingredients were missing -- eg the cacao nibs and the almond butter. I certainly hope that&#39;s not the case, because a cup of this stuff isn&#39;t  exactly cheap. I think the shop could employ some stricter standardization practices. <br><br>Other than that, we love the atmosphere and overall vibe of the shop. This shouldn&#39;t take away from the high rating that their açaí bowls deserve. Maybe we&#39;ll stick to their bowls for now :)

text: Absolutely loved going here for tea and snacks during our recent trip to SG. The place is pricey so be aware of that. They have a lot of different tea options and the staff is all very good at explaining the different flavors. We tried two (unable to recall the names), but absolutely loved both of them. <br><br>The snacks are also great including the desserts. We tried the sandwiches the benedict. I loved the sandwich it was delicious. They start the tea ceremony stuff later on in the afternoon, so we were not able to participate in that, but for next time we know. <br><br>After eating at the cafe, we went to the TWG shop to buy a few teas to take back home with us, but it was way too busy and expensive so left without getting it. Regretting our decision now. I guess TWG amongst other things in SG will be the reason we go back.

text: I have lost count how many times I passed next to this store and the wonderful smell was always there!<br><br>I entered this store and I felt that I was in Disney, at least, my kind of Disney! with so many different tea flavors, teapots and cup of all sizes and forms.<br><br>I wish I could take them all.<br><br>The service was on point and their macaroons were extremely delicious, they practically melted in my mouth. All the flavors were screaming my name and the price was great; only $2.00 per piece.<br><br>Thank you!

The employee was nice to serve me even though I only bought one macaron to try during closing. <br><br>The manager or supervisor on the other hand was a bit rude, while I was paying for my one macaron he didn&#39;t look at me nor acknowledged I was around he just handed me the receipt to sign and didn&#39;t say thank you. <br><br>I stayed at the marina bay sands hotel, which was a amazing experience for me. As well as I know I can get different type of food downstairs at the food court. <br><br>By the way <br>The macaron is so good ! $2 Singapore money

text: You&#39;re paying for the experience. From the elegant food to the bougey ambiance of the Marina Bay Shoppes, that is pretty much what you are paying for when you dine here. <br><br>I&#39;ve always walked by this location every time I&#39;ve been to Singapore and I was always curious to what it was like. I landed in Singapore in the late afternoon and wanted a quick snack time with some caffeine involved.<br><br>I ordered the Fortune Tea Set during their high tea hours. I thought the food was very delicious. Just what you would want for an afternoon pick up. My tea tower included one of the finger sandwiches, scones or muffins, and three macarons. I decided on the truffle croque, the golden raisen scones, a earl grey tea macaron, a rose macaron, and a tiramisu macaron. For the tea, I decide on the hot original Black Tea 1837. <br><br>I would be back again for afternoon high tea. Not sure if I want to eat here for a full meal because there are a ton of other heartier and more &#34;value&#34; options around the Marina Bay Shoppes. I say give this place a try if your looking for high tea and live your glamorous life! You&#39;re in Singapore in the first place!

text: My boyfriend loved this place. Hands down, of all the places we went to, we went to this place TWICE because he liked it that much (the pasta). Our first dining experience here was amazing---service was spot on and spectacular. Second time, we had to flag down our server several times and it left us feeling a certain way we didn&#39;t care for. <br><br>The place is situated right in the middle of mall which certainly gives  great opportunity to people watch. Definitely worth the trip depending on what server you get!

text: TWG is very old tea house and famous.  They have multiple locations..  This store is located inside the shopping mall next to Marina Bay Sands.   Very small place but have everything to enjoy afternoon tea.  <br><br>So many choices of teas to choose..  I took the recommended tea and loved it..  It was summer something (can&#39;t remember the exact name).<br><br>Price of the tea is not cheap but it will be great experience since they are not instant teas. Relaxing and enjoying the afternoon tea with sweets...  it was very meaningful.  Most of all, my wife loved it..

text: Pretty much everything went wrong, but sometimes you have to find humor in disaster. My girlfriends and I stopped by for a (very expensive) snack because one of them desperately needed to charge her iPhone. This is what defines millennial friendship- spending money for access to a power outlet.<br><br>We were seated and left to peruse the menu. 20 minutes pass without any server attention. Well, I guess there&#39;s no rush since her phone was charging behind the bar and our feet were in dire need of rest. A server finally approaches, but to move us to a table on the other side because our current section needed &#34;maintenance.&#34; Sketchy, but ok. After 10 minutes at our new table, our order still hadn&#39;t been taken. At this point, we thought of it as a game and actively tried not to get their attention...until I noticed ants crawling all over my silverware. We informed a server and he moved us to...the table immediately next to it. Because ants keep to themselves and wouldn&#39;t bother us if we&#39;re 1 ft away. <br><br>Anyway, at our third table in 35 minutes, we finally placed our order- earl grey tea, mushroom soup, 1 earl grey macaron, 1 grand wedding macaron, and 2 black tea blackcurrant macarons. We tore into the macarons, and my BFF noted that the black one tastes nothing like blackcurrant. I commented that it actually tasted like caramel, then realized that we may have been given the Napoleon tea with caramel by mistake. I asked our server what flavor this black colored macaron was, and he confirmed my suspicion. I told him we ordered a different one, and his response, &#34;oh I heard you say black so I thought you wanted the black colored macaron.&#34; Wtf? I didn&#39;t order them by color- I ordered them exactly as listed on the menu. &#34;I guess it&#39;s okay, we already ate most of it...&#34; I trailed off, expecting he&#39;d come thru with an apology for his dumbassedness and offer to bring the correct ones. I got nothing but an awkward staring contest. Poor guy had a blank look on his face and didn&#39;t know wtf to do, so I just said it was fine. To add insult to injury, these black macarons have dye that stained my lips and teeth, so my selfies for the night were ruined. The more I thought about this, the more my rage grew, so I asked to speak to the manager. He handled it like a pro and sent over 3 black tea blackcurrant macarons (threw in an extra freebie since there were 3 of us). Btw, they were red in color.<br><br>If you didn&#39;t have time to read the above novel, just know the food and tea are mediocre, the prices aren&#39;t justified, and the service is lacking. But you can charge your phone behind the bar if needed.

text: Great afternoon tea spot after shopping/window shopping all day! Their tea menu is INSANE - there&#39;s a guide book too for those who want a more detailed description of the teas. You really can&#39;t go wrong with any of the selections. The basic tea set is S$19, which comes with a pot of tea and a pastry or 2 scones/muffins. This would also be a good lunch spot for a date or something. Even though it&#39;s in the middle of the mall, the space is quite nice with some privacy behind the pots of orchids. Besides from the pastries in their trolley, you can also get special desserts. We tried the tarte tatin, wouldn&#39;t really recommend it. The tarte that the stewed apple came in was quite hard, so it was hard to eat it all together. The black berry fruit tart was quite nice though! Oh, and scones come with clotted cream and jam. <br><br>TIP: there&#39;s not a second steeping (they brew the tea in the back), but you can ask for more hot water.

text: The tea was very fragrant and flavorful but what really stole the show was the crepe cake!!<br>If you guys decide to have afternoon tea here, the crepe cake is a MUST! Crepe cakes are hard to perfect given the delicate layers and the perfect texture. However, the crepe cake here is definitely comparable, if not almost better than Lady M!<br><br>Even though it is located in the middle of the mall, the ambience was very nice and elegant!

text: The ambiance is incredible, the food itself is OK. So this location is located on top of a bridge inside the Marine Bay Sands. Underneath the bridge they have gondolas going by kinda like they way they do in Italy. It&#39;s 100% tourist, but the experience was a lot of fun. This is essentially a tea parlor with some savory and some desserts, the list of teas they carry is mindbogglingly. There are some many different varieties of teas, it can get overwhelming, but just make sure to talk with your server.<br><br>The food:<br><br>Chocolate fondant- warm chocolate cake served with a light custard cream and a scoop of homemade vanilla bourbon ice cream. The combination all worked nicely. The cake did feel a little too dense, the ice cream was lighter and easier to eat. For me, it was good, but not great. <a href="http://www.yelp.com/user_local_photos?select=Aod55R1VaA4PKZz98eAaRg&amp;userid=Y_iTTjKvV5hLy-880SZzlA">yelp.com/user_local_phot…</a>
Fancy tea place in Singapore.  Bit overpriced but a huge selection of teas. Great ambience.. well deserved 3.5 stars.

text: You can&#39;t take photos in the store but you can whatever you want if you&#39;re having tea!  Service was outstanding and the truffle sandwiches were so good.  The Parisian tea set with two teas and snacks for two was $70.  So worth it.  And you can drink from the $200+ teapots and admire all the TWG branded swag like the linens, all porcelain, etc.  They have so many teas - it&#39;s ridiculous.  I&#39;d recommend coming here at least once!

text: +Before we begin, It was 10.30pm when I got there. <br>The first thing I asked out loud was &#34;Where&#39;z the coffee&#34;<br><br>true story.<br><br>--------------<br><br>This place, when you sit down, you don&#39;t just watch people. People watch you.<br>So when you eat, a good tip is to eat like a lady.<br><br>-----------------<br><br>I had the chocolate Earl Grey tea. It was damn nice. I loved it. <br>It smelled and tasted of chocolate and tea.<br>The only horrible thing was they only served 1 pot and the cups were too dainty.<br>Give it to me in a beer mug and a barrel of tea , i SAY!<br><br>Food..i had some foie gras salad thing and chicken.<br>I&#39;m sorry if i can&#39;t give you the exact details. 10.30pm was way past my bedtime and they don&#39;t seem to serve coffee.<br><br>Chicken was meh. it was alright. tasted like chicken. I&#39;ve had better chicken elsewhere.<br>I think i had better chicken at a hawker centre.<br>¯\_(ツ)_/¯<br><br>Foie Gras...meeeeh<br>no opinion. sorry guys<br><br>-----<br>Tea Fantastic<br>Food Meh<br>French Waiter Cute but my singaporean accent threw him off

Doubting between two and three stars here:<br><br>Food and drinks: definitely two stars.<br>I was extremely disappointed to discover that these huge &amp; attractive tea pots are served less than half full while the cheapest tea is 11 S$. As a huge fan of cream tea, I decided to go for the 19 S$ set which offers two scones, jam and clotted cream plus a tea of your choice (as long it is the 11 $S kind though). <br>I honestly fell disappointed and cheated upon, the scones were tiny but what I thought was even worse was the amount of tea served. Like indicated above, the pots are filled less than half, more like a quarter.<br>I must admit that the scones were nice but considering the price and size I take that as a given, additionally the clotted cream was not really clotted cream.<br><br>Service and atmosphere: three stars.<br>Overall the service is average, they do provide you with extra lemon slices for your tea when asked but the real reason for going here is the location: this place is in the middle of MBS, which is one of the poshest malls in Singapore and you sit in &#34;the luxury circle&#34; surrounded by Prada, Louis Vuitton and others. So it is excellent for people watching and you feel like you are part of that luxury world (what do you want after paying 11 S$ for a empty-ish teapot).<br><br>So would I go again? Nope as I think it is horribly overpriced but I guess you pay for the location. Any other TWG in Singapore would get two stars.

text: &#34;TWG Tea is a brand of tea which was established in Singapore in 2008. The company promotes itself as a luxury brand. TWG stands for The Wellness Group.&#34; - Wikipedia / TWG website.<br><br>This is a classic example of how money cannot buy you class. The location is great, the furniture is great. These two alone must have cost TWG a pretty penny.<br><br>The look and feel of the brand screams &#34;Twinings&#34;. And Twinings have been around for 300 years. TWG, in the age of the internet, surely you cannot expect people to buy into your &#34;been around since 1837&#34; myth? Also, for extra credit, homework tonight: Read about the lawsuit filed by another tea company over TWG&#39;s logo. Good reads!<br><br>Back to TWG!<br><br>Even with the great location and ambience, TWG disappoints in all three areas: Tea, Food and Service.<br><br>_The Tea_<br><br>Ahhh, a tea shop! Prides itself on the range of tea and knowledgeable staff. What I got was snotty, rude wait staff. No help with the tea selection, no charming conversation about the brand. Just a slightly grotty thick menu with a lot of BIG words describing tea.<br><br>_The Food_<br><br>The food was overpriced, and just NOT good. <br><br>Example of overpriced: SGD$32 for a &#34;Chic Tea Set&#34;- 3 finger sandwiches, 2 baby scones, 1 glass of iced tea. - SGD$32! ANYWAY....if the finger sandwiches were good, or IF the scones were fresh or IF the iced tea was topped up, it wouldn&#39;t be too bad. But nope. It was just NOT good.<br><br>Macaron - $2 each. Pretty enough, I pointed to the colours not flavours. There were no signs identifying the flavours. I just chose the prettiest ones: Purple and Blue. Later, in my bill, I find out it was vanilla and passion. (Passion?) The macarons were soggy inside and crumbled too easily. Where&#39;s the almond meal? Where&#39;s the flavour? Where&#39;s my macaron!!?<br><br>Iced Tea (in a glass) SGD$11. I was so beyond disappointed by this time, I had no energy left to rage about the $11 iced tea.<br><br>_The Service_<br><br>Cold, unattentive service. At some points, there weere 8 staff on the floor, 3 behind the counter looking busy, the other 5 with their backs to the tables, talking to the staff behind the counters. (Wow, sorry about that long sentence.)<br><br>They didn&#39;t seem to know the menu very well, or if they did, they sure didn&#39;t share their knowledge. <br><br>In summary, stop kidding ourselves. TWG (since 2008) is not what it makes itself out to be. May get better, may even live up to it&#39;s self-generated hype. <br><br>But till then, let&#39;s spend our money elsewhere.

text: Everywhere I look something is sparkling: gold, fine china and most precious crystal, which you can likewise purchase. We see the most wonderful wooden tea tins, which are filigree hand-painted. The rear walls are covered with huge tins full of fine teas. It is not surprising at all, that TWG is known for its innovative tea variety.<br>There is, for example, a tea from Japan, which is usually not sold out of the country. Only TWG may offer it outside of Japan. In addition, there are also some sorts of tea, which are offset with gold. Later, when the very nice tea master opens one of the large tins, golden tea dust gets swirled up. <br>A visit to this store is truly an extraordinary tea experience.

text: Lovely place to chill, chat and hide from the heat. <br><br>Decided to take a break after walking quite a bit in town and at the mall. We were there on a weekday afternoon so it was rather empty and we were served promptly. <br><br>The waiter sits you down, hands you the menu and help with placing the napkin on your lap. The &#34;classy&#34; experience they try to portray and carry. Not too bad I must say.<br><br>The tea menu is ultra long. It&#39;s about an A2 size back and front printed with font 12?! A<br><br>What I usually do is have the waiter make some recommendations based on what kind of taste I feel like having today. Otherwise, I will probably take around 1hr to choose! And a Tea Book which is sort of a dictionary for the tea offered. <br><br>I asked for Sweet and Flowery. He recommended Silver Moon tea and Alfonso Tea. Took the silver moon option, tasted great. Pleasant and smells lovely.<br><br>My friend had a chocolate earl grey. It did smell like chocolate but tasted funny.<br><br>Ordered a tarte which was average. They have a decent selection of food, appetizers and snacks too. <br><br>Love to hang and chill at this cafe with friends. The atmosphere is very classy and soothing, allows you to chat at a comfortable volume unlike the local kopi shops which are great just a tad noisy.

text: We went for tea on a weekday to celebrate my friend&#39;s birthday. We ordered cakes and tea. My friend did not know the name of the cake, so she pointed at the fridge to highlight that she wanted the red colour cake. The waiter acknowledged. When the cake is served, instead of a cake, the waiter served a creme brûlée! <br>My friend told him it was a wrong order. He then served the correct cake. But with no fork. We were a bit surprised at the whole series of event, given that it is TWG.

Makes buying tea seem like you&#39;re purchasing fine wine! Loved the teas that the staff took time to share (sniff test), sans pretentiousness. The tea I tried was delicious! Enjoyed their macarons as well. Would recommend stopping by for a spot of superb tea (at at least 11$ per person depending the tea you order, it better be) and a civilized discussion with friends. They&#39;ve at least one restaurant and one store. It ain&#39;t cheap, but it&#39;s worth it.

What a classy tea shop,  great tea selection, not inexpensive but worth every penny.  Their macaroons are to die for, so many delish flavors and they always look so good displayed in their window.  Service is always courteous and friendly.

I fell in love with their teas on my visit to Singapore. This cafe/ restaurant is nice too - smack in the middle of the mall on top of a bridge.<br><br>Space is limited and may involve a wait.<br><br>Food and tea options get pricey real quick, but worth the experience for the teas!

Every Twg Tea spot is immaculate and well designed with servers creating a tea experience to remember. <br><br>Quiet and modern, you can choose from the BIGGEST TEA LIST I have ever seen with tea from all over the world. This really excites me and I know it sounds nerdy but tea is super relaxing and delicious.<br><br>This tea salon is anything but boring, you can get tea mixed with alcohol, light snacks and all sorts of tea ice-creams. <br><br>Next time you are in Singapore, make sure you visit a Tea Salon.

text: Sitting right smack in the middle of a bridge, the TWG outlet at Marina Bay Sands is definitely a sight to behold. <br>However, it is severely lacking in space and you&#39;ll find yourself sandwiched between different groups of diners most of the time. Expect bumps to happen whenever people move around, which may not be the most comfortable of dining experiences to be had, considering the setting and all. <br>Overall, I&#39;d have to say that the service is brisk and polite, but the lack of space is a severe flaw in the overall planning. They have to expand or people will just get sick of paying them a visit!

text: holds special place among my Singapore memories not for the food, but for the person I was visiting with. salmon avocado sandwich was alright, macarons were standard fare. We got it to go for the light/water show but missed it anyways. tbh salad was a bit pointless..

TWG is really one of those places that you see and the last thing you would think about it is that it is a Singapore Company. I love the atmosphere here, it feels fancy and service is great. However should you find yourself wanting to try what they have to offer you do need quote a bit of patience as service is rather slow from waiting in line to the serving of the food. Food is good however the menu is a little messy whereby I had to ask the waiters questions about the things I&#39;m about to order. Taste wise is above average but price wise it&#39;s more on the pricey side.

text: 5 star for the beautiful indoor decoration.<br>4 star for the infuse tea. <br>1 star for the service. <br><br>After I tasted their tea during afternoon high-tea at The landing point, I wanted to bring some of their tea back to US. <br>The store is beautifully decorated with a whole wall of large tea cans. There are designed tea cans from small to big. <br>The infused tea were similar to Tea-forte, the tea spot and Teavana. <br>The salesman has this snobby facial expression on his face all the time.<br>Why is he so arrogant about selling tea leaves?  <br>After I purchased a few of their infused tea and macarons, the female cashier looks very annoyed when I tried to take a picture of the store<br>&#34; No pictures&#34;. She waved her hand right in front of my camera lens. <br>And the guy who just sold us the tea pretended it wasn&#39;t his business. Cuz his job was done, right after we paid him.  <br>Wow, Really? I assumed this is not a fashion store, it&#39;s just a tea store. What&#39;s so secretive about the store that I can&#39;t take picture with it? <br>If there is a no-photograph policy, you should just mention it in a polite way instead of being a bitch. <br>This TWG is trying to be an upscale store,but unfortunately the people who work for them are discourteous.
They should just stick to selling tea.. Everything is either overly sweet or salty. Get your tastebuds checked if you think otherwise.

text: Tried all 3 fish I.e salmon, sea bass and cod.   All done well.  Tried the imperial rose and lemon bush tea and they all turn up well.  We also got the chocolate fudge as well as the apple tartan. Both were equally tasty and well executed.  Wifey had the imperial rose but I thought my lemon bush tea came out ahead perhaps because I like rioobos tea to start with.  Service is good despite being a busy lunch time.

No doubt a unique, fun location situated right in the intersection of 2 halls, on a raised platform while shoppers walk with envy....sort of.  Guess it&#39;s not your traditional British-style high tea in a hotel setting like the fabulous one back home at the Fairmont in DT but to us, was just a touristy thing to do.<br><br>Will give props to the overall marketing of their tin cans, easily recognizable.<br><br>Scones were a bit dry, and the sandwiches were OK.<br><br>Of the 3 macarons i added to the set menu, probably the caramel was the best but nothing like back at home.  Not as chewy or sweet haha.<br><br>Will say that service was impeccable, as a few different servers served us, and acted quite professional more than friendly, if that makes any sense.

text: The place is just beautiful so its nice to sit and just enjoy your tea.  The cutlery and plates are just so pretty!<br>When you go to this place, make sure you are not rushing.  Their tea menu is so extensive, that it will take you at least 15mins to select one.  The tea was great with the subtle flavors.<br>The let down was the dessert --- it looked very pretty but the flavors were not there -- felt like it was not good chocolate.  It was just sweet...<br>I went for afternoon tea so did not try any of the dishes.
Good rating, mainly atmosphere, nice view,  just had wine and olives/apps.  Very attentive staff,  nice stop over after s stroll throughout the gardens

I ended off my visiting friends&#39; short stay in Singapore with a posh afternoon hi-tea experience. <br><br>So some basic information about the place. TWG is a tea boutique franchise based in Singapore, set up by a Singaporean and French pair of friends who met in Morocco. They aim to transform the tea experience - which I understood to mean poshing it up many levels higher to trump the usual coffee&amp;tea places. I like that idea as afternoon hi-teas are supposed to be posh, posh.<br><br>Ambience: I have visited the TWG tea parlour branch at Ion Orchard. I prefer the branch at MBS as it is more spacious and enjoys more natural light. This is a fancy tea place - but somehow some patrons dine in shorts and tee-shirts. So please dress up nicely. Expect proper napkins, cutlery and fancy tea sets!<br><br>Service: Impeccable - tonnes of servers milling about making sure that you are well-taken care of!<br><br>Tea: Such a huge selection of tea flavours to choose from. Apparently, their white teas are quite popular. But they cost approx $26/pot. The more ordinary teas such as Holiday in Paris (I loved it) and Earl Grey are approx $13/pot. Quite pricey for tea ... and when I was at the Ion Orchard branch, they did not refill my tea pot with hot water though my girlfriend said they did so at the Taka branch for her. I ordered a tea milk shake when I was at MBS (the Asian tea flavour) - which was so satisfying - wasn&#39;t too thick nor too sweet - and you could sense good tea in there with all that milk and sugar!<br><br>Food: or rather, confectionary. I&#39;m a huge huge macaroon fan. The macaroon flavours here are all tea-inspired! I tried quite a few flavours that day ... I can&#39;t tell you my favourite as I need to try more of them to decide. Don&#39;t expect Laduree/Piere Herme sort of premium macaroons ... but these macaroons are still decent macaroons, good enough for a posh afternoon hi-tea experience. and we had the creme brûlée tart as well - it was rather underwhelming :( And I heard the savoury options aren&#39;t too impressive either.<br><br>If you want to posh it out slightly in MBS (as a tourist or local), I would definitely recommend coming here. But don&#39;t expect much of the food.

This is just one of the two TWG outlets at the Shoppes and is situated right above a man-made river running through the mall where gondolas glide across the waters. <br>As with all its outlets, the table settings and decor exude a sense of luxury and class. My friends and I swung by from their ION outlet which closes rather early at 9:30 daily. <br><br>To say they have an extensive collection is putting it mildly. Their menu is choke full of choices and amusing names, especially the tea blends. <br><br>Be sure to ask for the tea book if you want more details about a specific tea. <br><br>I ordered a pot of Silver Moon tea, a green tea blend which was meant to be shared by two. I was told I could pour about 3 cups from the pot. It turns out that the fancy tea pot with an insulator only poured out two cups worth of tea leaving us disappointed but we did fill out cups up pretty well so I gave them the benefit of the doubt. <br><br>What you&#39;re really paying for is the location and the ambience. I&#39;d definitely bring a date here to round off the evening with a good cup of tea.

text: tea service is pricy.. but the desserts are pretty good.. it&#39;s pretty popular so we had to wait to get seated.. <br><br>it&#39;s a great place to sit and just people watch and relax inside a mall<br><br>the store also has plenty of teas and you can buy them in individual wrapped bags for a quarter of the price than in their TWG canisters.. we bought 4 different teas back to the u.s. and bought some canisters of amazon..

text: I had the tea set with scones, macarroons and a choice of tea, and subsequently ordered an extra pot of tea (total cost was $40). The tea selection here is Extensive - I capitalize the E for the added effect. Request for the tea manual - where each tea is explained in much detail. A tea connoisseur will probably spend hours sipping tea here from the finely designed tea cups and plates. The setting here is lovely too, as it is located right in the middle of the bustling MBS shoppes.
Mediocre food and overpriced. Unless you are really into tea or like paying for ambiance, steer clear.

text: Visited TWG this week for the first time and also the last time. Expected a good experience to celebrate a certain milestone with my friend, instead I was leaving highly dissapointed and pissed.<br><br>The good thing - location, food was OK too (little portion, but I guess that&#39;s fine for these restaurants). Dessert was exceptional.<br><br>Epic fail - service. <br>1 - we arrived and got seated. Had to wait around 5 minutes to get the menu. It should be noted that the restaurant was half-empty with only few tables occupied and there were around 4-5 people on the service. Our impatient looks were ignored. Some of the people who arrived LATER got their menu instantly. Why?<br>2 - I ordered Ice tea with a special request for only 1-2 ice cubes. The waiter seemed to understand but brought tea full of ice.<br>3 - after finishing the main dish, we were supposed to get a dessert. It wasn&#39;t coming for a while. After my enquiry (again, we had to wait some time before somebody noticed), the waiter who got the question talked to his colleague who gave a &#34;WTF does this guy want?&#34; look. And then one more time. When I finally got the dessert from the &#34;looky&#34; guy, he didn&#39;t say a word (which reminds me that none of the dishes actually got any introduction or a nice word).<br>4 - the biggest problem is the inconsistency in the service. Some of the tables got almost constant attention from some of the staff, while we were being ignored for most of the time. Why? It made us feel like we&#39;re something less.<br><br>It&#39;s a shame that this food doesn&#39;t have a corresponding level of service. Never ever.

text: Singaporeans are a crazy crazy bunch of food lovers. When one stall is set up and gets extremely good reviews, that stall better be prepared to handle large crowds. Donut fever hit Singapore more than 2 years ago and while it has cooled down significantly, Singaporeans still love a new novelty donut stall now and then.<br><br>Sapporo petit donut, as its name implies, sells small donuts. Very small sized in my opinion. But the method of making it reminds me of the Japanese Taiyaki, fished shaped waffles with filling. Seems like a good fusion of western donut and Japanese style confectionery. <br><br>It comes in a few flavors at 8 mini donuts at $4.80. I picked red bean, chocolate and custard flavors in my selection of 8. Popping them into my mouth, I felt that they were really normal donuts and the fillings were really not that special. Normal chocolate flavor, normal custard-like texture, normal red bean sweetness. <br><br>Overall, it&#39;s a pretty ok snack if you&#39;re feeling slightly rich. Don&#39;t expect it to fill your stomach though, even 8 donuts seemed abit too little.

One of those with good roast duck! I have been here a few time becos we love the duck. <br><br>The sauce is pretty sweet and it&#39;s easy for lot of people to like it. When the duck slices are dipped in that chilli, it is very appetizing, and goes very well with rice.<br><br>They have soups too. Some of the soups sell out fast, and those remaining is usually slightly plain. <br><br>The char siew is lean and nice, lots of people likes it too. If they are slightly fattier, it would be heavenly.

text: Rong Liang Restaurant Pte Ltd has the word &#34;restaurant&#34; in its name but it&#39;s really a coffee shop. A stone&#39;s throw away from the more visible hawker centre along the main road in West Coast, it is frequented by people who are regular customers or heard of it through word of mouth. It is usually crowded but the turnaround is fast. This is a paradise for people who love roasted meat. We went in a group and ordered roasted pork, char siew and roasted duck for sharing. I would say this is an all-round place because there is a variety of appetizing soup and the vegetables are nicely cooked. Even my friend who is not into vegetables kept taking more helpings of the stir fried kai lan. If you are in the area, definitely drop by!

text: I ordered the roasted duck noodle for $3. The roasted duck meat was thinly sliced while the skin was quite crispy. The meat was very delicious especially with the sauce. However the noodle was cooked a bit soft and tasted soggy. Else I would have given 5 stars to them. For this price, one cannot expect too much anyway.

text: It looks like one of the popular local resturants in that area. The price is reasonable, but I think the rice and the pork are dry. Maybe that is the reason why they always ask you what to drink... Btw, the soup there is good.

I&#39;d say these guys are roast meat specialists. The meats are really tasty and they all have that signature smoky roast flavour. YUM. I had the boneless duck meat rice and it came sliced pretty thinly, but so very very tender. <br><br>They also sell a variety of soups. If i&#39;m not wrong, about 10 or so different choices of soups which apparently are very good and value for money. I havent tried them for myself but my friend who was with me concluded that the meal was very much worth it.<br><br>But based on the meat alone, I&#39;d say the same thing too!

text: This place serves roast duck and char siew which is to die for. I would rate it just a notch below the high-end cantonese cuisine restaurants at a fraction of the price. The soup here is also a must-try. Definitely my first choice for duck char siew rice when I am on the go.

text: Jeremy H is right, this joint has been around a very long time. In fact I can remember when there was a very small car park out front where you could safely leave your car curbside forever without risking a ticket, which made this a great pit stop and place to just chill out.  It also made it accessible.  These days there&#39;s absolutely no need to risk a run in with the LTA since the Holland MRT exit is right on the doorstep of this grand old lady of a &#39;bucks. <br><br>The store has also recently been made over with a nice brightly-lit minimalist interior.  I have mixed feelings about the change from the cosy, slightly dingy and definitely kitschy, stuffed couch dimly lit HV &#39;bucks of yesteryear.  It always made me feel like I was hanging out at a cooky aunt&#39;s parlor. This looks like a proper coffee shop now. I&#39;m sure unencumbered by nostalgia, any visitor to Starbucks at Holland Village will feel welcome and be impressed by the shiny clean interior. <br><br>I still love coming here and you could do a lot worse than giving them some of your time and money to luxuriate in clean minimalist comfort whilst you plot your next Yelp check-in.

text: Today is Aug 8, eve of National Holiday.  The online schedule for this Holland Village store indicates 24hrs on eve of a major holiday and yet when I was there at 6am, the store is pitch dark.  There&#39;s no signage whatsoever on the store front.  In addition<br>from my google search the phone number listed for this store is a Fax number.  Very inefficient and bad fir business.  When I dial the store number listed on YELP, I received a message saying this number you dialed is not on service.  Food for thought.

This Starbucks has been around for ages and when I say ages, I mean I&#39;ve been coming here since I was a geeky student in secondary school some 13-14 years ago! Holland Village has been a favorite haunt for my friends as our school at Dover Road was a short bus ride away. The second floor of Starbucks quickly became our study spot while preparing for our O Levels. It is actually hard to get a seat on the second floor - much more comfortable compared to the first floor with sofas and all. But the downside is the alfresco seating area is where smokers smoke so you get the occasional whiff of second hand smoke as well.<br><br>Back in the day we would arrive early in the morning, grab a venti-sized coffee and plonk ourselves down on a prized seat, study and do endless 10-year series questions, grab lunch from Cold Storage and sneak it in to Starbucks. Maybe another venti-sized coffee after lunch. Fun times!

text: The Starbucks in Holland Village is a two story outlet. This Starbucks is always filled with a lot of students and people studying. Expect the regular Starbucks drinks and food menu here. <br><br>Staff is really friendly here. Im always greeted with a smile and a little bit of conversation. It gets a bit crowded here on the weekends but weekday nights are usually pretty quiet. Don&#39;t sit upstairs though, it can get pretty messy and dirty with people hanging out for hours.

text: This is a new cafe that opened near my home and we ordered:<br>Basil Chicken Rice with Egg - they have a spicy and non-spicy version and we opted for a non-spicy as my girl is not sure if she can handle the spice level here. She loved it! I had a mouthful and it&#39;s actually pretty good. Good flavours without being overly salty. <br><br>Tom Yum Soup with Tanghoon - I&#39;m happy that its not the instant Tom Yum sauce version. The soup is slightly creamy and tasty. The ingredients is about 3 slices of fish and 3 medium sized prawns. I will order this again. <br><br>Chicken Chop Rice Set - my girl insisted that I try her Rice and chicken Chop although I told her, deep-fried chicken Chop taste the same anywhere. Which it was, it&#39;s ok nice. <br><br>We&#39;ll come back for the Basil Chicken and Tom Yum for sure!

i&#39;m giving this place 4 stars because i love the cakes that was formerly at b1 (tampopo deli). but i docked 1 star because the food they serve is pretty crappy. <br>the soup was too oily, the pasta was too salty...though the quality of the pasta itself was good, just the sauce was a bit much. <br><br>if you&#39;re new to this place, try the scoop cake, puddings, or cream puff.

text: We stopped by here to try some cakes! We noticed that there was a deal of $12 for three slices of cake. The cakes ended up being Okay - I probably wouldn&#39;t pay more than $4 for a slice. I think even that is pretty pricey for the kind of cake they have. I only liked the signature fruit cake.<br>The other cakes were a bit dry and not sweet enough (maybe I&#39;m used to eating overly sweet American cakes).

text: Greeting you at the entrance of the cafe are the two cake displays filled with tall chiffon cakes.<br><br>They disappear quickly but they are also replenished pretty quickly. Their best sellers are the matcha chiffon cake and the matcha roll.<br>It is a NETT priced cafe, but it is also self service. So whilst you order and pay for your food at the cashier, get a friend to head inside the long cafe, to find seats.<br><br>1. Matcha Chiffon Cake $7<br>I&#39;ll be honest, for a chiffon cake, $7 is really pricey. The chiffon cake itself is very light, however the butter cream all over the cake, tasted very cheesey. The cheesey taste was unexpected and I am not sure if everyone would like it. It was more like a cheesecake + matcha chiffon cake. <br><br>2. Chocolate Chiffon Cake $7<br>The chocolate chiffon cake was more enjoyable than the Matcha Chiffon Cake, the chocolate cream was so delightable, I devoured it in no time.<br><br>Would I come back here for more of these $7 chiffon cakes? No, why? Because they&#39;re $7! But it was an interesting experience. I may come back to try the matcha roll though.

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/lqvOIm2z7r_qc3tcQKavGg/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/dulcet-and-studio-singapore?reviewid=Ep4dmymw76x72dSF-3KZbw&select=lqvOIm2z7r_qc3tcQKavGg', 'altText': 'Photo of Dulcet & Studio - Singapore, Singapore', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': None}]
text: I don&#39;t recommend the coffee.<br>I have no opinion on the food, but it doesn&#39;t look particularly amazing.<br><br>In short? Order anything with cream.<br>Those cream puffs are like little pockets of magic, stuffed to the brim with tasty, light, fluffy dreams. Don&#39;t bite into one because you&#39;ll find yourself a little messy. Instead, be deliberate, calm, patient.<br><br>Break open the puff, separate it. Don&#39;t spill the filling. Put down one half, and then slowly bite into the other. Savour the texture of the puff, then let yourself be carried along by the silky lusciousness of that cream filling. Taste it. Luxuriate. Swallow.<br><br>Repeat. Blush because you realise you&#39;re making embarrassing noises while you wallow in this little morsel of sin. Continue eating anyway.<br><br>When you&#39;re done licking your lips, and your fingers, and wishing you&#39;d bought one more...<br><br>BUY ONE MORE. And do it all over again.<br><br>Side note: the strawberry shortcake and blueberry cheese tart are both also delicious. I like the blueberry more than the shortcake, I find that Canele&#39;s shortcake is still better, but man.<br><br>Have I mentioned the cream puff?

text: Best matcha Swiss roll I have ever eaten! The density of the roll is just nice and the richness of the cream is heavenly. The best part is that the roll is much cheaper than the other items, albeit the overall prices are not cheap. The cheese cake and matcha cake are also great. The cream and strawberries are fresh. I don&#39;t think you can go wrong with any of the desserts here. :)

text: Been here two times already! Both visits for desserts :)<br>I really love the pudding here. My favourite ones are the milk pudding (which comes with caramel sauce) and coffee pudding (comes with creamer). Not something you can easily find, and it&#39;s really smooth and wobbly. I was a little disappointed with the cake though. Tried the special called &#39;Rose Chiffon&#39;, the colour was nice, had a cream cheese frosting, but it tasted a tad too normal. And of course, the slice of chiffon cake cost a tad too much. <br><br>Anyway my friend ate a main course on the second visit and said it was bad. The pork was too dry! I guess I&#39;ll still stick to my desserts.

text: This is a relatively new set up lifestyle cafe by the folks @ Tampopo.  <br><br>Most of the hot favorite desserts like creme puff, different flavored milk pudding and cheesecakes @ the Tampopo restaurants can be found here.  They don&#39;t sell just desserts here, they do sell western/japanese food for lunch and dinner. The other of my all time favorite is their handmade warabi mochi. It is done just nice with the right amount of sweetness. It is soft yet chewy.<br><br>We loved the milk pudding so much that we often have it takeaway and slowly enjoy it at home.

Those cream puffs? More like cream bombs! Every bite squishes cream right out, and thank goodness it&#39;s bloody delicious cream, otherwise I&#39;d be a right idiot licking my fingers with every bite.<br><br>I&#39;m also a fan of the fruit roll, which is really a cake roll with fruit in it, but I&#39;m not complaining. Soft, pillowy sponge, with fruit and cream in between - if I wasn&#39;t watching my waistline (goodbye metabolism, le sigh), they&#39;d be a once-a-week staple. Thankfully my wallet is in agreement with the waistline, so I don&#39;t go by too often.<br><br>Then again there&#39;s lots more to ogle after - I hear the milk puddings are rather yum too.

text: Japanese Lifestyle Café, a Little Piece of Heaven <br><br>While Liang Court has long lost its former edge of glory over the years, it still remains as the representative Japanese mall with tenants Meidi-ya, Kinokuniya, Marutama, Saizeriya Ristorante and Tampopo holding the business together (anybody remembers Daimaru?). There is another reason to pay them a visit - Dulcet &amp; Studio.<br><br>Dulcet &amp; Studio is a whole new lifestyle café, with a contemporary yet cosy vibes - think Muji in a restaurant form. The name &#39;Dulcet&#39; means sweet to the taste, while &#39;Studio&#39; is the other part of the café where customers can sign up for cooking classes. <br><br>Expect a mixture of Western meets Japanese cuisine including specialty pasta, lamb rice, beef spare rib stew, fish &amp; chip. Lunch and dinner sets are served at a very reasonable price of below $15 and $20 respectively.<br><br>I much preferred the Black Pig Bolognese Fettuccine Pasta ($12.80) which reminds me of tomato based bak chor mee pok. The meat sauce is salty-sweet, and ladies would appreciate this as it does not leave you overwhelmed or over-full for lunch.

text: Very friendly service. Delicious desserts and tea. Great for dine in or take away.

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/cKIXRWpbU0A9dMmzykdWOw/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/dr-cafe-coffee-singapore?reviewid=LT5xaklBslbcgg2IfTD9xg&select=cKIXRWpbU0A9dMmzykdWOw', 'altText': 'Photo of Dr Cafe Coffee - Singapore, Singapore', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': ''}]
text: Located at the entrance of I12 Katong, it is hard to miss Dr. CAFE. It has an interior that looks exactly like Starbucks, with wooden furniture and a glass display counter, one would think it is a café that is trying to mimic Starbucks. <br><br>They serve coffee in the 3 usual sizes - tall, grande and venti. I got myself a Grande Latte, and the coffee was surprisingly good. The latte was creamy and had a slight aroma of the coffee beans. I doubt it would be aromatic enough for those who prefer their coffee strong though. Their coffee is also priced slightly cheaper than that at Starbucks. <br><br>Out of all the cakes and pastries displayed, I got the Chocolate Doughnut to satiate my sweet tooth. The chocolate was really rich, and tasted so good when paired with the coffee. Overall, it is a cozy café to spend a lazy Sunday in.

Visited this cafe for the first time under the impression that I&#39;d be able to get a bit of work done, spending an afternoon in a nice cafe. But no, that didn&#39;t happen.<br><br>I ordered a caramel frap with an extra shot. Barista didn&#39;t seem too sure about my order which just goes to show how the staff lack training ie cannot possibly be helpful to customers with their lack of product knowledge. But hey, it may be his first day, so I&#39;ll forgive that. Also got myself a cheddar cheese and omelette sandwich that wasn&#39;t too great, but wasn&#39;t inedible either.<br><br>While ordering my drink, I asked if there&#39;s wifi available and said barista says yes. However, when I later asked for the password, his colleague butts in rudely claiming the wifi&#39;s spoilt. I suppose it is possible, but when I checked my laptop, the connection seemed fine. It&#39;s just password protected.<br><br>Now, if they don&#39;t allow patrons to use their wifi in the first place, it&#39;s frustrating but understandable. Maybe they don&#39;t wish to have people spending hours in the cafe buying just one drink. But to say yes, there&#39;s wifi you can use and then to have another staff, rudely I shall emphasize, claim the wifi&#39;s spoilt isn&#39;t acceptable. Perhaps my laptop&#39;s lying to me and it REALLY is spoilt? There&#39;s no harm in explaining it nicely, is there? Or in the first place, state how it&#39;s not for public use. <br><br>The food and drinks available seem decent. But nope, crappy service simply means I&#39;m never patronizing the place again.

Cake from Tuxedo.', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Cake from Tuxedo.'}]
text: You can find Tuxedo right at the lobby of Carlton Hotel!  I got a cake from them for my birthday and as a lover of desserts, I was completely blown away by the taste of the cake. Decorated with panels of white chocolate and the cake which is dark chocolate with praline wafers cream as centers of the cake, it was delicious. I love the way the praline cream complimented the dark chocolate. The wafer bits in the cream added a crunchy texture of what would have been a seemingly normal chocolate cake. I daresay I&#39;ll be a very happy girl if I keep receiving their cake for my birthday every year from now on!

text: We were guests at the Carlton Hotel which made the Tuxedo Cafe a convenient place for a light breakfast. They have a breakfast special, but that only includes more plain pastry items. In addition to their savory items in the main display by the cash register, there are a number of other pastries against the wall of windows adjacent to the cash register. <br><br>The prices are on the high side (which is to be expected for a hotel cafe).

text: Are you addicted to sugar? Yes &amp; No? Who doesn&#39;t commit a moment of guilty pleasure - confession time has arrived! I am a sucker for anything enchanting - even if it doesn&#39;t taste wonderful, it has to be angelic - to surmount a pixie like me. Equally enticed by the greatest assassin - carbs - forever so domineering no matter how hard I plea for the stoppage of indulgence, it just never worked. Carbohydrates, both a comrade and foe depending on which school of thought you lean towards. I chose to make believe that they are my allies  - my energy source - of which my internal mechanics are good at catabolising. But scientists and experts believe that sugar is addictive while I hope I am not doing more harm to myself, SUGAR be it in complex or simpler form, makes life SWEETER!!<br><br>Today, you needn&#39;t dress solemn or act provincial to eat with great relish even though the place sounds poise - Tuxedo. No one was seen wearing the outfit here, only quirky Tux apron by the wait staffs. Cute. The dining room sits 30-odd without absolute count, classic black outline the entire space with bespoke Tux bow-tie endorsed the back of the acrylic chairs, menu and a stack of single-fold Tuxedo hankies as paper napkins. A place not intimidated by its name but a casual with lighthearted element.<br><br>Level 1, is where one enters through Carlton hotel main lobby. The newly refurbished Premier Wing - an extension to the existing structure, makes the compound brighter and classy. Walk right up to the far end and that&#39;s where Tuxedo stood, on your 9 o&#39;clock with Café Mosaic (serves Asian/Western-style buffet) at 12 o&#39;clock (restrooms tuck in between the 2). I walked into Tuxedo and was met with a smiling male wait staff. Here, you find your own seats without having shown. Effortlessly I found mine, only 2-3 tables were occupied at 12.30pm, a weekday.<br><br>A quick munch, I opted for a set lunch. No complicated items listed, the menu is a brief one with 4 types of sandwiches, 7 kind of pastries, some selections of tea and coffee. If that is not enough to fill you, walk to the counter for a merciless sweet-coma. Freshly baked Seafood Pies with Lobster Pie being the day&#39;s special, Chicken Curry Puffs, Bacon or Mushroom Quiches and then the Sweet indulgence section with Chocolate Raspberry Cake (milk version), Granny Smith Apple Dome, Strawberry Cheesecakes etc. Of course, I am having its Signature - Tuxedo Cake today.<br><br>The soup-of-the-day arrived shortly. It was Potato Leaf and Sausage in the making. Not overly creamy, I liked its light mouth-feel with a subtle scent emitting from the spuds while I can&#39;t figured if the greenish hues were part of its leaves, I still couldn&#39;t believe my ears - made of Potato leaf?? White sausage morsels add bites to the velvety creme base, a nice touch. Something not commonly tried and so I was impressed right from the start.<br><br>Then came the sandwich with Roast Beef stuffed in between 2 slices of Sourdough which has a mildly sour taste. Comparing the level of potency to that of Maison Kayser&#39;s, only 50% was met. So, if you adore a lighter version, this one is for you. Lightly toasted with crusty edges, the texture in the middle remained soft. Though I lamented the fact that the beef was tad dry-leathery and bland, the brie and seeded mustard add flavours to the composite.<br><br>Feeling less satisfied, I marched to the counter to ask for a Plain Croissant! Indeed, the saving grace! Holy Grail! Some days I liked it buttery, but today, I liked it milder. I see thin airy layers as I tear them apart, flaky crumbs were scattering all around (less crisp than the ones at Tiong Bahru Bakery and not as overwhelmingly buttery), causing some mess when I try playdough-ing the structure. Seriously, I have nothing to complain about this croissant. If you like something fanciful, they also have Almonds and Chocolate variants.<br><br>A-MUST-try now: Tuxedo Cake, its Signature. The dark chocolate lends a strong flavour, making the overall a moist and potent sponge. Never a dull bitter, thanks to the white chocolate ganache encircling its exterior. If you are expecting a feathery texture, STOP! This is not meant to be a chiffon, hence no way it could met your ideal. For a sweet-toothed, go for the Chocolate Raspberry Cake which is made from  milk chocolate, a sweeter form.<br><br>Like myself, if you are struck by a carb spell between 11:00 am to 3:00pm and needed to debug badly, head to Tuxedo for their daily lunch special. Set Lunch is made available where you get your carb fixed with a delectable sandwich - choose between: Baguette with Roma Tomatoes, Baguette with Tuna, Focaccia with Ham &amp; Cheese or like myself, a Sourdough with Roast Beef. That&#39;s not all, it comes with a choice of either a soup or salad and end with an option of either coffee or tea. The episode goes for S$15.80++. It doesn&#39;t sound like a shoestring meal I know but the freshly baked breads are worth the trip.

text: I love this place for the cool, airy, breezy vibe it gives me. It&#39;s not just me but my friends have also commented that this place has a general uplifting and positive vibe.<br><br>Dined here on one occasion 2 years back with my aunt and my impression of the place was excellent.<br><br>Dropped by again 2 weeks ago for a coffee break and had one of their Chocolate Cakes - it was Heaven.<br><br>Recommended place to chill-out and watch the world go by although there might be many students hogging tables on weekends to study for hours!

text: If you want great American diner food at a reasonable price in Singapore, then this is where you come. Sandwiches, cakes, and more. I had the chocolate brownie cheesecake for the first time today and I&#39;m bringing friends the next time! The seating area is al fresco and not fanciful but the food is delightfully affordable, unpretentious and comforting. Perfect for lunch and tea-time!

text: I&#39;m not a fan of Hanis in the least. The prices are fairly cheap, but the &#34;Western&#34; food they propose has never appealed to me, and I&#39;d much rather have a meal at the nearby Bras Basah coffee shop. <br><br>A regular patron of the National Library, I have found myself desperate enough on several occasions to grab a quick bite at Hanis before going back in to continue with research. The coffee is pretty good and very cheap, so that&#39;s quite a draw, but the quick bites that you can just grab and go are pitiful. I&#39;ve tried their tuna sandwich, and I&#39;m certain I could make something better at home. <br><br>I have certainly learnt my lesson after those first couple of experiences, and now avoid Hanis as far as possible.

Hanis Carbonara with chicken chunks', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Hanis Carbonara with chicken chunks'}]
text: I love their all day set meals. I always opt for their dory fish set. It costs $9.80, comes with a dessert (usually a fruit), a choice between orange juice or ice lemon tea and a bowl of soup of the day. <br><br>I have tried their avocado shake before and it&#39;s thick, not at all watery and has the right consistency. Their earl grey latte though.. was quite a let down..it was too watery and quite... bland. I tried that twice and each time, I regretted my choice. You can try their pasta as well, it&#39;s quite good, especially their carbonara! I quite like their chicken carbonara and their sausage pasta. It&#39;s quite generous the amount. It&#39;s a great place to go to if you are on a budget ($10-$15) .. though I feel that the cakes are worth a miss.

My friend and I didn&#39;t want be late for a show at Drama Box, so we had an early dinner at the cafe. We got the sets; they included a main dish, a drink, half a slice honeydew, soup of the day and a paperthin slice of garlic bread.<br><br>My prawn aglio oglio was mouth-watering - the pasta was springy, I got 5 medium-sized prawns and fresh bell peppers. My buddy&#39;s Chicken Superburger was just as tasty. She topped up a few cents for a foccacia bun. Her order arrived with potato wedges and fresh garden vegetables. The sliced cakes looked tempting but a little pricey as compared to those from Polar Puffs. We were still famished and got the flaky curry puffs before going into the theater.<br><br>What I love about Hanis Cafe &amp; Bakery is that prices are reasonable for the portions they serve. No GST and service charge is another draw.

text: To get Halal bakery joints in Singapore can be quite challenging and I am glad I found Hanis. Hanis is conveniently located at the National Library. A good place to read a book and enjoy a cup of coffee. And maybe a slice of cake too. The scones is a must try. It&#39;s really good and moist.<br><br>Hanis serves all day set meal and my favourite is Black Pepper Chicken Chop. At just $11.80, you get the main course, soup, a hot or cold drink and a dessert to seal the meal. A good deal I must say! The Black Pepper Chicken Chop is cooked to perfection with some charred areas which really is my favourite part of it. <br><br>If you don&#39;t have the time to sit for a meal, get their Cafe Mocha which uses the aromatic Illy coffee and the Chicken Ham sandwich.

text: Came here last night for a late night snack before bed.  This is a very clean and streamlined establishment tucked in the corner of the concorde hotel.  The lights pop but at the same time is dark and warm.  They have a buffet option (seafood buffet was 60 singaporean dollar) or an al a cart menu.  We opted with their hawaian pizza and the seafood spaghetti.  I also ordered a singaporean slonger cocktail.<br>The cocktail came out fast and it tasted great.  Not the overreaching taste of alcohol, but you definitely felt it!!  It was cold and refreshing and it looked good too.<br>The pizza and pasta cam out in about 15-20 min at the same time.  Pizza is about 8 or 10 inches wide.  The crust was crunchy but the cheese was melting, and it was soft.  Quality ingredients were used, you can tell.<br>And the spaghetti was good too.  Lots of pieces of salmon, oyster, clam, and shrimp.  Pasta wasent mushy or too aldente, it was just right.   They give you for both a good amount of parmesean on the side.  I did wish the pasta had more flavor, i had to use a good amount of cheese, salt and pepper to elevate it.<br>Overall the food was good.  For the price we got a good amoint of food.  Staff was friendly and on top of their game.  And the drink was delicious.  Will like to be back for their lunch buffet sunday

text: Now this is one seafood buffet that lives up to its name - The Harvest of the Sea buffet dinner at Concorde Hotel&#39;s casual Spices Café is for diehard lovers of all things oceanic. <br><br>There&#39;s a great assortment of western and local delights, including Prince Edward&#39;s seafood chowder, lobster bisque with prawn quenelles and drunken prawns with Chinese herbs.  Don&#39;t miss their coconut-scented seafood rice au gratin, corn-crusted salmon with thyme-infused garlic oil and filet of snapper with yellow bean paste and leeks.<br><br>Crab lovers, will be delighted to know that they can prepare your crab on the spot in six different ways so you get to enjoy the maximum freshness.

text: Came here for the Peranakan/Nonya lunch buffet. It completely exceeded my expectations.<br><br>On a given day, they either have laksa or mee siam, and either ice kachang or chendol (make your own)<br>The day I went, it was laksa and chendol. I&#39;d just had chendol the day before, so I skipped that.<br><br>Shiok:<br>- The highlight was definitely the LAKSA. Of a table of 5, four of us were eating laksa at the end, after trying everything we wanted to try. Without hesitation I will say it was better than the Katong laksa. Deliciously lemak, but not overwhelmingly rich.<br>- Chili crab. Difficult to eat, but all part of the experience.<br>- Nonya kuehs. Such a wide selection!<br>- Square ice cream on a stick! Durian flavour! (also had red bean, cempedak, and one other I don&#39;t recall)<br>- Satay is hard to do wrong. They had the standard peanut sauce, and also a pineapple sauce.<br><br>Ok, but have had better:<br>- Popiah<br>- Chap chye<br>- Otak<br>- Chok (porridge)<br><br>There was a lot more that I didn&#39;t even get around to trying.<br><br>Service was very friendly, and we were offered bibs to save our clothing from the laksa. Some of the buffet staff didn&#39;t speak English that well, though (probably PRC).<br><br>Then outside there was a table where a woman was selling kebayas and some Peranakan spoons, where of course I bought some things for myself and for gifts.

text: At Concorde hotel, free buffet breakfast included with the room. I wish they would change up the selections but for three days I practically had the same breakfast. However, one day they did throw in tater tots instead of mashed potatoes. I couldn&#39;t complain since it was free and it was decent. Staff was friendly, always happily greeted and acknowledged.

Great place for lunch and nice enough that you can take a client .<br><br>We had the burrata salad and croquettes which were both very nice.  Followed by a good cup of coffee.  <br><br>The place is small with an open kitchen and modern feel.  <br><br>Great place.  Will be back.

I work at Asia Square and knowing that this place opened with SG$2.- promotion, I had to go and try it out. The $2 promo is for a blended cup which is almost equivalent to TALL or maybe even SHORT at Starbucks (= a bit too small for me).<br><br>The staff was very nice when I asked about the $2 promotion as their menu looked like I was able to choose from 4 different coffee bean types (which turned out that it was a BLEND of these four types.).<br><br>They also have a $10 breakfast lasting until I think 3pm. Being a pancake lover, I went to try the $10 breakfast (for lunch) and found it a bit disappointing.... it was more like crepe and the portions were so small... no stacks. Just one pancake cut into fancy triangle pieces with powdered sugar and cut-strawberry pieces on top. Meh.<br><br>I think I will go explore other pancake shops... and after the $2 promo (until end of Dec 2013) I probably won&#39;t be back.

text: New coffee shop in Asia Square and a much needed addition as I can&#39;t say Jewel, OTC, or Starbucks really float my boat. Service is extremely friendly and the owners go out of their way to have a conversation about the coffee. Named after the &#34;optimal temperature&#34; of coffee (according to??) but I would beg to differ given I prefer my coffee piping hot. Currently have an introductory offer for $2 lattes which is quite the steal despite the smaller cup. From discussion with the owner I have tried their Mexican blend which has more of a chocolatey, berry taste (and is my preferred taste) and then when this sold out, also their other blend (name escapes me) which had a citrusy bright taste. I think they should label their beans so you know which one to request. Double shots are the norm apparently so that gets a thumbs up in my book. They have some baked items, which look like half-sized muffin (somewhere between a mini and a standard sized muffin) and they look pretty unappealing (especially compared to the sweet treats available at the neighbouring Artisan Boulangerie Company) and I would strongly suggest they try and up the ante in the bakery department!<br>There is also a tapas bar as part of 63 celcius. While I would go back to the coffee shop, I would give the tapas bar a miss and this is what has brought my review down... $18++ for a glass of wine that could barely be considered a &#34;glass&#34;... even with the free flow tapas from 4-7pm this was a rip off (and  &#34;flowing&#34; is not a word I would use to describe the frequency of the tapas being distributed). All in all, give the coffee a try, and hopefully the tapas side lifts it game because it faces pretty stiff competition from Cook &amp; Brew, The Exchange, The Bank, Marche and Extra Virgin Pizza.

63Celcius&#39;s 2kg Australian Tomahawk Wagyu was lovingly grilled in the Josper Grill to seal in the juices. This was certainly one of my favorite dishes of the night. This feeds a good 6 pax i think? I love that it&#39;s simply done and so juicy and flavorful.
Like any other Starbucks only this one is on the 1st level (that&#39;s second floor for you American types) and has a lovely outdoor covered, fanned patio to boot!

text: This is a very popular store for yong tau foo. Besides selling yong tau foo, it also sells fishball noodles and wanton noodles. Toast is also available.<br><br>I suggest to just focus on the yong tau foo. The items are fresh and of decent size. There are both fried and non fried items and the variety is plenty. I like both the soup (tasty) and dry versions. <br><br>The most popular would be the mushrooms - big, thick, plump juicy mushrooms which are full of flavor - and the fried meat balls. I think the meatball has lard which makes it quite addictive, but too much of it can get a bit rich (jelak). <br><br>Items available (from what I can remember)<br>- mushrooms<br>- fried meatballs<br>- broccoli<br>- fried eggplants<br>- lady finger (okra)<br>- whole round tomato<br>- quail eggs (set of 2)<br>- fried egg tofu<br>- regular tofu (fried and non fried), taupok<br>- seaweed<br>- bittergourd<br>- fried yam<br>- fried dried bean curd sheet<br>- mushroom meat ball<br>- fishball<br>- enoki mushroom<br>- crabsticks<br>- stuffed chilies<br>- pig skin<br>- cuttlefish<br>- fried wantons<br>- and many more (the typical ytf items)<br><br>After selecting your items, inform the staff what kind of noodles (kway teow, mee pok, yellow noodles, bee hoon) or rice you want, and if you want to add vegetables (kang kong, bean sprouts, cai xin). <br><br>NOTE: when it is very crowded and you don&#39;t find any available seats/tables, just join the queue to select your items. Tell the staff how many in your party and they will find/allocate your group a place. They have this system down to a science. <br>You may just have to wait for a while. Anyway, by the time you have your seat, your noodles will be more or less ready. This is definitely not a place for lingering during the peak lunch hour. <br><br>It opens from 730 am to 6 pm. Apparently the Yong Tau Foo stall in Takashimaya food court is a sister outlet. Since the price increase at Lucky Plaza, the prices at both outlets are more or less the same.

text: MAKE SURE YOU CHECK WHAT THEY CHARGED.. text: Very delicious yong tau foo. The posters say it all. The speciality is the super crunchy fried meatball and well marinated shiitake mushrooms. Price is reasonable for such an expensive location. The staff are quite particular that you order first before taking a seat chosen by them. I wouldn&#39;t say service is good but hey, you are really there to savour the food rather than linger and chat as it can get busy during meal times. Definitely worth visiting again and again!

text: Mm I love Milksha! My husband and I were in search of boba while getting loss in the ginormous Suntec City Shopping Center. Google maps lead us here thinking we were going to something KOI or Tiger Sugar so we were a little surprised when we arrived here. Honestly I&#39;m glad I found this place. It was a cool twist to traditional boba, especially if you like the milky flavor. We ended up returning to Milksha several times and I will continue to do so on my many endeavors to Singapore.
