text: I been waiting for Milksha to open in Singapore not too long I arrived on this sunny island. Then a trip to Hong Kong somewhat disrupted my plan but I would not head back to &#34;The Land of the Free&#34; before getting my hand on a cup of Milksha&#39;s signature drink. Finally I braced myself and headed out into the Sunday crowd. <br><br>Arrived at Suntec and I was lucky to so easily spotted Milksha on the 2nd floor. Saying Suntec is a huge mall is just an understatement. It was confusing with all the different towers too. <br><br>The line was not too bad in front of me. Probably like 4 persons. However, while I was waiting for my order, the crowd started appearing and the line outside looked scary. Ha!! Lucky me!!!<br><br>SERVICE 5/5<br>Staffs taking my order and bagging my order were both nice and friendly! Currently Milksha is giving out a cup sleeve with every drink purchase. The sleeve got me really excited!! It was so cute ;D<br><br>AMBIENCE 4/5<br>I don&#39;t think it was meant to be a café. They have these really mini tables inside which they probably serve for people to place their drinks and take pictures.<br><br>DRINK 4/5<br>The staff said they usually recommend 0 or 30% sugar level. I chose 30. I wish it was sweeter. I ordered the Azuki Matcha Milk, hard to drink up the Azuki with normal level of ice. So next time I will do less ice and 50% sugar level. <br><br>Perhaps next year they will open a 2nd store at Orchard? Going all the way to Suntec for Milksha  can be a pain. Then again I probably will still trek my way there :P<br><br>PS. Made my trip to Millenia area again and bought my 2nd Azuki Matcha Milk. Definitely 50% sugar and less ice!! 07.16.2019

text: Milksha is located upstairs in Suntec City Mall and they&#39;re easy to spot from one of the tower entrances! It seemed like they had ads for their matcha drinks but I was intrigued by their roasted wheat tea latte. It was only S$3.80 which is pretty reasonable for the small size! I got mine with honey pearls and they were fresh and chewy. I liked that the drink wasn&#39;t too sweet and it had a distinct roasted taste to it. Would definitely recommend this drink to others looking to decide on a boba place in the mall!

text: I usually wouldn&#39;t rave about coffee establishments but when it comes to The Coffee Bean &amp; Tea Leaf at Junction 8, I feel like I must. The outlet may be a little crammed at certain spaces and each time I drop by, there will always be a handful of students studying or doing homework. <br><br>The highlight of the café is its all day breakfast menu and of course, delicious cakes! Most importantly, the brand name is halal-certified which means more visits from me. I am in love with the Eggs Benedict ($6++) prepared here; delicious poached eggs mixed with hollandaise sauce atop a slice of chicken ham. Love the fresh salad on the side too because I&#39;m a sucker for dried cranberries. Personally, I think eateries that serve all-day breakfast are a godsent because really, who&#39;s to say what time breakfast should be? Breakfast food is always the most amazing! Before I digress any further, I also adore the Pure Caramel ice-blended drink here. The coffee-free beverage is so creamy and full of caramel gorgeousness that it makes me go weak in the knees. The rich Home-Style Carrot Cake and cheesecakes here are another joy to behold. The cream cheese icing present on the Carrot Cake is phenomenal and the cake itself is really flavourful. Best enjoyed with a fruity tea!

text: Only reason why I came here is because it was the closest place for a coffee and my friend was in a pinch for time. <br><br>I prepared myself mentally for a bad cup of coffee and pointed to the coffee that had a label that said &#34;most aromatic&#34;. <br><br>At $6.70, I was amazed at how horrible the latte was. Zero flavor. I should&#39;ve ordered water instead. <br><br>I&#39;m puzzled by how this chain or ones like Starbucks are in business, knowing that they peddle sub-standard products to their customers. <br><br>Yelp did not allow me to post without adding 1 star. But technically this place deserves zero stars.

The Coffee Club was a meeting point for me and my friends. It was a nice meeting place, quite enough to have a lovely chat. I also went there after dinner and only wanted to order something light. I ordered their Macadamia Moments and it was DELICIOUS! I will definitely visit there again for dessert.

I have no idea why Cedele seems to be so popular. I like their bread. Seriously, all two stars go to their bread. But the incredibly boring sandwiches themselves and the bland soup they are served with get absolutely zero stars from me. <br><br>Sometimes you buy a sandwich out and you marvel at the wonder of its simplicity. Other times you ask yourself why you just paid close to $10 for something you could make *better* yourself (and are reminded of how lazy you are).<br><br>This outlet in particular is probably the worst among the Cedele&#39;s I&#39;ve been to. I&#39;m usually a fairly patient person but I have never seen such inefficient service in my life. It. Just. Takes. So. Long! And I&#39;m not getting any younger!

text: Was looking for a petfriendly cafe in West to bring my dog, and found this gem!<br>My parents were really taken by this quaint place!<br><br>I do recommend to try the meesiam (which may seem like a strange choice for cafe food), but the portion was really generous, &amp; the broth was really tasty!<br><br>The ondeh ondeh cake is pretty good too! The toasted coconut bits really made the cake!

text: Nice ambiance. Pricy quality.<br><br>Lamb shank $28. Well grilled with moist insides and slight crisped on the edge. Chewy yet flavourful. I don&#39;t like the fats though it adds to the taste. I don&#39;t mind the redness.<br><br>Beef Sirloin $28. Medium rare. Good balance of greens and fries. The fries is the surprise. I will remember the fries. As for the steak, it&#39;s pretty good. Nothing memorable, on the positive side.<br><br>Ambiance like this on the west side neighbourhood is a nice find.

text: Let&#39;s start with this place is dog friendly... I was sold at woof! We went for brunch and were pleasantly surprised, the food was wonderful and moderately priced! They were super busy and the server was running and the wait time was still fairly reasonable. I read another review that suggested that this establishment is unfamiliar with salt... to be fair, we have found a majority of restaurants in Singapore under season...  most will bring you some if you ask or you can follow our idea and carry salt and pepper with you! We will definitely be returning!

text: Tucked away in a corner of a residential street, I wouldn&#39;t know about the existence of this cafe if my friend didn&#39;t introduce it to me. Business is quite good during lunch time and I would guess that most customers specially make their way here. Since it&#39;s not in a mall or upscale location, I expected the prices to be lower but it was comparable to mid range restaurants. I had duck confit which was crispy on the outside and tender on the inside. I would have preferred it to come with a less creamy sauce. Portion and taste are fine so if you are tired of chain restaurants, give this a chance!

text: When I first saw W39.. Located next to KFC... It looked so cute and bloo!!! :) i had heard great comments about their cakes so I decided to try their rainbow cake at $6.80+ it&#39;s reasonably priced even though.. Anyone who can bake will tell you that&#39;s still overpriced.. Nonetheless... The buttercream wasn&#39;t too buttery and the cake was light. The colours were pretty too :) we had a side of chicken wings which tasted and smelt just like the har jiong kai which you get at a tze char at 2 times more than what the tze char stall would charge you for.. Nonetheless I would recommend you to checkout other places for wings and you can def try their apple crumble pie :) delicious and a  generous serving with a dollop of ice cream! :)

text: i put off writing this review just to see if i still feel as strongly as i did, about this place, after a cooling off period.<br>it&#39;s been more than a month now and i think it is safe to say i&#39;m not clouded by any impulsive verbal diarrhoea.<br><br>firstly, finding this place is a challenge.<br>even for a former west sider junkie like me.<br>fortunately, i was cabbing it and even though the taxi driver knew of the road, he still brought me on a tour of the colourfully named roads, kuning(yellow), merah(red) before arriving at puteh(white).<br>if you are driving, your safest bet will be parking at clementi stadium.<br>limited parking in front of w39 is available and if you do like to take a risk at parking illegally, do have a word with marcus before you do so.<br><br>it was packed to the brim on an august saturday afternoon.<br>thankfully, we secured a reservation and were seated within.<br>decor was pleasant enough but i&#39;m forever wary of style over substance.<br><br>staff were not the most experienced but they tried.<br>upon the recommendation of their staff and the fact the brunch menu exclaimed it as a local favourite! nasi lemak with roasted spice chicken leg, that was what i ordered.<br><br>when it arrived, the fleeting moments of it&#39;s decent looks gave way to an inner flaw that is hard to overlook.<br>salt or the lack thereof.<br>yes, most times people complain about their food being overly salty but today the oldest, most ubiquitous food seasoning was missing?<br>did someone forget about it?<br>but not only was the coconut rice lacking in salt, the coconut milk was way watered down resulting in a tastelessly bland, overly wet and not so lemak rice.<br>sure, you could ask for more of their homemade sambal but again that is mere window dressing.<br>nasi lemak rice has to be palatable enough for you to eat it on it&#39;s own.<br><br>next the chicken leg, best described as a powdery turmeric mess.<br>again, did salt go AWOL?<br>after just one bite, all you want is to wash it away with their decent coffee.<br>mind you, their nasi lemak is priced at $12.50, so the benchmark should be set so much the higher, no?<br><br>and guess what? <br>they interestingly use nicely poached eggs for most of their dishes.<br>but guess what, i&#39;m not a fan of poached eggs!:(<br>give me oily fried eggs with runny yolks, anytime, for my nasi lemak, please!<br><br>seeing how i only recently scored me the maverick badge, here is a 2 star rating in hope you can score yours too!:)

text: was in search for the next big rainbow cake in singapore that drove (well rather by Mr SBS uncle) me here. Cakes look pretty on the shelves that screams &#39;eat me&#39;. so i did. ordered the rainbow cake and red velvet. <br><br>remember how many say not to be just a pretty face but have substance? sadly this place just has a pretty face when it comes to dessert and coffee. i have to admit the sponge cake used in the rainbow and red velvet cake is light and not that sweet but the cream... OMG. tooooo sweet and too much. <br><br>ordered a latte to go with me cakes but sadly I had better coffee. i&#39;m not picky with my coffee and even I can say its meh... sooo for coffee lovers I would recommend you trying something else instead<br><br>i have to admit the service here is good and attentive. they just have to up a notch on the desserts and drinks to make this a good chill out place.<br><br>i can&#39;t comment on the savories for i had none of it this time but I doubt i&#39;ll ever come back and try - looking at the reviews. <br><br>however, this is a good place to come once and see the pretty cakes. <br><br>overall, its a good attempt at a cafe but needs more work to reach memorable. <br><br>Gambatte W39!

text: New indie cafes and bistros are popping up around Singapore faster than ever before (oh my poor pocket), but this is actually a good thing - more options, more variety, more cool hangouts for the weekends :)<br><br>Visited W39 last Saturday with some friends for a casual breakfast, and it was love at first step-in! Located at the far end of a stretch of shophouses near West Coast Road, the exterior of this cool little bistro reminded me of a summertime beach house. The decor theme is a mix of lemon yellow stripes against fresh whites and blues, full-pane glass doors and lots of windows - such a happy, inviting place, tucked just steps away from a quiet private residential neighbourhood.<br><br>Indulge yourself with the shelves of magazines, little trinkets and nostalgic old-time snacks (think rabbit brand candy, and sour lemon!) as you wait for your food to be served. We were tempted by the seemingly popular Mee Siam, but somehow all ended up ordering the Hearty Breakfast or classic Eggs Ben (all great choices). The Hearty Breakfast was yummy and very well made, eggs were perfectly fried - runny on the sunny side, slightly charred on the other... the sausage and toasts were tasty, and served with arugula salad on the side. Happy patrons we were.<br><br>I really love this place - service was warm, friendly and prompt. Food was good and not grossly overpriced, and it wasn&#39;t too packed for a Saturday either. Will certainly be back again :)<br><br>Both indoor and outdoor seating available. Check out my photos.<br>Oh, and they sell some baked goods such as bread loaves and cakes to-go too.

text: Drawn by the siren call of the Yelp Saturday Brunch Club, hordes of hungry hungry Yelpers descended on W39 for a good balance of &#39;ang moh&#39; brunch options and some local choices. <br><br>Now, I&#39;ve have rated W39 3 stars. I enjoyed the mee siam although it was atypical (much too rich and creamy, though the poached egg was a fascinating take), and while it might not become my go-to place when I have a mee siam craving, I definitely wouldn&#39;t mind ordering it again. The Eggs Benedict was well put together, my only complaint is that it was TINY. I could have had three of &#39;em. The Honey Lemon was way way too sweet, but once the ice started melting, it wasn&#39;t so bad.<br><br>BUT. For everyone else at the table, I could tell that W39 felt a lot more 2-starry than 3. (And if you&#39;ll refer to Jerilyn&#39;s review, you&#39;ll get further evidence why.)<br><br>The Nasi Lemak that one of the other Yelpers ordered was... very underwhelming and the small size of the Hearty Breakfast, well okay it wasn&#39;t small, just not HEARTY (full caps intended). The rice for the nasi lemak was under seasoned and the paninis were awfully small. Small niggling issues here and there that really undercut the place standing out amongst the increasing number of brunchy cafes popping up in Singapore.<br><br>My conclusion after our visit? An Eggs Benedict and Mee Siam are just enough to feed one, and if that&#39;s all you order, you&#39;ll have a pretty good meal.<br><br>If you stray off that path that I have painstakingly cleared for you though, don&#39;t blame me when you find yourself in a minefield of mediocrity.

text: Have been hearing quite a bit about this place but have been feeling lazy to trek down to the West to try it out. Well, finally I did and I wasn&#39;t disappointed at all.<br><br>Was a short bus ride away from Clementi or JE MRT Station. <br><br>On first sight, the place reminded me of my area at Serangoon Gardens with the cafe nestled snugly among  residential houses. Was quite crowded on a rainy Sunday evening where most people were there for dinner; isn&#39;t it a testament to how good a place is if it is filled on a raining Sunday evening? The interior was filled to the brim and so was the exterior.<br><br>We weren&#39;t there for dinner but vowed to try their mains the next time around as it looked so good from what we saw at our neighboring diners&#39; tables. Ordered a chocolate cake (forgotten the exact name but have a look at my picture) and the texture was gooey, melty and is a chocolate maven&#39;s piece of heaven - a must try. The coffee wasn&#39;t the best but was passable.<br><br>Loved the atmosphere! Wished I knew of this place while I was at NUS as it would definitely be on my hang-out list!

text: Homely with lots of wooden furniture and glass walls.  Best tiramisu with expresso to mix together.  Mee Siam tastes superb too. Awesome!

The only cafe/resturant I&#39;ve found in West Coast that comes close to an Australian style coffee shop. Coffee was good and they have a decent range of meals and snacks on the menu. It has great customer service which can be hard to find in Singapore.

Heard about the crowd here on weekends so I was a little concerned about coming here on a Sunday night. <br><br>The place wasn&#39;t too hard to find from the nearby bus stop (you might have parking problems if you&#39;re driving though!) and the ambience was decent. <br><br>There are lots of nostalgic stuff laid all over the place which makes the overall ambience quite cosy - albeit a little forced, as another Yelper mentioned in his review. <br><br>Having gone down mainly for dessert. A friend and I ordered a flat white, the crunchie hazelnut and a tiramisu to share among us. <br><br>I take pride in my coffee and I can honestly say the flat white was nothing special - a little too flat (pun unintended) actually. <br><br>The crunchie hazelnut and the tiramisu looked great and I thought it would at least make up for the disappointing coffee. <br><br>I was wrong. <br><br>The crunchie hazelnut had an overwhelming taste of fresh cream that made it far too sweet for both our tastes. <br><br>The tiramisu came with a serving of espresso - which was something I had never seen before, and for good reason. Without the espresso, the tiramisu tasted entirely of marscapone. Even with the espresso poured in, it still felt pretty... off. I couldnt taste any kahlua liqour in the tiramisu with or without the espresso, which to me, sealed the deal as one of the poorest tiramisus I&#39;ve had. If you want a good tiramisu, try out Kith Cafe at Park Mall - it&#39;s far better. <br><br>The place was also quite noisy, so if you&#39;re looking for a quiet place to hang out with friends or loved ones, take note. <br><br>I didnt try any of the food items, but the lamb ribs and wagyu burgers other people were eating looked quite appetitizing.  But then again, so were the desserts we ordered.<br><br>Not coming back to this place again. At least the service here was something worth mentioning.

text: Came here with the Singapore Yelp Brunch Club and while I loved meeting fellow yelpers, W39 was well, ehhhh. <br><br>It&#39;s 2.5 stars (but not quite 3) in my opinion. <br><br>Let&#39;s just say, the concept is good but the execution just well, kinda sucked, for lack of a better word.<br><br>Food: I got the Hearty Breakfast, and wasn&#39;t the least impressed (especially because I was at Arbite the weekend before, and they, they do a mean hearty breakfast - but more on that in another review!) the portions in general just seemed small all around (except for the local options) which would be fine if it tasted amazing but everything just seemed subpar. I also tried bites of the Mee Siam and the Ham &amp; Cheese Panini. The Ham &amp; Cheese Panini definitely tasted kind of like something I could&#39;ve done myself, however, the Mee Siam was probably the best thing there in my opinion. It was hearty, with a nice sweet flavor to it. I enjoyed that the most. We also got the Honey Lemon Ice Tea which tasted like someone spilled half the jar of honey into. Did they?! <br><br>Ambience: Like I said, great concept, horrible execution. They try to be &#34;cute&#34; with the cute nautical theme and selling old candies we grew up with but it just seems kind of copied. The seating inside is limited and pretty cramped and the service was alright. <br><br>All in all, we left happy to have met everyone but not so happy with the food. Not horrible but really nothing special.

text: A lovely corner boutique cafe that serves good food and desserts! A lovely place for lunch and weekend pig out. Also good for small events and celebrations

W39 was just kind of average. Worth a visit if you just want a chill out spot with a nice decor. But not a place I would return to.<br>The service was earnest and polite but quite inefficient. <br>Granted that I did not try the food, I really cannot comment on any dish in particular. But when I checked out what the other diners were having, none of them screamed or even said &#39;EAT ME!!!&#39; And the coffee was decent but really not worth the fifteen minute wait for it.<br>But if you are bent on trying an average brunch place, it could be wise to reserve a table, as W39 was quite crowded on a Saturday afternoon.

W39 is the brainchild of 2 Eastie sisters and this cheerful blue and yellow spot is actually both a bistro and a bakery and that only means 1 thing for me-brunch.<br><br>I wouldn&#39;t have gone out of my way for brunch in the West if not for an appointment in the area. Sorry westies, you&#39;re not gonna be seeing more food posts from the western part of Singers.<br><br>My Mocha tasted more like regular latte. Where is ze chocolate??! Meh-ish latte at best. Very diluted. Thankfully I&#39;ve lowered my expectation so I wasn&#39;t overly disappointed. Don&#39;t go expecting anything artisan.<br><br>Hearty Breakfast ($13.50) is a greedy and lazy girl&#39;s best option. Well, first and foremost, it has everything. It&#39;s quite hard to screw up an American breakfast since everything is kinda outsourced. The scrambled eggs were a little overdone for my liking. The best part was the toast (i think it&#39;s brioche) with its airy texture. Salted butter would be welcomed anytime. <br><br>I originally opted for a Brie Parma Ham Panini (or was it a Croque Madame) but i was tempted by the Braised Pork Cheeks Gruyere Panini (S$13) that the neighboring table ordered. The mouthwatering scent was too good that i had to change my order immediately! Boy was I glad i did!<br><br>The panini was stellar with the slightly crusty shell and dense and moist center. Pork cheeks were tender and flavorful and the sandwich had a perfect meat-gravy-bread ratio. The taste of the meat was rather strong but i&#39;m a carnivore so i don&#39;t care. Besides, it was balanced by the savory gravy and the light sweetness of the bread.<br><br>If you&#39;re looking for something lighter, the assortment of cakes, breads and pastries should not disappoint (i base that on my review of their breads).

This was good. They had great white beer and crab cakes and salad. The tenderloin steak was also great, but it was too bloody when I had asked for medium. Sauce that came with the tenderloin was good. They let me substitute mashed potatoes instead of fries.

text: Great ambience! Nice food, real chill. Would recommend for a good outing with friends

it is the weekend! which means it is brunch - and here is a good place to get a decent one, even if more than a little far out. this rustic little cafe is unpretentious (pretty rare in the recent crop of cafes), and it serves up an averagely-decent brunch menu that spans american brunch classics to local delights.<br><br>most of us started off on the western side of the menu - mostly average fixins&#39; - their poached eggs are probably the most notable thing on the menu.<br><br>they make an appearance in most of the breakfast dishes, and each is a neat parcel of cooked white and flowing yolk - good execution, but it might have helped more if the sauces and flavors had just as much care.<br><br>the local specialties were rather a hit-and-miss. a hit with a very lemak mee siam that was served with a poached egg - you will want to eat this hot because it quickly loses its charm as it cools - and a terrible miss with the nasi lemak, which came with another one of those poached eggs. the rice had barely any flavor, the chicken impressive-looking but barely seasoned and a tad dry - this dish was pretty dismal.<br><br>I also think that poached egg on the rice smacks a little of trying-too-hard - there&#39;s something to be said about the texture of a golden fried egg with a runny yolk and the texture it brings to the dish.<br><br>but I got pretty lucky with my main of grilled saba (mackerel) drizzled with a sticky soy glaze on baby spinach. definitely not the sort of thing I expected in this sort of place, but nothing to complain about since it worked very well. the mackerel was oily and savory, the baby spinach crisp and green, and that glaze a sweet-savory counterpoint.<br><br>it works for this place that its kitschy, in a good almost-believably-local way, without any of the pretentiousness in the hipster-hangouts we see these days. the food is decent, though not quite worth traveling for without a car - I suggest it only if driving and looking for a cute little place to sit on the weekend.

text: Ate here with the yelp crew and was expecting something delicious but definitely left unsatisfied and worse, hungry.  I think the restaurant does a good job with the decor and food presentation but I just wasn&#39;t impressed with the food.  We tried most of all the things on the breakfast menu and it was just eh..  Maybe bc I&#39;m used to American brunch places that are huge and delicious (referring to NYC and LA only) but yeah.. Will not go back..

This place is a nice surprise on a quiet stretch of Changi Rd - when you step in, the chill vibe kinda feels like you&#39;re on holiday in Malaysia. My top vote goes to the claypot rice - wholesome, rich and aromatic. Unlike most others, each grain of rice here is completely infused with flavour. My foodie family would finish up every bit, scraping up the rice crust at the bottom of the pot - the shiokest part. The gently brewed chrysanthemum tea makes a perfect ending - no added sugar, just the way we like it. The prawn noodles and laksa are good too. Generally, I come here to enjoy refined hawker food in an aircon setting and at unpretentious prices. It&#39;s also a pleasant 10min stroll along the Siglap river from Kembangan MRT.

text: This month Nom&#39;s is organising its first Cafe Week which is happening over 2 weekends on 10-13 Dec and 17-20 Dec 2015. There is 14 cafes participating in this event, offering Brunch/ Lunch at $25/ person, Tea at $15/ person, and Dinner at $35/ person. <br><br>The cafe is located at Keppel Bay, which is about 10 minutes walk from Harbourfront MRT station. The place looks like a different world from the nearby noisy and packed Vivocity. Here there is a spread of yachts anchoring around by the bay with expensive looking Condominiums in the background. Sounds like a place for the rich and famous. <br><br>The cafe is located at Keppel Bay, which is about 10 minutes walk from Harbourfront MRT station. The place looks like a different world from the nearby noisy and packed Vivocity. Here there is a spread of yachts anchoring around by the bay with expensive looking Condominiums in the background. Sounds like a place for the rich and famous. <br><br>Boston Clam Chowder ($14++)<br>Served in squid ink bread with bacon, Idaho potatoes, celery, parsley and clam stock<br>The chowder is very rich and thick. Best have it with the crispy squid ink bread which balances the salty bacon&#39;s taste in the chowder.<br><br>Charred Broccoli Salad ($17++)<br>A healthy mix of Virginia ham, baby gem lettuce, avocado, spiced almonds, Spanish onions, blistered grapes and shaved parmesan, drizzled with honey-garlic dressing<br>It is quite a light and refreshing, although I would prefer the vegetables to be chopped into smaller pieces with more dressing added.<br><br>Next for the main courses which also come with 2 choices.<br><br>Linguine Aglio Olio ($18++ for spaghetti version)<br>Linguine Aglio Olio tossed with Chilean scallops, sundried tomatoes, bird&#39;s eye chilli, wilted spinach and smoked bacon<br>The pasta is quite tasty with the sweetness of the tomatoes balancing the spicy taste of the chilli and salty bacon.<br><br>Duck Leg Cassoulet ($28++)<br>Duck Leg Cassoulet served with carrots, pearl onions, mushrooms, Brussels sprouts, garlic confit and bacon<br>The serving is quite huge. The duck meat is quite tender and flavourful, although I feel that the sauce is a bit on the salty side. The sourness taste of pearl onions quite stimulate one&#39;s appetite.<br><br>Lastly for dessert, there is also 2 choices for us to choose from, although we are both quite full by this time.<br><br>Sticky Date Pudding ($12++)<br>Sticky Date Pudding served with housemade butterscotch and vanilla bean ice cream with sprinkled walnuts<br>It is my all-time favourite dessert which I will always order when I dine here. I am so happy when I notice it on the menu. The story behind this dessert is that the co-owner of Prive used to operate a restaurant called Brown Sugar which served great Sticky Date Pudding. Since then it is a well known fact that it is the must order dessert here. The sticky date pudding is served pipping hot. It tastes sweet, soft and moist, although I could not taste the bites of dates this time round. A great well done dessert.<br><br>Chocolate Posset<br>Served with summer berry coulis, pistachio biscotti<br>It is chocolate mousse, served in a jar. It tastes quite rich and creamy. However it is wasted on me who is a non chocolate lover. It tastes a bit jelat after a few mouthfuls.<br><br>Overall the food is not bad. Comparing with the ala carte prices, having the $35 nett for the set dinner sounds like such a great deal. The place is packed during the weekend. Getting the staff to refill the water takes quite an effort, although they do check with us on the food from time to time.

Kids friendly with a small outdoors playground. The quality and price of food meet the expectations of a rather upscale, not too fancy cafe-- clean, neat, nothing too special, common but still prepared with care. I visit once or twice a month for brunch for the nice morning view of the marina or for dinner for the serene atmosphere of the Singapore evening.

text: Have always dined at Privé Cafe and this was my first time at Privé Grill.<br><br>Service was top-notch and the wait staff were very attentive to our needs. My sole intention of dining here was to try out their steaks.<br><br>Verdict:<br>- US Creekstone Farms Angus Ribeye Cap (280g) at $88 - this was the most expensive steak on the menu. The waiter recommended this as I wanted something tender and juicy and boy was he right! My only teeny weeny gripe was that I asked for Medium Well and certain parts look Medium to me. Plus, there were 1-2 chunks of fat within the beef which may have contributed to it&#39;s &#39;tenderness&#39; but I can do without the fat.<br><br>- Appetizer of Crabmeat and Prawn Cake at $17 - our appetizer came as a set of 2 prawn cakes. Order this only if you are famished as the size of each prawn cake is rather large and you might be too full to feast on your main course. The prawn cakes were delightfully crispy and the meat stuffing sat well and didn&#39;t crumple as you cut into the prawn cake. Dish was served with rockets which acted as an excellent foil to the savory appetizer.<br><br>- Roasted Barramundi Fillet at $32 - my partner ordered this and I had a bite of the fish which was amazingly fresh!<br><br>- Lemon Meringue Tart - we asked if we could order this from the cafe and the staff politely agreed to our request while bringing us a menu to choose from. I remember having this tart a while back and felt that the tar/lemon portion was bigger then what was presented to me. Hmm, nonetheless still my favourite dessert at Privé Cafe.<br><br>There was a nice end to the night where all the female diners were presented with a small brown paper bag with a wrapped brown package inside!

text: Ok this is not your usual menu. We went to a special wine dinner with an off the menu selection. So the expectation was high in terms of food quality since we were pairing with some great wines from Australia. <br><br>We began with the starter. The dish was nicely balanced. Though a hint too much lime and could have done with a little more salt. The Sauvignon blanc went perfectly with it. <br><br>This was followed with the salmon belly, which was very good. It also paired well with the estate Chardonnay. The wine was exceptional and complex going well with the rich fish. <br><br>For the next dish an air dried beef with truffle foam was presented. Another good dish, though I felt that the truffle overwhelmed the dish a little. <br><br>Mains was an exceptionally good hanger steak. Perfectly seared and served plain with mustard. It was juicy and wonderfully tender and flavorful. Best dish of the night. Went well with the cab sav. <br><br>Dessert was nice but not exceptional. The wine on the other hand was very good and was the star of the dish. <br><br>Generally the food was very good, up to expectations. But the price with wine pairing of about $100 per person made it exceptional good value so I rate this a 5 star, though if I removed the wine and rated the food alone it would be a 4 star. Be aware that we ate at the aircon grill room with a special menu so I can&#39;t vouch for the standard menu. Nonetheless I&#39;m impressed to want to come back again to try the normal menu.

text: Very honestly: 2.5 actual stars for the food, extra 0.5 stars for the ingredients and another star for the location. <br><br>Prive cafe is situated right in front of a Marina, the perfect spot to feel like you are in Santorini, or Tuscany, or somewhere in the Mediterranean, with a view of the gorgeous (i like to imagine it as blue) sea, and private yachts. Need a vacation and have no cash, try Prive cafe!  It is also kids friendly with a nice little playground where kids can frolic while the adults caught up over eggs and coffee. <br><br>All the good things aside, food wise, I was disappointed. I had their Prive burger, and fiance had the Ultimate breakkie. The first thing I noticed was all the fresh ingredients, the salad looked fresh, the beef patty looked thick and juicy, I was excited to start. However sad to say, the taste just wasn&#39;t there. The beef patty while thick was tasteless. The buns were soaked in butter causing them to lose their fluffiness. And the ultimate breakkie also nothing spectacular. While they didn&#39;t scrimp on the ingredients, the cooking would be better done to make full use of the good ingredients they have! <br><br>Meh, I would still go back because of the location just to give them another chance.

text: This is a review of a dinner with a friend on a Friday evening at Privé Grill.<br><br>First, as it is on Keppel Island, it is a little off the beaten path.<br><br>The room is modern yet classic.  This is the type of room that defines what I expect from a fine dining experience.  My only issue with the ambiance is that, even on a Friday evening, the restaurant was almost completely empty.  This means the evening was missing the energy brought by other diners enjoying their meals.<br><br>The staff is excellent.  They are friendly and professional.  But, more than that, they demonstrated an eye for detail and took extra steps along the  way to insure we enjoyed our meal.<br><br>The food ranged from below average to excellent.  It is this level of inconsistency that left this just short of a five star dining experience.<br><br>The meal was extremely well paced.  The staff had a knack of being there when needed.  The server was very helpful with our questions concerning the menu.  The food came in a perfect and never rushed order.<br><br>After we had selected the bottle of wine, they brought an amuse bouche of sashimi.  When I communicated to the server that my dining companion can not eat raw seafood, the server quickly whisked hers away.  Soon after, a replacement of grilled watermelon was brought out.  <br><br><a href="/redir?url=http%3A%2F%2Ftinyurl.com%2Fdxc3e5u&amp;s=5a846e4616a5223dd07ab3d95806a909de43d83189efe8cc72ac2873eade972a" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">tinyurl.com/dxc3e5u</a><br><br><a href="/redir?url=http%3A%2F%2Ftinyurl.com%2Fcvexxd7&amp;s=0170808ac5b85b14f47c431095b4c2b79662017e80a7eb35acf8729f1ccec2fc" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">tinyurl.com/cvexxd7</a><br><br>A nice basket of breads was provided next.<br><br><a href="/redir?url=http%3A%2F%2Ftinyurl.com%2Fc2yyzbw&amp;s=d12e41489c1acde24b30bf524be448d95fd64d69936ab5b7ee508d68a2a54736" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">tinyurl.com/c2yyzbw</a><br><br>We usually order starters to share.  However, on this evening, we went our own ways.  We shared small bites but, for the most part,  we stuck to our own appetizers.<br><br>I chose:<br><br>JAMÓN IBÉRICO BELLOTA  (Saffron Pear Chutney, Tomato Bruschetta) <br><br>This was very good.  The Iberian ham itself was excellent.  The sweet tomatoes provided a nice contrast to the ham&#39;s saltiness.   The bread was simply there as an organic spoon.<br><br><a href="/redir?url=http%3A%2F%2Ftinyurl.com%2Fbn8b3c9&amp;s=b2979a46c14c09b3aa23bda8eacd1282e6c9bcf7d27df721bcb70f2fb858f6c0" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">tinyurl.com/bn8b3c9</a><br><br>She chose:<br><br>PRIVÉ GRILL&#39;S CAESAR SALAD (Poached Egg, Bacon, Shaved Aged Parmesan, Garlic Croutons, Anchovies)<br><br>First, my friend ordered this without the sliced anchovies.  From my taste and watching my dining companion easily complete it, this seemed like a very successful rendition of a classic.  The only negative was the large shavings of Parmesan were a little difficult to navigate.  They may have been a little form over function.  The salad would have been easier to eat with an even distribution of smaller shavings .<br><br><a href="/redir?url=http%3A%2F%2Ftinyurl.com%2Fcju9qol&amp;s=9181ebd6b4fbfd81c8decd47959f9aa7031f828c7ced3a8c8eaf198dcbcefeed" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">tinyurl.com/cju9qol</a><br><br>My Main:<br><br>NEW ZEALAND &#34;HARMONY&#34; ORGANIC (Sourced only from free-range farms, Harmony&#39;s cattle are all 100%grass-fed in open pastures. - RIB-EYE 340g) - <br><br>Hmmm, with all of that fancy talk, I expected a melt in my mouth spectacular steak.   It simply was not to be.  It was cooked to a perfect medium rare.  However, through lack of seasoning or some other misstep, it was rather bland.  While not tough, it was also not as tender as I expect from a high quality rib-eye.<br><br><a href="/redir?url=http%3A%2F%2Ftinyurl.com%2Fc4bfl95&amp;s=c9044066dad17d87fc2c4792cb4de996f51bfc7e7fa77c2466bf3460309b21ba" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">tinyurl.com/c4bfl95</a><br><br>TWICE BAKED POTATOES (Bacon, Sour Cream, Chives)<br><br>This was barely edible.  It was more akin to overcooked baked potato than twice baked potato.  I love potatoes.  I really do.  For me to walk away from a potato, there has to be something seriously wrong with it.<br><br>Her Main:<br><br>JOSPER-ROASTED WHOLE SEA BASS (Confit of Garlic Bulbs, Lemon Caper Sauce) <br><br>Every show has a star, and for this meal, the sea bass was certainly the diva.  It was tender.  It was buttery.  The garlic and the lemon were provided in a way that they were complimentary without dominating the flavor of the delicate fish.  This is how a fish should be served.  Unfortunately, it was hers and I only was given remnant bites here and there.<br><br>One last little touch, when asked about dessert, we looked at the menu.  We both decided we simply could not eat anything else.  After we told our server, she soon returned with a small bag containing a slice of carrot cake for us to share later.  <br><br>The receipt:<br><br><a href="/redir?url=http%3A%2F%2Ftinyurl.com%2Fd2tvq9v&amp;s=e6181dd16aa1dd7e66efe6f0c0fbbf49fa0b22f525aed893cf6c181d6f18577f" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">tinyurl.com/d2tvq9v</a><br><br>Overall, this was a very good dining experience.  The service was excellent.  All the ambiance required was the buzz brought by additional diners.  The food certainly had some very high points but there were also some low ones.  In the end, we both enjoyed our time at Privé Grill.<br><br>(Special note: We  topped it off with a lovely and very peaceful walk along the water.  This is definitely a secondary perk from dining here.)

text: I don&#39;t really make my way to fancy restaurants unless it&#39;s for some kind of occasion. Trudged all the way to Keppel Bay for a friend&#39;s birthday dinner and I believe I&#39;ll like to make my way there for many future special events to come!<br><br>First their service is excellent. The service staff are well-versed with their menu offerings and they are patient to help you make your choice if you are unsure. For the 4 of us, we ordered the 1kg Australian grass fed Angus Beef to share and it&#39;s a decision that we all totally DID NOT regret. Added on to the order with some servings of sides and another main dish - grilled seabass - absolutely love them.<br><br>If you are celebrating your birthday there, just let the service staff know and they&#39;ll be happy to serve up a complimentary slice of cake accompanied with well wishes and a birthday song from the crew. <br><br>We further satisfied our sweet tooth with a sticky date and pear pudding that&#39;s just simply...marvelous. The sweetness of the pear complemented the sticky date pudding well and it was overall, very pleasant!<br><br>So who&#39;s up with a special occasion soon? Bring me to Prive Grill please! ;)

This place has come up in brunch location wish-lists the girlfriend sometimes talks about, so off we went one late morning (okay, more like early afternoon. okay 1.30pm).<br><br>Even arriving at that time (when we thought most people would be done with lunch, let alone brunch), and it being a weekday, it was still a packed house. Interesting mix of office-y crowd, expat mothers, and... young couples? Seems like <br><br>As we surveyed the seating situation, the hostesses came up to ask if we wanted to dine from the cafe or grill menus, and I wondered if it would make a difference to where we were seated, but we were showed to the first table inside the door all the same. Menus came out pretty quick, but perhaps someone could come take our order? The staff were incredibly busy bussing tables and moving things about, and considering we sat next to two dudes who looked like managers doing paperwork, maybe they weren&#39;t so keen to walk our way?<br><br>We both ended up getting poached egg dishes, and when they arrived, they looked a little... conservative. I had the eggs benny, and while they were generous with the hollandaise sauce, everything was kinda room-temperature-ish, while I was thinking that the eggs might be warmer? I&#39;d also asked for an additional side of hash brown(s), which appeared in a singular triangle that may have been more at home at a fast-food joint.<br><br>The mushroom soup was pretty good though, chunky and flavourful, so it wasn&#39;t all bad.<br><br>Perhaps I had my hopes up - after all, this is at a yacht club filled with luxury boats, and I&#39;d heard such great things. Maybe next time I&#39;ll pick a quieter time, and hope the kitchen and staff aren&#39;t quite so busy?

text: We came to Prive Cafe for a spot of tea and found it a lovely place for a lazy weekend afternoon. Cakes go for 50% between 3pm-6pm on weekdays so if you happen to be at a loose end on a late week day afternoon, there&#39;s a good variety of cakes and such for a good chinwag with a girl friend or two.<br><br>We liked the fruit tart with a generous topping of pears, mangos, raspberries and blueberries, as well as the carrot cake and the apricot almond cake. The chicken pie was also pretty good and the coffees decent.<br><br>Service was pleasant and efficient.

Sticky date pudding', 'width': 180, 'height': 180, 'caption': 'Sticky date pudding'}]
text: One of my favourite places for brunch is the Prive Cafe overlooking a beautiful Marina filled with bobbing yachts in the breeze. This is one of those places that makes you feel like you&#39;re on a holiday and far far away from Monday blues. The only downside would be the really long walk it would take to the cafe/restaurant if you&#39;re not driving. <br><br>Best items on the menu would be their all-day breakfast dishes! My staple items would be the Eggs Royale, with English muffins topped with smoked salmon and poached eggs, its everything I&#39;d ask for in a big hearty breakfast. Try out a hot cup of their Hazelnut Latte, one of the best I&#39;ve tasted! Its creamy and thick in all the right flavours, but not sickly sweet and balanced with just the right amount of coffee aroma. <br><br>For dessert if you still have space in there somewhere (I&#39;m a girl - we have a separate stomach for such things) the Sticky Date Pudding is awesome! It comes drowned in a sea of butterscotch sauce, a scoop of vanilla ice cream and lots of chunky half walnuts - yummy!<br><br>Its a great place to take a stroll along the bridge or marina after your meal too!

text: Really enjoyed the restaurant week offerings at Privé! I&#39;m not much of a shellfish person but Privé put the scallop in a very different gastronomical light for me. The ingredients used towards the scallop ceviche were fresh and complemented the scallops very well. The lamb saddle was nothing short of delicious and highly recommended. Their dessert could use a little work though. Had the mango tarte tartin with coconut ice cream which was more of a strudel a la mode really. Nonetheless both &#34;tart&#34; and ice cream were too sweet and rather artificial in taste. Overall, excellent food.

The thrill of dining here really comes from being next to a marina with yachts on a lazy morning than from the food. It paints an idyllic picture for brunch, complete with the famous eggs benedict. <br><br>Also, the fact that Prive serves all-day breakfast doesn&#39;t hurt, especially for those recovering from a hangover or who just cannot bring themselves to wake before noon on week.<br><br>The service staff is a little forgetful. But you&#39;d probably do well to forgive and forget too, looking out over these calm waters.

Great marina location on the water with a laid back vibe and beautiful view of the harbor.  Food and drink and service well attempted.  Nice location for group dinner or just a quiet location for a drink.

text: I came here for a work thing, which is good cos I wouldn&#39;t be able to afford dinner here on my own. We took up the private room, which was a big favor from Prive - perks of friendship eh? Lots of wine and orders off the Josper Grill - the grill is as good as it gets! Started off with the amuse bouche of crab meat cake, pan seared duck foie gras as appetizer and honey glazed beef short rib for the main. The short rib was.. wow. Just, wow. Sweet, smoky, tender, and it went down well with the caramelized onions on the side. Dessert was a lovely nut tart, such a beauty to look upon. Prive is a lovely setting for a romantic date, but only if you have really deep pockets.

Other than the pain of getting here (you need to drive or take a taxi), the views of the marina and the exaggerated pleasure of dining on a private island make coming to Prive totally worth it. The views of the bridge are somewhat similar to looking at the Rama VIII bridge in Bangkok. The alfresco seats are especially nice in the evening but only with a breeze and no rain prior.<br><br>Most people dine at Prive Cafe, which serves breakfast favorites like eggs benedict and a dinner menu featuring lamb shank and a number of pastas. You must have the sticky date pudding and you can forgo the Kahlua and Cream milkshake.

text: This was one of the worst dinners I&#39;ve ever had in Singapore. And it wasn&#39;t because of the conversation.<br><br>Ordered our food and we waited two hours. I kept picturing that the kitchen must have one guy with one pan cooking and maybe he&#39;s one-armed because that&#39;s the only excuse for how slow the food was to come out.<br><br>Also the $74 ribeye (the most expensive thing on the menu) looked horrible but tasted &#39;ok&#39;. It was hilarious, everyone was asking me &#34;what is that?&#34;. They were shocked when I told them it was the ribeye. Doesn&#39;t the management/chef/owner know that people eat with their eyes first? Guess Money can&#39;t buy them common sense. <br><br>Anyways, save your money and go to Mortons if you want beef. <br><br>If you want anything else try your local food court because the service will be prompter and the food will look like what you expect. <br><br>BTW management, the dinner was on the 24th of October 2013. We paid more than $500 between the 4 of us. Want to comp my meal next time? Because even if you did I wouldn&#39;t waste 2 hours waiting for it. C-ya.

I never tried the food at Prive so I am in no position to comment but visually the food at Prive&#39;s fine dining restaurant looks a lot more appetizing as opposed to the food served up at Prive&#39;s cafe/bistro. <br><br>The Prive Bar has a great setting with outdoor couches facing the yachting docks. For a moment it actually feels like you&#39;re not in Singapore. <br><br>Back to reality, I had a  mixed berries mojito which was honestly terrible. The ice was not crushed nor blended properly leaving behind mini ice cubes. The mojito was quite sweet as well which made me wonder if fresh or canned berries were used. Lastly, it came in a really huge tall glass which just further emphasized quantity and not quality. I would definitely return but only for the location and comfortable seating!

text: I&#39;ve been here for brunch, dinner and desserts and have never been disappointed once!<br><br>Watch out for the crowd on weekends though this place is buzzing even though its not the most accessible.<br><br>I enjoyed my eggs royale and coffee for brunch but what&#39;s unexpected was how good their mushroom soup was! Creamy, flavourful mushroom delight in every scoop.<br><br>For dinner, I had the no frills burger, it was filling and scrumptious. Dessert didn&#39;t disappoint either with the refreshing lemon meringue pie. <br><br>Even though it overlooks the marina with a nice view of the yachts and the waters, it&#39;s not exactly the most romantic place for a meal because it can get quite noisy. Unless you can luckily find yourself in a nice corner spot, at night the outdoor seating does get quite dark! <br><br>Final verdict: Great food with one of the best views

Eggs benedict', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Eggs benedict'}]
text: Hi, my name Catharina and I am a brunch addict. I find every reason a good reason to go brunching.<br><br>...and I think Choupinette is awesome!<br><br>Reasons for giving it four stars:<br>- Their eggs benedict are consistently good. The poached eggs is one of the better I has in Singapore so far.<br>- Despite what previous reviews said, I like the service and good service is rare in Singapore: they are always super friendly and chatty. I must admit they sometimes forget things but they are always apologetic which I find more important.<br>- They are located walking distance from my home (ok, I realize that this is probably not applicable for most other people so not a real argument but it counts for me, ok?)<br><br>Reasons for not giving it five stars:<br>- It is not cheap, but I don&#39;t think it is overpriced either. You pay 25++ for eggs benedict, a coffee of your choice and a juice. Other places in Singapore charge similar prices though.<br>- The juices are not fresh, they are long life juices but I like that they offer a big selection.<br>- They do not serve cocktails and I think a brunch is not complete without a bloody mary or a mimosa but I guess that is aligned with their French concept, however eggs benedict is not really a French dish either.<br><br>This is one of the cases where I wish there was the possibility to give a half star, I would definitely give Choupinette four and a half stars!<br><br>Would I go back? Yes, already have been several times! <br><br>Recommended!

text: I heard about this place in reference to their eggs Benny - supposedly the best in Singapore. I thus ordered the smoked salmon eggs Benny while my eating mate got the regular eggs Benny. Hers were slightly better; while mine were average as far as eggs Benny go. I had a few issues with this place though; for one, the dishes are massively over-priced. In terms of value for money, you are better off going virtually anywhere else for this meal. We paid $56 for the two brunch sets. They come with a juice and either coffee, tea, or hot chocolate. I got lime and my friend got orange. Her&#39;s tasted suspiciously of the minute maid variety while my juice was terribly bitter.<br><br>They also brought out our hot chocolate at the exact time as our juice so it got cold. The eggs Benny are regular sized portions, but for $26 I expect the whole nine yards. We had to ask for more hollandaise sauce, and I was unimpressed by the amount of meat they served to my friend. <br><br>The seating is rather cramped, but the setting is still quaint. I liked the atmosphere but it certainly did not make up for the feeling of paying an arm and leg for only slightly above average fare. I will not be returning here on my own volition unless I am feeling particularly charitable!

Nothing really exceptional and rather expensive. <br><br>Don&#39;t get me wrong, there&#39;s nothing really bad about this place, but it&#39;s not quite value for money as the set brunches are rather costly at around S$26 for coffee, juice and eggs benedict. The portions were on the small side and while the eggs were done right, the sauce was pretty much average. The coffee also really wasn&#39;t up to scratch. Final price for 2 people with tax was around $60.<br><br>The interior was done to evoke the interior of a french cottage. Maybe it&#39;s just me, but the french folk music and accordion were getting on my nerves before the one hour mark. It was just too touristy and cliched. <br><br>My idea of french music is two guys wearing LED helmets before getting on stage and hitting the decks...<br><br>It&#39;s okay, but there are other better places to get your brunch fix.

text: I don&#39;t think this serves the best Eggs Benedict in Singapore. But to be fair, one man&#39;s meat is another&#39;s poison. <br><br>I tried both the Eggs Benedict and Eggs Royal. The Benedict did not impress me. The hollandaise sauce is so so only. The Royal is another story. The smoked salmon is nice when eaten with the bread and eggs, but too salty on its own. My photo of Eggs Benedict was labelled wrongly.<br><br>We sat by the side and the sun was glaring into our eyes at 8.30 am. There&#39;s no offer to pull the day curtains to block the sun rays.<br><br>We took away a quarter loaf of poilane bread. I bought it before from a shop in Dempsey Hill, was surprised they have it here too, but comes already sliced. After trying out the poilane bread, I noticed that it is not as fresh as the one I bought from Dempsey Hill.<br><br>The sourdough bread is... what can I say? My search for true sourdough bread in Singapore continues.

text: A small french restaurant with a wide variety of baked goods eg. Donuts brioche baguette crossaints whole wheat breads &amp; quiches etc. They offer excellent breakfast set menus that include excellent poached eggs paired with a a very crispy toast to match. Recommended for brunch or breakfast!

My husband and I ordered the bennies from here. Mine was with the salmon. His was with the ham. When the order came, we shared and compared the bennies. I prefer the salmon. He prefers the ham. <br><br>We visited this place because of all the reviews that said it has the best bennies in town. I can probably agree with that since all the eggs were nicely done. Based on the reviews, they probably are consistent with this. I can&#39;t say much until my next visit (if I do go back).<br><br>One reason that will make me think twice before going back is the price. It is a little bit too steep compared to other places that serve similar items.  My husband couldn&#39;t get over the fact that we need to order the &#39;set meal&#39; that comes with a juice (not freshly squeezed) and tea/coffee. The set costs about $26- and if i remember correctly, it&#39;s before GST and service. <br><br>The wait staff also forgot to bring us the juice so we ended up gulping some down before we left the place. Would have been better to serve the juice before the mains and end with coffee or something....

My default brunch place after church on Sundays when the dude wants to eat AM food and we&#39;re too lazy to be adventurous. <br><br>2 Croque Madames, one with a salad and one with pomme frites.<br><br>Enough said.<br><br>With the exception of one guy, the servers either have an attitude problem (&#34;What croque do you want?&#34; Me: Croque madame please. &#34;No what croque do you want??&#34; Me: a croque madame like I said...&#34;*rolls eyes*...chicken? ham? eggplant?&#34; Me: oh you meant what FILLING!&#34;) or are inexperienced. Your water glasses never get refilled unless you ask and the person managing the waiting list doesn&#39;t know how to manage it. <br><br>So this is a bit like your favorite grumpy hawker. Just eat your food, think zen and leave.

text: The food was alright. Decorations were nice. Very cozy, but a bit on the cramped side. Wait staff were not very attentive. Had to ask several times for the bill. A tad overrated as I&#39;ve heard from a number of sources about how great the eggs benedict were. They were just okay. Not sure this place is worth visiting.

text: Tucked away in a corner of the intersection between Bukit Timah Rd and Princess of Wales Rd sits a quaint café, Choupinette (that&#39;s &#39;sweetiepie&#39; in French).<br><br>Tiptoe pass the out-of-worldly decorations on the patio, and take a trip down the rabbit hole. Such unconventional interior design was carefully thought out and selected by owner cum Parisian art dealer Agnes Verrier, who switches up the furniture regularly to keep her sweetiepie relevant and trendy. <br><br>Amazing décor doesn&#39;t always translate to fantastic food. Well, the quickest way to vanquish (or confirm) doubts is to put the fork to the test.<br><br>Their Eggs Benedict&#39;s might come across as slightly expensive ($20+ with a fruit juice &amp; any hot drink), but if you haven&#39;t taken the clue from the disproportionate chairs and the avant garde décor, the servings here are fit for giants! <br><br>Served atop two hefty freshly toasted slices of bread, air-flown from France, are slices of honey-baked ham and sizably huge poached eggs, topped with generous servings of Hollandaise sauce. <br><br>Yes, Choupinette does offer their brunch fares everyday from 9 to 6 except Mondays, when they observe the same traditions as eateries in France, closing on the first day of the week. <br><br>Other mouthwatering offerings are their Chocolate Chouchou (their signature chocolate doughnut), as well as their Macaroons, which are handmade and polished to lofty French standards.

text: I heard about this place in reference to their eggs Benny - supposedly the best in Singapore. I thus ordered the smoked salmon eggs Benny while my eating mate got the regular eggs Benny. Hers were slightly better; while mine were average as far as eggs Benny go. I had a few issues with this place though; for one, the dishes are massively over-priced. In terms of value for money, you are better off going virtually anywhere else for this meal. We paid $56 for the two brunch sets. They come with a juice and either coffee, tea, or hot chocolate. I got lime and my friend got orange. Her&#39;s tasted suspiciously of the minute maid variety while my juice was terribly bitter.<br><br>They also brought out our hot chocolate at the exact time as our juice so it got cold. The eggs Benny are regular sized portions, but for $26 I expect the whole nine yards. We had to ask for more hollandaise sauce, and I was unimpressed by the amount of meat they served to my friend. <br><br>The seating is rather cramped, but the setting is still quaint. I liked the atmosphere but it certainly did not make up for the feeling of paying an arm and leg for only slightly above average fare. I will not be returning here on my own volition unless I am feeling particularly charitable!

text: I don&#39;t think this serves the best Eggs Benedict in Singapore. But to be fair, one man&#39;s meat is another&#39;s poison. <br><br>I tried both the Eggs Benedict and Eggs Royal. The Benedict did not impress me. The hollandaise sauce is so so only. The Royal is another story. The smoked salmon is nice when eaten with the bread and eggs, but too salty on its own. My photo of Eggs Benedict was labelled wrongly.<br><br>We sat by the side and the sun was glaring into our eyes at 8.30 am. There&#39;s no offer to pull the day curtains to block the sun rays.<br><br>We took away a quarter loaf of poilane bread. I bought it before from a shop in Dempsey Hill, was surprised they have it here too, but comes already sliced. After trying out the poilane bread, I noticed that it is not as fresh as the one I bought from Dempsey Hill.<br><br>The sourdough bread is... what can I say? My search for true sourdough bread in Singapore continues.

My default brunch place after church on Sundays when the dude wants to eat AM food and we&#39;re too lazy to be adventurous. <br><br>2 Croque Madames, one with a salad and one with pomme frites.<br><br>Enough said.<br><br>With the exception of one guy, the servers either have an attitude problem (&#34;What croque do you want?&#34; Me: Croque madame please. &#34;No what croque do you want??&#34; Me: a croque madame like I said...&#34;*rolls eyes*...chicken? ham? eggplant?&#34; Me: oh you meant what FILLING!&#34;) or are inexperienced. Your water glasses never get refilled unless you ask and the person managing the waiting list doesn&#39;t know how to manage it. <br><br>So this is a bit like your favorite grumpy hawker. Just eat your food, think zen and leave.

*Update*<br><br>Not sure how these updates work (it&#39;s my first) but I wanted to add that I went back to Choupinette and have confirmed that they now hold the title in Singapore as Best Eggs Benedict.  They have perfected the bread toasting and now offer more hollandaise sauce.  Well done!  You didn&#39;t earn another star rating, but you are on your way...

text: Really love the interior of this place, the row of good-looking bakery goodies really make the best backdrop of a nice quaint cafe.<br><br>Came here for brunch on a weekend and it wasn&#39;t as crowded as we thought it&#39;d be, or perhaps we were really early.<br><br>Had the poached eggs with salmon, my usual. It was great but I felt they were a little too heavy handed on the vinegar. Also had the creme brulee for dessert, not the best one I&#39;ve had. The almond croissant was delicious though, crisp and creamy flavourful.<br><br>The service here is satisfactory - was rudely acknowledged with a snooty head nod when I called for service.<br><br>Not sure I&#39;d come back here again for the food, but maybe only if I&#39;m in the area and craving for some good pastries.

text: Tucked away in a corner of the intersection between Bukit Timah Rd and Princess of Wales Rd sits a quaint café, Choupinette (that&#39;s &#39;sweetiepie&#39; in French).<br><br>Tiptoe pass the out-of-worldly decorations on the patio, and take a trip down the rabbit hole. Such unconventional interior design was carefully thought out and selected by owner cum Parisian art dealer Agnes Verrier, who switches up the furniture regularly to keep her sweetiepie relevant and trendy. <br><br>Amazing décor doesn&#39;t always translate to fantastic food. Well, the quickest way to vanquish (or confirm) doubts is to put the fork to the test.<br><br>Their Eggs Benedict&#39;s might come across as slightly expensive ($20+ with a fruit juice &amp; any hot drink), but if you haven&#39;t taken the clue from the disproportionate chairs and the avant garde décor, the servings here are fit for giants! <br><br>Served atop two hefty freshly toasted slices of bread, air-flown from France, are slices of honey-baked ham and sizably huge poached eggs, topped with generous servings of Hollandaise sauce. <br><br>Yes, Choupinette does offer their brunch fares everyday from 9 to 6 except Mondays, when they observe the same traditions as eateries in France, closing on the first day of the week. <br><br>Other mouthwatering offerings are their Chocolate Chouchou (their signature chocolate doughnut), as well as their Macaroons, which are handmade and polished to lofty French standards.

Very french and while it was over hyped back then when they were the more prominent french bakery open by a french, I have to say their Croque Madame and Danishes are still really good. What makes the sandwich this good I reckon is the creamy Bechamel Sauce and the perfectly set sunny side up. The ham is of good quality and it hardly disappoints. The staff aren&#39;t always the friendliest, but if you aren&#39;t just loitering this small shop and genuinely hoping to buy something, their attitudes are not all that harsh.<br><br>It is a nice place for brunch or just to pick up bakes for a picnic out. go early for the danish, my favourite, cherry danish, is always grabbed up by the time I roll out of bed and make my way down!

I&#39;ve had brunches at many places in Singapore, but nothing is quite charming like Choupinette. Tucked in a corner along Bukit Timah Road, this place got popular only very recently-up till a year ago, you could walk in on a Sunday and immediately sit down for a brunch. <br><br>The interior of the place is furnished in a homely, cozy fashion; a nice alternative to the unanimity of modern &#39;minimalist&#39; cafes. The menu is not extensive, but the food all taste pretty good. Having tried almost everything, my favorite still has to be the Eggs Benedict and Eggs Florentine. Unless you catch them on a super busy/off day (hardly), you should be able to expect nicely poached eggs, well seasoned salmon and wonderfully light, silky, buttery hollandaise sauce. If you wish to opt for something light, they also serve the fluffiest, flaky and flavorful croissants that go extremely well with tea or coffee.<br><br>But as with most things in the area, the food is pricey. I would say $50+ is considered average for a brunch for two. Whats comforting is that the food is almost always consistent, and I have never left disappointed.

text: Choupinette is possibly my top brunch place in Singapore. When I think about the perfect eggs benedict, this place comes to mind.<br><br>From the name you can tell that it is french. It&#39;s also quite an establishment along the Bukit Timah stretch that is just near my old junior college. I can&#39;t remember who told me about this place but I am glad I found out. It is a very small shop with seating of probably around 10 tables, so do be prepared to wait.<br><br>Their smoked salmon eggs benedict is really divine. They also have other delicious things on the menu, and what I liked is that you can order them together with a juice and a coffee. This is exactly how people in France/Switzerland have their breakfast. I love it! They also have a wall of breads for you to buy and take home. Baguette anyone?

The food here is honestly very good! I especially love their chicken rice. I dare say that theirs is much better than other run-of-the-mill chicken rice stalls all over this island. Their chicken is tender and flavourful, rice is tasty and soft, and the chicken is served over a layer of bean sprouts and cucumber slices. <br><br>They have this Chicken Rice Set that is $4.80. It comes with <br>- chicken<br>- blanched Vege with oyster sauce<br>- over a layer of bean sprouts &amp; cucumber slices<br>- rice on a separate plate<br>- small bowl of soup with 2 wantons<br><br>It&#39;s a very satisfying meal and I find it way value-for-money lor!<br><br>Hub likes their wanton Mee and my daughter likes their char siew rice. She commented that &#34;other people&#39;s char Siew rice no nice&#34;. And my help likes their breakfast fried white Beehoon. See, a little bit of something for everybody!

A little late here but WELCOME TO THE HOOD Firebake! Can I just say that Firebake Woodfired Bakehouse and Restaurant is my favorite dining spot in the East? I&#39;ve been waiting with bated breath ever since I heard that Konstantino (or Tino) is gonna open up a place to sell his kickass sourdough bread made. Plus this passionate man was building a full-scale woodfire oven just so that he can bake his breads in (how&#39;s that for passion)! Of course, you can expect that I made many rounds around their block so that I can be the first to check them out when they open.<br><br>Tino is truly an artisan who is devoted to his craft. From raw ingredients to firewood to water, everything is as non-processed, sustainable, and close to its natural state as possible. Organic flour, natural non-iodised and non-processed salt, water that has been treated using Firebake&#39;s elaborate Nordaq Fresh water filtration system, all these pure ingredients go into the making of a perfect loaf. <br>Of course, there&#39;s more to just freshly baked breads here. The menu here features contemporary dishes cooked with traditional European techniques, which complement and showcase the range of woodfire baked sourdough bread. <br><br>But first, bread! For first timers, the Firebake Bread Board with Greek extra virgin olive oil and the special Norwegian Roros Smor cultured butter ($10) is a great way to sample the different sourdoughs. There&#39;s the fluffy and chewy white which is perfect with the pate; a wholesome wholemeal with caraway which is lovely with the butter; a triple fermented rye for making a satisfying sandwich; and a fruit with plump sultanas and apricots that is perfect on its own or with more butter. The breads are also available in loaves ($8-13) and trust me they will be gone in no time.<br><br>You can make a meal out of just the bread, but make sure there&#39;s space for the rest! The 4-Spice Chicken Liver Pate ($12) is a smooth one, made with an equal ratio of butter. I love how it spreads beautifully on the white sourdough. It is also served with another slice of fruit loaf if you&#39;re into the sweet and savory combination.<br><br>Other refreshing appetizers that make perfect pairings with the breads include a Mediterranean style cold Smoked Eggplant ($15) with spiced hummus, tomato and Manchego.<br><br>The Heirloom Tomatoes ($17), provide bursts of flavor with smoked oil, feta, pickled cucumber and other aromatics. The mix is soaked overnight in tomato jus to enhance its flavor. Of course, sourdough croutons go into this one.<br><br>My favorite is the Wood-fired Pumpkin with Burrata ($16)! My mouth is watering just thinking about the creamy buffalo cheese with a sprinkle of pistachio dukkah, orange blossom, and a touch of molasses. In fact, I had this as my main on an occasion. <br><br>Favorite must-have main? The Cured Norwegian Salmon ($23). Love that pink in the center and how smoky it is. Plus that bread crust for added texture and some grassy sauteed leeks to go with. <br><br>The Norwegian Blue Mussels ($25) is cooked in Golden Ale (rather than wine), and flavored with chorizo and butter. I found this a bit bland and the only flavor was from the bits of chorizo (and only when i bit into them).<br><br>The Australian Prawn Capellini Aglio Olio with Sakura Ebi ($19) has an amazing aroma from the grilled prawns and prawn oil. I would love for punchier flavor (garlic and spice) but the pure seafood fragrance becomes more pronounced as you chew on it. Maybe give it a sprinkle of salt to enhance the dish a little.<br><br>The Grilled Pork Belly ($22) with garden vegetable broth is what i&#39;d reach for on a cold night. The vegetable broth is like a clear sweet minestrone, all naturally flavored by the pumpkin and celeriac. The sous-vide pork is given the cast iron grill treatment before being served and that crunchy skin is yums. The pork is kinda porky (if you know what i mean), so not all may take to this. <br><br>Another hit is the Rangers Valley Striploin of Wagyu grade A3! A 300gm slab for only $38? COUNT ME IN.<br><br>Firebake Bread and Butter pudding ($10) is so damn good please. Make sure you call and reserve it as they only serve 12 a night currently! This is made using their fruit loaf and soaked with creme anglais. It&#39;s a small bowl, but it goes a long way..<br><br>For a lighter but nevertheless sweet ending, go with the Moscato Poached Peach with a sourdough ice cream (SAY WERT) and rye chips ($12). The ice cream is a little like yogurt, with the nice pull to it.<br><br>Head on over to Firebake for the rustic dishes and lovely breads. They also serve a special blend of coffee from Jimmy Monkey, and there&#39;s also nitro-coffee available. For drinks of an alcoholic nature, there are affordable craft beers, and boutique wines to complement your meal. Alternatively, sip on some Nordaq Fresh water (still or sparkling) for $3/4 (free flow). Firebake is now open for dinner and they have just started a weekend brunch service too! GO NAOOOO!

text: We ordered a couple of mains recommended by the waitstaff. The Scottish mussels were tiny, but that aside, the taste was lacking. Quite flat and no punch. The saving grace was the house bread served along side. Hub&#39;s lamb fared better as it was quite flavorful. But the serving was also quite portioned and ended up going to have laksa afterwards.

text: The food was beautifully presented but flavor and textures very average. I had the chicken pie with gravy. Filling was average in taste and the gravy watery. The mash was the best thing on the plate. The eggplant is served cold and pretty tasteless. Apparently the bangers and mash are ok. The scones have to be the most perfectly round scones I&#39;ve ever seen. Texture wise very dense and heavy. I won&#39;t be in a hurry to come back.

text: Went in Saturday 17/03/18 at 12:35. This small restaurant was packed. I was given a seat in front of the cooking area and it was uncomfortably hot. <br><br>I ordered a bottle or sparkling water and a steak. The water arrived quickly but came with no ice and was only a little colder than room temperature.<br><br>My medium rare steak arrived after 25 minutes. It looked great but It was cold. <br><br>I can only assume the steak being cold was due to how busy the place is but is that really an excuse ?<br><br>Due to the issues listed above I will not return.

text: A pretty fancy bakery located in the heartland. Prices are not cheap but quite reasonable given the quality and taste. The most tempting items were the tarts. There&#39;s the dark chocolate version for people who are not into too much dairy ingredients. The chocolate taste was very rich. It is probably too sinful to polish off one by yourself so perhaps buy and share with friends. Haha.

An interesting selection of baked items, indelibly marred by truly dismal service. <br><br>This little bakery offers a selection of tasty looking baked treats - pies and cakes, quiches and specialty breads. <br><br>Unfortunately, staff just can&#39;t give two hoots about you. My wife and I stood around, trying to make sense of the curiously unlabeled mini breads (3 for $2.80, sweet deal but there&#39;s no sign to tell you), whilst staff pretended not to notice us. <br><br>Upon asking, a staff member grudgingly named the dizzying array of mini breads at a speed that defied normal human comprehension, and then stood, arms akimbo, impatiently waiting for us to decide. <br><br>You&#39;d be better off buying bread from the delightfully old school and significantly more helpful Balmoral Bakery on the opposite side.

text: As a resident in the area, one quickly notices when a business closes and a new one opens with a huge white wall scrawled with &#34; Drips&#34; and has industrial looking ovens inside. I checked out Drips on my way home today (not knowing anything about its predecessors in Tiong Bahru, so completely blind experience). <br><br>When we walked in the first thing that caught our eye was the fruit tarts, especially the macadamia tart since we had just had a tasty one on vacation and noted that few patisseries in Singapore work with those nuts. There were also some very crisp looking croissants, baguettes and brioche. So my first thought was ok, someone here must have trained somewhere because your average start up baker doesn&#39;t start off big with an expensive inventory of berry and nut pies that look THAT good.<br><br>My partner and I took home a chocolate tart and a blackberry almond tart. I thought the tart crust was great - firm and crumbly. The chocolate filling on the former didn&#39;t blow me away but then again I have a penchant for punchy desserts like the Cedele chocolate truffle. My partner thought his blackberry tart was moist, sweet and had &#34;great gelatin&#34; soaking up the berry run off well. The only downer was that the tart was skimpily dressed in berries but I guess you can&#39;t blame bakers for trying to manage inflation. Not a bad start but I&#39;d probably need to try the croissants and those great looking baguettes for a better judgement. Considering that there are now 4 very competitive bakeries in the neighborhood, it&#39;ll be interesting to see how tea time dollars are distributed.

text: I have lost count how many times I passed next to this store and the wonderful smell was always there!<br><br>I entered this store and I felt that I was in Disney, at least, my kind of Disney! with so many different tea flavors, teapots and cup of all sizes and forms.<br><br>I wish I could take them all.<br><br>The service was on point and their macaroons were extremely delicious, they practically melted in my mouth. All the flavors were screaming my name and the price was great; only $2.00 per piece.<br><br>Thank you!

text: Rate: 3.5/5 <br><br>Unexpectedly noticed this TWG shop during a work visit to the area and it was a pleasant surprise because I was looking for a nice treat. <br><br>I love their tea and so their macarons flavors were a must try. <br><br>Earl grey fortune and chocolate and Matcha were both tasty. A little soft for my taste compared to Lauderee which is a favorite of mine but I felt the flavors were great and it was the right ratio of filling to outside. <br><br>For $2 a macaron, not bad. I wish they didn&#39;t sell out of the Sakura macaron which is their limited edition flavor. <br><br>Service was fine as well.

text: Everything about Singapore was wonderful and an adventure.  The tea salon had lovely little tables and a chance to relax with a steaming cuppa tea!

This is the original, and my favorite TWG outlet. It&#39;s a small glass box in the lobby of Republic Plaza, generally quiet, even during the lunch hour rush. I really enjoy the tea-flavoured food (favorites being the smoked salmon, and the tea jelly that came with the scones). Service is attentive, without being obsequious. <br><br>I&#39;m not sure now that this is necessarily the best value for tea lovers, but it is a good place to go if you want to impress, or if you want a quiet hour or two to yourself in the early evening. Quiet is not something I can say about their other outlets.
