text: This place is really strange. And I don&#39;t just mean the food.<br><br>Start with the menu. The first page introduces the 2 chefs to you. but instead of telling you their food philosophy or style, is all about their experiences working in well-known places and how good they are. One chef is &#34;a gifted Chef&#34; and a &#34;prodigy of Celebrity Chef Sady Cerna&#34; (I think they meant protégé).<br><br>Furthermore, they have something really peculiar called &#34;enzymes&#34; which feature prominently in many of their desserts. I have no idea what their &#34;enzymes&#34; are, they probably aren&#39;t you know from biology (otherwise their desserts might decompose if kept overnight). There were samples of their &#34;enzymes&#34; on the table, and they looked like mostly-clear liquids (though one bottle had a lot of cloudy stuff at the bottom, making it look like what kombucha presumably looks like).<br><br>I ordered the ice cream (they were out of the &#34;enzyme&#34; creme brulees) and it was bad. I had 3 flavours: butterscotch, melon (with guava) and pineapple tart<br><br>The butterscotch &#34;ice cream&#34; was really butterscotch-flavoured heavy cream - it didn&#39;t have the taste and temperature of ice cream. The melon (with guava) ice cream had a noticeable amount of ice crystals in it. And the pineapple tart ice cream was very mild tasting.<br><br>Meanwhile, the ice cream was served with a really random assortment of toppings (apple, banana and nuts) and caramel sauce, which didn&#39;t harmonise well with the ice cream flavours.

text: Came here after eating pho and since I saw the reviews on Yelp, I decided to give it a try. While walking around Joo Chiat Road to see what kinds of desserts they serve around this area, I stumbled upon here after seeing the advertisement on Creme Brûlée Poire William.<br><br>My friend and I were the only ones in the cafe at that time and I was the only one having desserts. Looked over the menu to see what they offers. Was indecisive what to get - Creme brûlée or soufflé and ended up getting Creme Brûlée Poire William and a piece of chocolate macaroon (the only macaroon they served on Christmas Eve).<br><br>Creme brûlée Poire William was al-right. Though the name sounds fancy but in reality only the pear in the middle gave it an extra touch for the creme brûlée. The caramel wasn&#39;t thick enough and I think I tasted more of the pear than the creme brûlée itself.<br><br>Macaroon was interesting as the bottom part there wasn&#39;t really a shell that made it round. The bottom is similar texture like brownies. It was harder to bite than it looks. I was looking forward to having a Strawberry one but they were out. <br><br>Overall, it is definitely pricy in this dessert store. Should probably tried the souffle instead. Will probably try out the souffle the next time I&#39;m here.

text: Popped by for desserts after dinner. I went in without any expectations because it was a random choice but the gf said that the desserts aren&#39;t bad. <br><br>Small seating area with a small cake counter by the entrance. As we went in 30mins before closing (last order), I didn&#39;t pay much attention to the menu and simply opted to pick from the counter.<br><br>Green tea cake with azuki looked deep green and not too dry. After tasting, it wasn&#39;t too bad but it could be more moist if the cream were slightly wetter. It&#39;s not bad but kinda pales in comparison to the tiramisu.<br><br>I loved the tiramisu because it&#39;s so packed with rum and coffee! The lady&#39;s fingers were thoroughly soaked, just the way I liked it but the cream cheese weren&#39;t too watery and held the sponge layers up. It looks really unpretentious in the cheap plastic cup but woah it was fantastic. <br><br>Will certainly be back to try other desserts!

text: Generally good desserts. I would have give them 4 stars. Tried both the lava cake (bittersweet chocolate, but I would like there to be more gooey chocolate) and the expresso baliey&#39;s souffle (as light and fluffy as a good souffle should be)<br><br>However, minus half star for the pricing. It is over-priced for the area. It&#39;s $12 for the souffle, same price as Bistro Du Vin by the Les Amis Group and located in town.<br><br>Minus another half star for not serving tap/iced water, nor topping up hot water for our pot of tea. Not cool at all.

text: I was here on a quiet weekday afternoon with my friend, and decided to venture into this place for some dessert.<br>Admittedly, this place does serve some pretty upmarket and pricey desserts, but since we have not had &#34;nice desserts&#34; in a while, we decided to take a plunge. One of the stuff that we ordered was the Espresso Baileys Souffle, which was really nice. The coffee taste really came through and the dessert was really satisfying. Another dessert that we had was the cheesecake, which was very rich and creamy. This one was also another of our favorites! The cheesecake almost melts in your mouth.<br>All in all, a highly recommended place if you are willing to splurge a little on desserts.

This place has really good pastries and cakes. the souffle is really very good. I had the Soufflé with Crème Anglaise with a hint of Malibu, Which was quite simply the best souffle i have ever tried. Very light, and not too sweet. The thing simply melts in your mouth. <br>My friend had the sorbet which was a bit too sour for my liking. <br>Other cakes like the molten lava cake comes highly recommended.

text: Located some distance from the main street, the place was a far cry from the busy road. Here one could bring in pets into the cafe. One did not have to worry about own pets doing personal business around the place. The staffs were efficient to handle it easily. The menu covered quite a wide range from bento sets to western main courses to bingsu, as well as, items for doggies.<br><br>Duck Leg Confit Aglio Olio (S$18)<br>Spaghetti, Whole leg confit in its own fats topped, tossed with mushroom ragout and garlicky chilli oil <br>The pasta was garlicky with a slight spicy taste. A bit too oily at bottom. The duck leg looked quite dry but the meat was quite tender and not too salty.<br><br>Unagi Bento (S$23.90)<br>Japanese style unagi, basted and grilled with in-house yakiniku sauce and served with rice, tempura prawn &amp; miso soup<br>I was surprised that the plain looking rice tasted like the chicken rice version of rice. It was garlicky and oily with hints of ginger. The eel was tender and flavourful. The tempura prawn was more like ebi fry as it was covered with crumbs instead of batter. It was light and crispy. <br><br>Cornflake Chicken Cutlet (S$20)<br>All time favourite!<br>XXL juicy chicken thigh, coated with cornflake crumbs, honey mustard<br>Served with coleslaw and wedges <br>The serving was huge. Crunchy crispy crusted, inside the meat was thick and juicy.<br><br>Black Sesame Bingsu ($14)<br>Finely shaved ice, topped with black sesame powder, colorful mini mochi balls, and a scoop of  black sesame ice cream.<br>Unlike the commonly available versions in Singapore, the version served here was not overly sweet, with the tiny mochi balls providing a chewy texture.<br><br>If you are bringing your dogs over, don&#39;t forget to order items such as <br>Furkid&#39;s Minced Pupcake ($6.50/ chicken)<br>Contains carrot, oats, potato, egg<br><br>Furkid&#39;s Minced Pupcake ($7.50/ lamb)<br>Contains carrot, oats, potato, egg <br><br>for them.

text: It is a great spot for the furry friends to mingle but not the most ideal place for the humans (in terms of food). I came here twice to chill out with my sister and her dog.<br><br>If I am paying $18 for my Unagi rice, I expected the unagi to be covering at least half of the bowl on the surface. But my unagi was well hidden inside and let&#39;s just say that they are bits n pieces that combined to about an inch and a half size.<br><br>Carbonara pasta was merely edible after adding Tabasco sauce.<br><br>The cornflakes chicken waffle is a dish that is refreshing to me. However, the first few mouth were too overwhelming for me. The chicken is covered with lots of cornflakes. It&#39;s too oily for my palate. The sweet smelling aroma that ended with a bad taste in the mouth got me even more disappointed. Waffle at Prima deli is even way more delicious than this.<br><br>The seafood baked rice picture on the menu has salmon in it. We were deceived by it. When it came, it was practically baked rice with a few of mussels. And it tasted better with Tabasco.<br><br>Even the only presentable decent one was the chicken katsu rice. Even then the rice is not fragrant for that price that we pay for.<br><br>Try it for yourself and be your own judge. I have a high benchmark for food so I am definitely not going to come here for a meal. But i wouldn&#39;t mind a cup of drink to chill out watching our furry friend mingle. <br><br>Despite the taste of the food, this cafe makes a good chill out place with your furry friends. Especially on weekends, when there are more people in the cafe, it makes a good boundary where the furry friends can mingle.

text: yes, i have been dragging my feet with respect to review writing, mainly because yelp seems to have abandoned it&#39;s global domination plans and i was thus in mourning:(<br><br>the shutting down of it&#39;s CM program outside of north america can only mean a less attractive overseas yelp elite program.<br>no more CM also means no more ROTDs.<br>it remains to be seen how the elite program can keep it&#39;s overseas portals alive and well.<br><br>but i digress........<br><br>for those with roots well grounded in sg will know 85 redhill and it&#39;s humble hawker beginnings in the heartlands.<br>the last i checked 7 outlets have sprouted all across sg under the umbrella of a well run fei siong group.<br>authentic, nostalgic yet enjoyed by all in clean, comfortable surroundings and easily affordable.<br><br>no one makes fishballs like my mom does but alas it&#39;s a lot of work and mom can&#39;t make much these days.<br>so here i come on days of lull at mom&#39;s kitchen.<br><br>love the teochewness from the dumplings to the meat balls to the fish cakes and balls.<br>not as commercial tasting as others, with the right saltiness and bounce.<br>of course, the noodles here also can&#39;t really be replicated at home though some chefs do them better than others here.<br><br>the chilli way is also definitely better than the ketchup way!<br>if not, the soup version is a healthier alternative with a good handful of traditional tang chye to boot!<br>nothing more comforting............hmmmm maybe bak chor mee.<br><br>it can get rather crowded here, especially when you catch the sea of parents with tuition or enrichment going children in tow!<br>so timing is key.<br>being school holidays now, the traffic at united square is more sane.<br>so do take advantage and drop by for that special bowl and if it&#39;s a weekday, you get to buy a cup of coffee or tea for just 50 cents more!

text: I&#39;m a big Gong Cha fan and if I ever crave bubble tea, only Gong Cha will do it for me. The honey milk tea is my favourite and, deoending on how I feel that day, I will get it with either  pearls, brown crystal jelly or ai-yu jelly. <br><br>I tried getting pearls and brown crystal jelly together but i wouldnt recommend it. Too many flavours going on and your cup is basically only half filled with tea.<br><br>But yes, the brown crystal jelly is really quite something. YUM.

I&#39;ve been to Gong Cha many times while living in Hong Kong and have strongly missed milk tea since moving to Japan. So when I saw Gong Cha, I immediately decided I wanted to get my milk tea fix. Their menu is a lot smaller than the Gong Cha I frequent in HK.. Maybe 1/6 of the options. I ordered the Alisan Milk Tea which is Alisan tea with a heavy milk mixture on top.  The sticker on the old says you can sip the tea through the milk froth without a straw (nasty! Don&#39;t do that) or slurp tea followed by milk through the straw or stir it. I just let the milk slowly dissolve on its own and drink as normal.<br><br>Poor service under pressure during rush hours..to be honest it wasn&#39;t even that busy but I waited over 15 minutes for my drink. During that time, I saw them make 3 wrong orders. Even if I wasn&#39;t leaving Singapore today, I would honestly say I won&#39;t be back.. At least not to this location. The girls working were nice enough but didn&#39;t seem to know what they were doing and had poor communication skills.

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/FGG7cKZVKxlzny1LVzeg0g/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/gong-cha-singapore-2?reviewid=3Y0OwT2U_718MM4vO3Bq2w&select=FGG7cKZVKxlzny1LVzeg0g', 'altText': 'Photo of Gong Cha - Singapore, Singapore. Gong Cha Alisan milk tea', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Gong Cha Alisan milk tea'}]
text: I don&#39;t understand what the fuss is all about.  In Hong Kong i saw Gong Cha at a lot of locations, in Singapore i saw them and gave in.   I got the Milk tea alisan.  i have now idea what it is but it was flavorless to me.  It was watered down in my opinion.  It tasted like regular milk tea but with no sugar and more ice.   Maybe i ordered the wrong thing or maybe the waitresses wanted to get off right at  11p.m. but i was disappointed in my drink.   Though compared to the charlie brown cafe, the drink here was better.  Is it sad for me to say that i think that Quickly was even better?  Maybe a 2nd chance might be better.

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/P9Njtr0HoogLT5toBAeTAg/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/gong-cha-singapore-2?reviewid=RIShkybBbgOP706U2KADrg&select=P9Njtr0HoogLT5toBAeTAg', 'altText': 'Photo of Gong Cha - Singapore, Singapore', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': ''}]
text: When this place first opened, the lines went on forever. People were crazy about it - and when I tried it, I though, well, it does taste pretty good - but there are other places that sell pretty okay Bubble Tea too. It&#39;s good, but I always felt the lines were a little too crazy. You still get lines at their outlets - but it&#39;s not as insane as it used to be.<br><br>What I Love: Their Green Tea Bubble Tea is good. There are quite a few types you can get, quality of milk, level of sweetness - and for that, I love this place. You can make the type of Bubble Tea you want. It doesn&#39;t have to be sickly sweet. And it doesn&#39;t have to be too milky too. So, you&#39;re your own Bubble Tea creator.<br><br>What I Don&#39;t Love: The prices can get a little steep. It&#39;ll set you back $4-$5. Compared to other Bubble Tea places where you can get one for $2 or so.

I like the occasional bubble tea and Gong Cha does deliver up consistently decent cups. If you can help it though, you might want to skip this particular outlet which is always crowded with long snaking queues blocking the corridor. Not that it&#39;s particularly better or worse than other outlets, but it&#39;s probably the most crowded outlet all the time!

text: Nice place to chill and grab a cup of coffee if you need a break while shopping at the Raffles city mall. It has excellent views through the large glass wall of windows which overlooks the city. Drinks are pretty standard, nothing out of the ordinary though.

text: Great tasting Malaysian street food served in clean and cool Singaporean cafe. Try the Kuala Lumpur fried Hokkien Mee if you have never tried the dish.

userinfo: {'link': '/user_details?userid=Mj3SKlJ6EH_mwx3Waxds0w', 'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/photo/L4j10U3OQvsmCPzL8w3Sdw/60s.jpg', 'srcSet': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/photo/L4j10U3OQvsmCPzL8w3Sdw/ms.jpg 1.67x,https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/photo/L4j10U3OQvsmCPzL8w3Sdw/120s.jpg 2.00x,https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/photo/L4j10U3OQvsmCPzL8w3Sdw/90s.jpg 1.50x,https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/photo/L4j10U3OQvsmCPzL8w3Sdw/168s.jpg 2.80x,https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/photo/L4j10U3OQvsmCPzL8w3Sdw/180s.jpg 3.00x', 'markupDisplayName': 'Patrick L.', 'displayLocation': 'Singapore, Singapore', 'altText': 'Patrick L.', 'userUrl': '/user_details?userid=Mj3SKlJ6EH_mwx3Waxds0w', 'partnerAlias': None, 'friendCount': 20, 'photoCount': None, 'reviewCount': 1, 'eliteYear': None}
text: this is a good spot to buy their dim sum although the serving has reduced over the years. $2.50 per steam dish is considered cheaper than most area.  Most dishes are fresh and made in the store on the day.  Buns are tasty （my motherinlaw favourite) made in the traditional style thats a bit juicy.  Can get A bit messy as the juice will drip. yum.<br><br>Noodle store is made well, no complaints.<br>The mixed vegetable rice store is also good value for money this opens later, think around 11am<br><br>Service is so so but you dont really expect much from these type of outlets.<br><br>Good for morning breakfast, opens early around 7am.

This is a food court by block 345. It is definitely one of the best food court in the Clementi area. Majority of the stalls have very good local food, the ambiance is bright and clean and people there are always nice and friendly. What more can you ask for in a local food court?<br><br>My favorite is the mixed rice. Their food are displayed very attractively with lots of care. You can expect not to get leftover bits of fish or meat. Every piece of meat and fish are very well proportioned and definitely cooked with care. Their vegetables are also fresh looking and cooked perfectly with no excess oil. You won&#39;t get any overcooked mushy looking vegetables here. They also keep a pot of tasty curry or soy-based gravy at the end of the line if you like your rice with gravy. The staffs are also very friendly and patient while you make your choice among the large number of dishes they have there. Now, who says you can&#39;t eat healthy while eating out and eating cheap?? <br><br>Besides the mixed rice, this food court also has the local Western food chain - Char Grill Bar, Kimly Seafood, Jalan Besar Rojak/Popiah, a chicken and duck rice stall, a dim sum stall, two noodles stall and a pretty decent claypot rice. <br><br>If you are looking to go local, this is a highly recommended food court.

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/AyAnngKLwDZibEZkfOeWsA/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/ke-kou-duck-singapore?reviewid=SlDrL9s_fk6bJ6FW0H6X9w&select=AyAnngKLwDZibEZkfOeWsA', 'altText': 'Photo of Ke Kou Duck - Singapore, Singapore. Mix of Kuay Chap, braised duck and vegetable', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Mix of Kuay Chap, braised duck and vegetable'}]
text: They have one big round table that was good for my whole family. We order a mix-mess of stuff to share:<br>1) Braised Duck - good size serving, it looked like half duck and it&#39;s mostly boneless! Tasty and tender slices. Good!<br><br>2) Kuay Chap Platter - it&#39;s a nice spread of everything. Not bad tasting too.<br><br>3) Oyster Sauce Vege - average good.<br><br>4) Porridge - this is the one that I love. It&#39;s a thick goo of smooth porridge where they&#39;ll top a layer of their braised sauce over. The effect is a flavourful bowl of goodness I can happily eat in its own.<br><br>If anything at all, it&#39;s the porridge that will make me a willing return customer. As price-wise, it&#39;s not the cheapest meal around but with duck and Kuay chap options, it&#39;s always a little on the high side. Having said that, it&#39;s not ridiculously priced either. You need to check it out for yourself.

The ambiance, magnificent, the food delectable, the architecture, simply beautiful, the service, decent, and the table settings, spotless. You pretty much get the drift here, the Empire Cafe is close to perfection. The high ceilings and casual warm vibe welcomes you in and has you seated before your consciousness has caught up with your subconscious.<br><br>The prawn noodle soup was delicious, or maybe its the attractiveness of everything that is a driving influence. Be prepared to pay a little extra, it is close to $30 per dish, and though most of this restaurant is close to magnificent, it probably cannot justify for the food.   <br><br>This is located at the Raffles hotel, as you already have read, it maintains that class and touch of edge that is required of such a hotel.

text: Awful plastic-like food and amazingly slow service, even though we were there at around 2:30pm on a Saturday and it was only half-full.

userinfo: {'link': '/user_details?userid=m1JEc-0CcjUW8CteI3yvQg', 'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/assets/srv0/yelp_styleguide/514f6997a318/assets/img/default_avatars/user_60_square.png', 'srcSet': None, 'markupDisplayName': 'Gaurav B.', 'displayLocation': 'Southern Islands, Singapore, Singapore', 'altText': 'Gaurav B.', 'userUrl': '/user_details?userid=m1JEc-0CcjUW8CteI3yvQg', 'partnerAlias': None, 'friendCount': 0, 'photoCount': 5, 'reviewCount': 10, 'eliteYear': None}
text: Very poor service. Food was below average in terms of quality. We got drawn in as they had a vegetarian menu however the experience was no good. The food took forever to arrive and that too a long while apart. So we were served our tofu but no rice for 10 mins. Had to ask for water 3 times and finally had to tell the server that the service they were providing was very poor.

userinfo: {'link': '/user_details?userid=-B07E1F0tZ3HvgVdwJTj_A', 'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/assets/srv0/yelp_styleguide/514f6997a318/assets/img/default_avatars/user_60_square.png', 'srcSet': None, 'markupDisplayName': 'W D.', 'displayLocation': 'Singapore, Singapore', 'altText': 'W D.', 'userUrl': '/user_details?userid=-B07E1F0tZ3HvgVdwJTj_A', 'partnerAlias': None, 'friendCount': 1, 'photoCount': None, 'reviewCount': 10, 'eliteYear': None}
text: It&#39;s an Asian Cafe. And there&#39;s no such category here. Do you count fried rice with chicken chop as fusion?<br><br>The menu is quite extensive. And generally I do not have a good feeling about places with pages and pages of options. I feel confused and wonder: what is really good here?<br><br>You can get a meal here from about $12.<br><br>Nasi Goreng is spicy! That&#39;s a good in my book. (Hard Rock Cafe a few doors down also serves Nasi Goreng that isn&#39;t spicy but is not bad too.)<br><br>The shrimp dumpling noodle was okay. I had the dry version and I didn&#39;t like how it wasn&#39;t that dry, and had a kind of starchy sauce.<br><br>Good thing is all the options here are halal.<br><br>The bad thing is that in my noodles, I tasted the presence of MSG. It was also in the nasi goreng. Apparently, you can request no MSG, when I asked to confirm if they use MSG. I don&#39;t have a reaction to small amounts of MSG. But I did feel some effects of MSG on me on eating here. Not as bad as some reactions to some Chinese soups I&#39;ve had, but I certainly felt it.

This is the Bukit Timah branch. Located next to Coronation Plaza sling a row of multi storey terrace shophouses, there&#39;re plenty of parking kerb side along the front or behind within the housing estate. <br><br>I had the steak and fries, meat was tender and nicely done to a pink medium. Would have preferred fries to be string cut and crispy instead. There&#39;s a good selection of sandwiches and salads plus the usual cafe fare like fish and chips. Love that they serve fresh tea leaves for my pot of ginger mint tea.

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/vR2wdskyMDfVw7pW1IYn0g/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/naj-restaurant-bugis-singapore?reviewid=CJ8YZ8tFaF2ludS0WCmlvg&select=vR2wdskyMDfVw7pW1IYn0g', 'altText': 'Photo of Naj Restaurant Bugis - Singapore, Singapore', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': ''}]
text: To escape the human traffic jam on the other side of Bugis Junction, I take my meals at Naj Restaurant if I&#39;m in town.<br><br>This 24-hours coffee shop serve Bugis, Indian and Turkish food.The chicken kebab sandwich from the Turkish stall is accompanied with a small saucer of mayonnaise and tastes not bad. The grilled chicken is tender and succulent. Their teh tarik was nice too,  it came piping hot and is not too sweet. I had prata from their Indian stall for breakfast one time. The pratas came the way they ought to be - crispy, light and fluffy.<br><br>If you make the effort to walk a little further up from the MRT station to this shop, you&#39;ll get to enjoy lower prices than the other eateries in the area as well.

text: For breakfast, you have quite a variety of noodles and rice and varieties of pre-processed meat with eggs. The coffee is dark and rich and service is no nonsense. You also get to eat with local Singaporeans which is a treat.

Their milk bubble tea is pretty darn good - the pearls are a good texture and decently priced at $2.90. Get the 0% or &#34;less sugar (30%)&#34; option. Only wish adding pearls to other flavors (which is not the most extensive list) wasn&#39;t so expensive.

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/8me7tgaZWVYDLhqymHLibw/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/chatime-singapore-2?reviewid=s3PQVG9X3kuBT5AJcxKWWg&select=8me7tgaZWVYDLhqymHLibw', 'altText': 'Photo of Chatime - Singapore, Singapore', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': None}]
text: Between Koi, Gong Cha, and the occasional Share Tea run, I felt like I needed to shake up my bubble tea routine. (Am I allowed to proudly drink bubble tea at 25 going on 26?)<br><br>Earl grey milk tea with pearls and grass jelly ($4) -2.5 stars<br>I&#39;m spoiled by the other outlets. The grass jelly wasn&#39;t as smooth and the pearls got kind of gummy after chewing them for a bit. The tea also just wasn&#39;t as fragrant. Decent, and the menu seems interesting (the others don&#39;t have Earl Grey milk tea - I could&#39;ve sworn they did a long time ago!) but I&#39;d probably head to Gong Cha next door for the regular flavors.

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/t6qynzIpgMfp9KqvAQTXVQ/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/chatime-singapore-2?reviewid=xoTTY_6FjlOxkSjhbmkSkA&select=t6qynzIpgMfp9KqvAQTXVQ', 'altText': 'Photo of Chatime - Singapore, Singapore', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': None}]
text: Their roasted milk tea is thick but can still taste the tea! Order 0% sugar for a more healthier choice! Oh their pearls are chewy and sometimes better than goong cha&#39;s (IMO)

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/aPj2fP1lSb-W0UnSvZOQWg/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/73-hillcrest-singapore?reviewid=VdCNti34ThA2oUrTjMyTNw&select=aPj2fP1lSb-W0UnSvZOQWg', 'altText': 'Photo of 73 Hillcrest - Singapore, Singapore. Pork in Duxelle + brioche. Yum', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Pork in Duxelle + brioche. Yum'}]
text: It&#39;s time to let Singapore know about 73@Hillcrest. It was, and still is,  one of the hidden gems you will tell your friends about, but not post on social media, because you don&#39;t want to have to wait too long for a table. <br><br>But alas, they are too good to keep quiet about. Previously i had come only for dinner, but now they do weekend brunches too. For dinner, I&#39;d recommend the burgers, big portions, be warned. But my fav is the iberico pork ribs, so tasty, so tender. <br><br>Apparently, for weekday breakfast, they are converted into a coffee shop, so local kopi, chee cheong fun, chwee kuey, the works. They&#39;ve also recently had a prata store join them, which i sampled. Good prata, the crispy type. <br><br>For brunch, i had the pork in Duxelle + brioche. Let&#39;s just say i wiped the plate clean. Very clean. They probably didn&#39;t have to wash it. But I&#39;m sure they did.  <br><br>If there&#39;s anything to complain about, it&#39;s probably the coffee. On the weekends, no kopi, only espresso type coffee, which can always be tricky. Need a good barista for that. Not any issue for me at dinner i just drink beers, so give stars at dinner time. For breakfast, still 4.5 stars, the half  taken off for the coffee quality.

userinfo: {'link': '/user_details?userid=c9NyBe4SaxqWQJwrHaiSJg', 'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/assets/srv0/yelp_styleguide/514f6997a318/assets/img/default_avatars/user_60_square.png', 'srcSet': None, 'markupDisplayName': 'Poh K.', 'displayLocation': 'Bukit Timah, Singapore, Singapore', 'altText': 'Poh K.', 'userUrl': '/user_details?userid=c9NyBe4SaxqWQJwrHaiSJg', 'partnerAlias': None, 'friendCount': 0, 'photoCount': None, 'reviewCount': 1, 'eliteYear': None}
text: I just moved into the neighbourhood and this bistro was highly recommended by my neighbours.  Here is where my rant starts, the confusion and mess on the weekends for their coffeeshop/bistro concept was a total disaster. I had no idea if someone would sit me down, so I just sat at a table (outdoor area) and a coffee shop patron asked me not to sit there because it was reserved for his friends. Swiftly, there were two young male staff who came to help out and gave me the menu and explained everything (how their shop concept works especially on weekends). The menu was also very disorganised, I had to change my order so many times because there were so many &#34;weekday specials&#34;, &#34;weekend specials&#34;, &#34;weekend brunch specials&#34;, &#34;student specials&#34;, &#34;japanese specials&#34; along with a separate japanese menu, easily 100-150 items on the 2-paged main menu + separate 2-paged drinks menu + separate 2-paged japanese menu, WAH LAO just make it an easy 1-page menu! Luckily the one staff as mentioned before (sorry did not get their names) slowly went through the menus and explained/recommended me some items.<br><br>Having an open concept kitchen, customers can walk through and look at the kitchen operations whilst they are working. Food handlers were not wearing gloves and kitchen was in a unhygienic state during lunch service (if you want to do stuff dirty then don&#39;t allow customers to walk through). When I left the bistro via the back door, food were left all around the back fridges&#39; area! Raw pork, raw beef, fresh vegetables and drinks were all together, on the FLOOR, eeeeewwwww! Uncle at noodle stall was digging his nose and cooking the noodles, not to mention he&#39;s so rude! Toilet was in a horrible state, my son could not use the male cubicle because the light was blown and it will be absolutely in darkness when he went in. Staff told me the light has already not been working for 2 weeks and the management refuses to fix it (whattttttttttt).<br><br>However, I have to mention that the menu was very affordable amongst the whole row of restaurants and the food is okay, not excellent but great for the price. <br><br>I can recommend: 73 Ribs - Succulent, fall off the bone, tender.<br>Fish and Chips - Tastes like good ol&#39; beer battered fish and good slaw.<br>Wild Mushroom Chicken - The sauce was meh but the chicken was moist.<br><br>Highly not recommended: <br>73 Burger - The tempura was too greasy, fries on this plate had no salt and I had to ask for salt myself (the fries on other plates were good)<br>Aglio Olio - It&#39;s a mushroom, bacon, chili flakes locally inspired noodle dish. No seasoning too. Don&#39;t call it an aglio olio if it&#39;s not.<br>Flat white - It&#39;s so foamy even when I ordered it flat. <br><br>Conclusion: <br>Decent food 2.5/5 (pass)<br>Good service 3/5<br>Disgusting hygiene 0/5<br>Bad menu 0/5<br>Bad coffeeshop/bistro concept 0/5<br><br>Will not come back again until they make clear their operation concept, menu and the HYGIENE! When you are in a location like Greenwood/Hillcrest, there are so many better restaurants next door!

Nice place to hang out for those who enjoy instagram worthy food. But the taste and the price doesn&#39;t really quite measure up as much to the presentation. <br><br>Generally wouldn&#39;t be my natural choice to visit but it&#39;s nice to hang out if you are willing to splurge a little and take some nice photos with your food to boost some social media likes. <br><br>They do come up with new items regularly so for those who likes gimmicky food, do consider them!

Cute concept, but absolutely the slowest restaurant that I can recall ever going to. After sitting menu down for 10 minutes, searching the internet, and finally just staring at the waiter.. I finally got waited on.  I drank my whole &#34;dirty chocolate&#34; (which was very tasty) and ordered a coffee, and waited again. Because of extended time for it to come, I inquired about, as well as why food had not come. I was told kitchen had orders before mine and had not come to my order. While I believe that&#39;s true, if the ratio of employees to seated customers is 1:3, they can&#39;t make much money. The coffee, I don&#39;t think was ever ordered, but they gave complimentary because of the wait. <br><br>Overall, food was good but service was professional but way too slow for me to return again, except for a takeout beverage.

text: Oink Don $29.00++ *Highly Recommended*<br>We highly recommend the Oink Don, if you&#39;re very hungry, craving for quality pork and love carbs! Starting from the top, take your pick on Deep Fried Pork Cutlet w/bone, Grilled Pork Chop, Roasted Pork Belly and Pull Pork Carnita. There&#39;s so much meat here, I think an entire piglet died for this main course! In all seriousness, the meat were very flavourful, juicy, not one molecule of the variety of meats here was dry. Add on the black pepper cream sauce and every item has a tinge of smooth and delicate peppery flavor.<br><br>Check out the thick layer of pulled pork carnita covering the fluffy egg and Sambal Fried Rice w/ Black Pepper Cream and Bacon! The pulled pork is the most tender, most juicy pulled pork ever, definitely took alot of time to slow cook this to perfection! Yea Baby!<br><br>Sea Don $35.00++  *Highly Recommended*<br>This Sea Don comes with a spectacular sight of a Whole Lobster, King Salmon, Squid set above another &#34;treasure&#34;, the Seafood Fried Rice w/ Garlic Butter Sauce, Prawns, Scallops, Octopus, Egg. I&#39;ll be very honest with you, the seafood fried rice is the best fried rice I have ever tasted. The rice itself has a distinct &#34;wok-hei&#34;, and the rice absorbed all the sweetness from the variety of seafood cooked altogether. The crunchy prawns embedded in the rice also provide a nice bite in between the soft and pillowy rice.<br><br>Enough about the rice? I could go on for days about the yummy seafood rice, but! The highlight of this dish, the Whole Lobster, showcases the high quality grade ingredients used at the Benjamins. The lobster has a sweet juice crunch and it&#39;s easily removed from the shell, a good sign of the meat being fresh. The salmon fillet is huge, it&#39;s actually longer than the bowl itself!<br><br>Molten Lava Cheese Burger $25.00++<br><br>Probably the next new hyper on social media is this Molten Lava Cheese Burger, served with a Choice of Fried Chicken Cutlet, Soft Shell Crabs, Beef. The soft shell crab here is also huge, I&#39;m starting to realize that everything served here at The Benjamins is on the generous side! The cheese comes oozing on and it&#39;s great as a dipping sauce for the potato tater tots.<br><br>Pizza Burger $28.00++ *Highly Recommended*<br>Brand new on the menu is the Pizza Burger. The Benjamins takes pride in making their ingredients in-house, such as this Beef Patty, Pepperoni, served with a fusion of Black Olives, Grilled Artichoke, Spinach, Monterey Jack, Mild Cheddar. The minced beef patty has a good mix of meat, breadcrumbs, fats and seasoning making it extremely delicious and addictive. This meat patty looks to be approx 250grams.<br><br>Overall : The Benjamin&#39;s continue to amaze our tastebuds and eyes with their innovative creations. Definitely try out the Sea Don, Oink Don and their smoothies, I&#39;m quite confident you cannot find anything quite like these items in any other eatery in Singapore.

text: I came in because I&#39;ve always seen the oversized milkshakes featured on Instagram. I wanted to see the milkshakes myself so my friend and I decided to try the place out. Right when you walk into the mall, The Benjamin is immediately to your right. We shared between two milkshakes (Fairy Pebbles and Charm My Shake) and they were $16 each. Honestly, I don&#39;t think people even finish the milkshakes because my friend and I barely touched it. There was just so much going on and we basically came for the picture. Both milkshakes tasted the same and I think just the flavor of cereal and some of the topping ingredients changed.

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/9kz7XWMMgpGy8Zj3PjXwrg/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/the-benjamins-singapore?reviewid=8yXRGIwTpxcAdfN4rV1HMA&select=9kz7XWMMgpGy8Zj3PjXwrg', 'altText': 'Photo of The Benjamins - Singapore, Singapore', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': None}]
text: I popped by here on a Sunday afternoon for a bombastic milkshake. <br><br>While I found our milkshake really quite pretty (and pricey!), taste-wise it was nothing special. Basically a plain vanilla milkshake with various biscuits and candy floss put on top. I would have loved it if the shake itself actually tasted good. <br><br>Meh.

Had the creamy mushroom ciabatta for lunch today, which was delicious. Served with a side salad and fries, it was quite filling for lunch, but my boyfriend and I also split the sautéed vegetables. They were carrots, snow peas, asparagus, mushrooms and green beans in garlicky oil - lots of flavor and delicious too!<br><br>Didn&#39;t try the milkshakes but will definitely be back. They look so elaborate with pretzels, cookies, ice cream, etc. coming out the top!<br><br>Nice atmosphere, really cute decor, but the service was a bit slow even though the restaurant was less than half full.

I like the food here.  It takes a while to be served, but I think their Italian food quality is quite good.  Try the pasta.<br>一見単なるカフェにしか見えませんが、きちんとメニューには料理があります。イタリアンが多いですが、トマトパスタも悪くないですし、日本人的にはアリかと。料理が出てくるまで時間がかかるのが玉に瑕。<br>ちょっぴり高めかなと思う部分はありますが、まともなのでまたいつか行きます。2015/11<br>p.s. 同じビルに出来たjamiesもそろそろ試したいところ。空いてきたかな？

text: Came here on July 3rd, the same day as their re-opening day after renovation. I had waffle with bacon and scrambled egg (S$18), which is not bad overall- taste wise. The texture of the scramble egg is pretty good- it was fluffy, but I just wished they give some herb or whatever into it to enhance the flavor cos it turned out pretty plain to me. For the Bacon &amp; Waffle, we all know how easy to prepare them.. but even the waffle was just mediocre. Honestly for that price range for such a simple dish, I expected much more. <br><br>The same thing with the seafood pasta (S$23). It was just ok only. I&#39;ve had better. The texture of the pasta is a bit wrong - like it was over cooked. Pasta is the easiest dish to make with high margin. I&#39;m sure that I don&#39;t ask to much if at least I want my pasta to be al dente. I could name some cafe that offers brunch places at a lower price and higher standard of food. <br><br>On the plus side, this place offers free wifi, comfortable seatings with elegant &amp; relaxing ambiance.

text: [1] Portobello Fritters $12.90<br><br>- We all knew good food coming before it reaches our table. All thanks to the fragrance from the truffle oil. Portobello fritters were so crispy, drizzled with truffle oil on the outside and best of all, it wasn&#39;t soaked with oil when we bite our way through it!! So good I think I could have a few servings on my own.<br><br>[2] Sambal Sotong $16.90<br><br>- These 2 sea creatures were presented to us in a nice char. &#34;Almost&#34; grilled to perfection but I thought cooking time could be a little shorter to keep the tenderness of the flesh. The flesh itself tasted slight garlicky and goes really well together with the sambal chilli.<br><br>[3] Salted Egg Yolk Calamari $13.90<br><br>- Salted Egg Yolk food items wasn&#39;t new to any one of us here, it has been trending for more than a year already. What made LHOD&#39;s dish stood out? Their version of salted egg yolk sauce was thick, grainy with salted egg bits and not salty. The proportions of salted egg, curry leaves and chilli were perfect where each individual ingredients did not overshine each other. Great on these breaded calamari! LHOD could consider using this sauce to create new dishes too.<br><br>[4] Prawn Paste Chicken Wings (4pcs) $15.90<br><br>- Look at these wings!! Chicken wings were huge and juicy within. Skin deep fried till super crispy, lightly marinated with prawn paste and a dash of herbs. A pity the marinade did not penetrate into the meat completely otherwise they would have tasted even better.<br><br>[5] Drinks:<br>[a] Iced Chocolate $7.90<br>- My kind of drink but it wasn&#39;t chocolatey enough for me. I preferred thicker sinful ones.<br><br>[b] Green Garden Fruit Fizzies $8.90<br>[c] Pink Passion Fruit Fizzies $8.90<br>[d] Lavender Blue Fruit Fizzies $8.90<br>[e] Sunny Day Fruit Fizzies $8.90<br><br>- These non-alcoholic thirst quenchers were more interesting. Pretty colors and interesting flavours made us couldnt make up our mind which to try first. We ordered the 4 most popular ones to try out. My favorite was the Pink Passion Fruit Fizzies. I love slight sourish drinks as it gave me more appetite to eat more!<br><br>Mains:<br>[6] Big Breakfast $16.90<br><br>- For this price we paying, portion served was really generous. Scrambled egg was done pretty well, just the way I love my eggs to be. The spinach and mushrooms were a little salty but they definitely complement the bread well. Served all day!<br><br>[7] Seabass wif Salad $34.90<br><br>- Fish meat was firm and succulent. Pretty to my eyes and tasty on my palate. The chef made the pan-fried potato balls looked like scallops, Genius! My 2nd most loved mains for the night.<br><br>[8] Pork Ribs wif Salad $32.90<br><br>- Whenever I order pork ribs, I&#39;m most concerned with the tenderness of the meat and the sweetness level of the marinates. Lucky this plate didn&#39;t disappoint me. The marinates wasn&#39;t overly sweet and carried off a smokey aftertaste. The meat fell off bones easily, tender and nice.<br><br>[9] Spaghetti Laksa Prawns $26.90<br><br>- Tadahhhh.. My vote goes to this spaghetti laksa prawns for best dish tonight. Look at the huge prawns we were given! Very fresh and crunchy. The spaghetti texture was al dente and every mouthful you could taste the spiciness of the sauce. I love the fiery kick from the laksa sauce, but I could take something spicier. If only the sourish from the tomato base could reduce, I believe the laksa taste would outstand more. Nevertheless, this was still my top choice :)<br><br>[10] Chilli Crab Bun $19.90<br><br>- Who don&#39;t love crabs? Everyone on this table loved them! Chunks and chunks of generous crabmeat were made into patties and served to us in a delicious bun made in-house. Look at the Chilli crab drizzle, so generous and everything overflows! We almost licked up the plate *haha*<br><br>[11] Pulled Pork Sandwich $17.90<br><br>- If we compared this pulled pork sandwich with the chilli crab bun, the former crabby was so much better. Pulled pork was too dry and tough for my liking. Overall lacked the juiciness of meat which I found it a pity. <br><br>Desserts:<br>[12] Sticky Date Pudding wif Vanilla Ice Cream $13.90<br><br>- Sticky date pudding was so good, we wiped it out in seconds. Every mouthful you can taste the fragrance of dates. Beware: It could get very sweet if you pair with the bananas given but we gals dun care! Whack!!<br><br>[13] Creme Brulee $10.90<br><br>- Tofu-liked vanilla custard base was smooth and slippery, eventually disappeared after touching our tongues. The torched sugar crust gave it more flavour. I would say it&#39;s a common item which can do with or without.<br><br>[14] Vanilla Bloom Pot $6.90<br>[15] Pandan Rose Bloom Pot $6.90<br>- These mini pots piped so beautifully with flower petals attracted us at first sight! Almost too pretty to eat them. Vanilla bloom pot tasted less sweet with a very nice milky flavour and fluffy sponge cake below. As for Pandan Rose, the frosting was too sweet although it smells good. But I couldn&#39;t finish the first mouthful. The Pandan cake below was slightly dense too. This flavour definitely for the sweet toothies only.

text: Little House of Dreams has been through a big revamp and now sits comfortably beside Ben &amp; Jerry&#39;s ice cream. The decor is very pretty, chic and cosy. The warm, light colours are used for the furniture and walls. There&#39;s even a play corner for kids to hang out, while parents watch them and have some savoury mains, sides, cakes or ice cream and waffles from Ben &amp; Jerry&#39;s. I love that you can order items from both places and dine in a single location.<br><br>Sambal Sotong $16.90<br>Beautifully plated, this was an interesting menu item that you don&#39;t normally get to see in cafes. The squid itself had a chewy texture with a characteristic earthly flavour. The squid also maintained a slightly charred aftertaste. As I&#39;m a weakling when it comes to spicy food, I did not try the sambal sauce.<br><br>Prawn Paste Chicken Wings (4 pcs) $15.90<br><br>We were expecting drumlets and winglets but we were surprised to see 4 full chicken wings in a basket. On first impression, the prawn paste aroma was evident. But upon the chicken wings cooling down to  a temperature which we could consume it at, the prawn paste taste was nowhere to be found. The skin was however, superbly crispy and the meat was juicy without being oily. No need to rush to the washroom to wash your hands after consuming this chicken wings!<br><br>3. Salted Egg Yolk Calamari $13.90 *Highly Recommended*<br><br>I loved salted egg and I love calamari, hence this is one of my highly recommended dishes to try at Little House of dreams. The salted egg yolk sauce was creamy and yet slightly grainy and lumpy, coupled with a distinct aromatic flavour that had a mild salty-spicy aftertaste. I just couldn&#39;t stop munching on these! Even though, these calamari rings sat for awhile, during the photoshoot, despite being being soggy, the presence of the salted egg still stood out clearly.<br><br>6. Ribeye Steak with Salad $39.90<br><br>I usually liked my steak medium, but this was medium-well and I still liked it. The steak was juicy and tender and together with the provided steak sauce, this was a  very appetizing. The salad had little sliced baby potatoes which I felt was an interesting way to present carbs on a plate, without making the plate look cluttered with carbs.<br><br>8. Pork Ribs with Salad $34.90<br><br>The pork ribs were thick, meaty and succulent. The meat was tasty but just like the pulled pork, it could&#39;ve been a bit more tender. The sauce was sweet and tangy and perfectly marinated deep into the meat.<br><br>9. Spaghetti Laksa Prawns $26.90<br><br>Simple ingredients and yet exploding with flavours.  The prawns were huge but the gradual follow up with the spicy intensity didn&#39;t allow me to taste the prawns.<br><br>10. Chilli Crab Bun $19.90 *Highly Recommended*<br><br>The chilli crab patty was made with real crab meat, the sauce itself wasn&#39;t spicy and kids could probably eat this too! The chilli crab bun was certainly a satisfying and enjoyable one. The bun was toasted till the ends of the bun was crisp and pillowy in the center. The chilli crab sauce topped the crab patty with a sweet and tangy taste contributing to a shiok and yummy satisfaction level.  The crab patty was also well marinated, tender, and flavourful.<br><br>14. Vanilla Bloom Pot $6.90 *Highly Recommended*<br><br>This was so pretty! So much effort is made by Little House of Dreams to give you the unique dessert experience. This is actually a cupcake dressed up as a potted plant. The creme on top, was alright in sweetness factor. The cupcake on the inside was on the drier side but tasted great, when combined with the creme. I&#39;ll probably be craving for this in the d<br><br>18. Snickers Cheesecake $7.90 *Highly Recommended*<br><br>The owners mentioned that if you like nuts, or snickers, you&#39;ll be a fan of this cheesecake. That was me and I knew immediately that I had to try this. Indeed, this cheesecake was filled with nuts, caramel, chocolate and a chocolate cookie handmade crust. The cheesecake was dense, but not overly sweet. I wasn&#39;t  expecting this to be spectacular but it sure was!<br><br>19. Lavender Blue Fruit Fizzies $8.90<br><br>All the fruit fizzies are ingeniously thought out. My Lavender Blue Fruit Fizzie was made with lavender and little iced cubes with real strawberries on the inside.

text: Little House of Dreams is a homegrown bakery and one-stop party decorations specialist that offers bespoke cakes, cookies, cake-in-a-jar, freshly baked goods, party supplies, party decorations and even party props rentals.<br><br>They have experienced party stylists to create bespoke dessert tables to suit any theme and occasions such as weddings, baby showers, parties, corporate functions and photo shoots.<br><br>Little House of Dreams also conduct baking workshops at their baking studios or at a location convenient for the customers. Their sister shop, Dreams and Confetti, offers a specially curated selection of party supplies, imported tableware, pretty cake stands from USA, candies, trinkets, gifts and much more.<br><br>Little House of Dreams has recently launched a new savoury food menu in December 2015 which features burgers, pastas, pizzas, salads, sides and sweet treats. One noteworthy point is that the dough for the burgers, pizzas and pasta are all hand made in-house at the Little House of Dreams.<br><br>REVIEW<br><br>The hot foods here are all prepared by their talented pastry chefs. As the Little House of Dreams&#39; forte is in baking and bespoke dessert creations, we find that their savoury food items would require a little more fine tuning.<br><br>Being a fairly new establishment, the Little House of Dreams has great potential for growth, with their great desserts, cosy ambience and friendly service with a personal touch, and I will be happy to return to try their new offerings.

Cute place, with pretty desserts but at relatively higher prices (well.. it is at Dempsey). We tried the lemon meringue tart, yummy but $9 a pop!! Perhaps their focus is more on their desserts, their savory menu is really lacking in quality. Service was bad too. Don&#39;t think it&#39;s worth a second visit. <br><br>Came here on a Friday morning and it was relatively empty. But was surprised that service was still extremely slow. We seated ourselves, the server saw us but did not even approach us and just stood around. We asked for information regarding several things (menu, availabilities etc.), and she had to go ask someone else multiple times - she didn&#39;t seem to know what&#39;s going on. <br><br>They do not have physical menus, everything is on the iPad. Our party of 4 had to squeeze together to browse a small screen. Their digital menu seems pretty poorly planned out too - they only have brunch items available on weekends and public holidays, but it was featured under their &#34;Popular&#34; section which didn&#39;t indicate the availability of the items. New items that were featured on their little posters were not on the iPad and, quote the server, we were supposed to &#34;just order from the iPad&#34;, but how?<br><br>Food is just ok. They arrived way too slowly... We got appetizers, salad and main dishes. The main dishes came first. We didn&#39;t understand why our main dishes came out before the appetizers, and the salad was the last to arrive.<br><br>Seems like a cute place to have brunch at, and a nice place to hang after work as it seems like they have live music occasionally. But if the service was already so bad when it wasn&#39;t very crowded, can&#39;t imagine when it is.

text: Strange place with many apparent contradictions. Cute pink, Tiffany-blue and white décor, adjacent to a Ben&amp;Jerry&#39;s counter - as if to appeal to an adolescent audience. Yet, the alcohol list is almost as long as the limited food menu. We didn&#39;t try the bakery goods, but the unimaginative savoury dishes range from bad to barely acceptable. For lunch, the kitchen only opens at 12:30 pm. With so many alternatives in the Dempsey area, why bother? And why do the owners wastefully put an iPad at every table, when it says &#34;For Staff Use only&#34;. Incidentally, the staff are very friendly when they appear, but alas they are largely absent. Pricey for what it is - without the Entertainer offer, would be pretty bad value.

Baileys custard bun - 3.5 stars<br>Interesting having alcohol in your custard. It was tasty though.<br><br>Apple bun - 3.5 stars<br>I liked the apple and raisin filling, though the day after the bread tasted a little off.

text: I came here on a Tuesday for Afternoon Tea. This services offered between three and 5 o&#39;clock. My suggestion would be to get here before 15:00 as people tend to queue fairly early. Not sure why because there is plenty of seating for all who have made proper reservations.<br><br>This is a fabulous affair; one not to be missed. There is no shortage of afternoon tea offered in Singapore, however, at approximately US $55, afternoon tea at the famous raffles hotel is quintessential Singapore. I enjoyed afternoon tea on several days throughout my visit however, many places fell short. This was my absolute favorite afternoon tea experience.<br><br>Once seated, you are greeted by a friendly serve her offering you an assortment of tease and coffee. They bring in assortment of pastries and savory items such as cucumber tea cakes and tartlets to your table. Then, as if this weren&#39;t enough, you are offered the opportunity to partake in the buffet which includes everything from dim sum, fruit cakes, a variety of scones, fruit and bread pudding with an absolutely wonderful vanilla sauce. <br><br>I went with the English breakfast tea so strong and my cattle was never left empty.<br><br>The only downside is that you are not able to take your leftovers with you. I was disturbed at this is customary in Singapore due to Government health related regulations. While understandable, it is never the less quite a bummer. <br><br>I will definitely make reservations for afternoon tea in the Tiffin room again.

Tiffin room is a classic case of style over substance. The setting, ambience and service are excellent, as is expected of a restaurant in the iconic Raffles hotel (the birthplace of the Singapore sling). But the food sadly misses the mark. We had the &#34;tiffin&#34; special where the dishes are served in indian &#34;tiffin&#34; boxes. The food is very unremarkable, missing the typical flavors Indian food is so known for. For the prices they are charging, I would have hoped for a bolder take on flavors. It could be they are not catering to the usual Indian palate, but I find that very off putting. Why claim to be an Indian restaurant when even the simplest of Indian dishes are not authentic. So yes, if you want &#34;toned down&#34; Indian food in a plush ambience, go for it, but for actual Indian flavors and variety go elsewhere, both your stomach and wallet will be happier.

text: First time to the tiffin room for their Indian buffet lunch. It&#39;s $68++ and honestly I didn&#39;t think it was worth it. The food was tasty but very much toned down to suit western palates. The spread was not particularly varied though there&#39;s still sufficient representation for each section (salads, appetizers, hot, desserts). There was a section for non Indian food lovers, smoked salmon, cheeses etc. <br><br>What&#39;s unique? During this Christmas season, there was special honey baked ham and turkey carving stations and log cakes as well.<br><br>Other positive points: Fresh garlic and butter naan were served freshly baked to the table automatically. They were served with a minced lamb dip.  The waiter also comes along twice with daily specials. One was like a pulled lamb and the other was baked mushrooms with cheese. The mushrooms were the bomb!<br><br>Lastly, the raisin cardamom kulfi was the bomb! A little too sweet but the flavor was to die for!

text: I really want to love this place, we were excited and reserved a week prior our arrival to singapore, tucked lovely inside iconic Raffle hotel, crispy white decor, tall ceilings w lot of natural lights, but overall experience had been mediocre, it felt more of a tourist trap than a place that we can really enjoy the tea w dessert pairings! There was dimsum when we visited, kinda weird combination, none of the dimsums stand out anyways, the waiter and bus boys were friendly, but at the same time they were tense covering numerous tables and trying to please and help w photo taking for each tables to please their customers, or at least they tried. What really turned me off was the quality of tea and pastries, the selection of green teas were limited, black tea was subpar in quality, macaroons were not part of the pastries,  I felt like for the amount we were paying per person, at least we deserve some quality tea and pastries.

text: We decided that the best way to try the Tiffin Room would be a high tea, which I must say was very well done and included a couple of things to set it apart from the crowd.<br><br>The staff were perhaps somewhat surprisingly very friendly, not stuffy, we saw them taking photos for groups and even allowing people to chose when they were served, so full marks here.<br><br>The food was enjoyable, and the inclusion of a buffet of Asian dumplings and extra sweets was nice; though I was a little disappointed that some of the sweets appeared in both the served tray and buffet... A minor issue really.<br><br>As a once off experience when visiting Singapore I would recommend this, though there was nothing that would excite me to repeat my dining experience from the high tea perspective.

text: Afternoon tea was such a disappointment, Raffles and the Tiffin Room are definitely resting on their laurels here. A plate of sandwiches made from slightly stale store-bought loaves doesn&#39;t cut the mustard in this foodie capital. Cucumber sandwiches, while traditional, are quite uninspiring, not to mention the tuna mayo and egg mayo sandwiches that accompanied. The dim sum selection was equally uninspiring. The sweet selection wasn&#39;t great either. As it is nearly Christmas there were mini mince pies; I&#39;ve had better store bought ones and a vague approximation of Christmas pudding which was pretty horrible. The only thing I ate which was really nice was the curry puff. There was also a choir singing Christmas carols. They had lovely voices but were so loud that it was impossible to carry on a conversation, for the ENTIRE tea service. <br>Of course many people go to tea at Raffles simply for the atmosphere and experience but that doesn&#39;t mean the food needs to be poor at best. I&#39;ve had Sunday brunch at Raffles and it was excellent so it&#39;s not as if it&#39;s a hotel-wide problem. My advice would be to give it a miss and check out one of the other excellent teas on offer in the city.

text: As I stood in line waiting to he seated for the afternoon high tea, I wondered whether I had fallen into yet another tourist trap. Every single table was occupied, so be sure to reserve well in advance. With the added service charges, the two hour escape from the heat will set you back S$68 and champagne is extra. I do think it is worth the experience.<br><br>The staff is incredibly attentive, constantly filling up your coffee or tea, replenishing food and asking whether you are enjoying your high tea. <br><br>The spread includes fresh scones, curry chicken pies, steamed buns, dumplings, fresh fruit, bread pudding and assorted pastries. In addition, each table gets a three tiered stand with sandwiches and more pastries, so technically you never have to leave your table. The quality and freshness of the food were excellent. The scones were still warm, moist and flakey. Perfect with a bit of butter and strawberry preserves. No kaya though. The seafood and vegetable dumplings and the bread pudding were my favorites. <br><br>Definitely a must do while you are in Singapore. You will be so full that you can skip dinner.

text: As I stood in line waiting to he seated for the afternoon high tea, I wondered whether I had fallen into yet another tourist trap. Every single table was occupied, so be sure to reserve well in advance. With the added service charges, the two hour escape from the heat will set you back S$68 and champagne is extra. I do think it is worth the experience.<br><br>The staff is incredibly attentive, constantly filling up your coffee or tea, replenishing food and asking whether you are enjoying your high tea. <br><br>The spread includes fresh scones, curry chicken pies, steamed buns, dumplings, fresh fruit, bread pudding and assorted pastries. In addition, each table gets a three tiered stand with sandwiches and more pastries, so technically you never have to leave your table. The quality and freshness of the food were excellent. The scones were still warm, moist and flakey. Perfect with a bit of butter and strawberry preserves. No kaya though. The seafood and vegetable dumplings and the bread pudding were my favorites. <br><br>Definitely a must do while you are in Singapore. You will be so full that you can skip dinner.

text: Skip the afternoon tea and go elsewhere. The standard for afternoon tea is a really good scone and clotted cream, but they totally messed up the scone. Also, the dim sum was cold and we had to ask several times for our cups to be filled with tea. The hotel is lovely to look at and walk around in, but I would suggest snapping some photos and going elsewhere for tea!

text: Coffee with condensed milk. Came in a teeny tiny cup. Not a good value. According to my husband, coffee was so so also.

I am only reviewing this Bakerzin for my pickup of mooncakes that I ordered last month.  First, the mooncakes that I ordered were simply delicious.  I know the mooncake tradition is to give them as gifts to others in celebration of the autumn-moon festival.  However, my friend and I had find a way to celebrate our bdays in Singapore that was&#34;non-traditional&#34;.  <br><br>Bakerzin is tucked away in this mall.  When you enter the mall, it will look like a rat race and a little confusing.  From the entrance of the mall, you will just need to head straight forward.  I was surprised that I found it since I didn&#39;t google search in advance for the exact location.    <br><br>The pickup process was quick.  They checked my invoice and presented me my items.  Fast and quick.  The staff here was friendly.  <br><br>I am not sure about parking since I took a taxi.  My taxi drive was able to wait in the parking area as I went to pick up the mooncakes.

text: I was excited to visit Old Airport Road Hawker Center specifically for &#34;Lor Mee&#34; from the Uber popular stall- - &#34;Xin Mei Xiang Zheng Zong&#34; after watching a segment on YouTube. <br><br>I braved the long queue and waited over an hour to partake in, what I expected to be a bowl of yumminess. Unfortunately, it was a huge disappointment! <br><br>Lor Mee- served with noodles and a generous topping of fish and other ingredients. The gravy was significantly rich and thick with a slightly gelatinous texture and predominantly tasted of fish. It&#39;s definitely an acquired taste. Not something I&#39;d get again. <br><br>Despite the rave reviews of Lor Mee, the unsung hero is the Minced Mixed Noodle IMO. Pork dumplings and minced pork swimming in a bowl of wide rice noodles. The broth was light and full of flavors with the fresh herbs adding brightness to this delicious dish. A must try! <br><br>Char Kway Teow noodles and proteins were impeccably cooked with a beautifully smoky charred flavor however, it was well under seasoned and one noted. Perhaps a dash of soy sauce will help lift the flavors a bit or it was an off day for the stall. Overall it wasn&#39;t a bad dish. <br><br>Fried prawn and pork rolls were a mixed of sweet and savory flavors. While it wasn&#39;t my favorite, it was a nice side dish. <br><br>Curry Chicken and Black Pepper Pork Puffs had a flaky crispy crusts and loaded with herbs and spices. A great snack especially on the go. <br><br>A great tourist destination for food, sweets and beverages on the cheap!

text: Ok. Maybe I was waiting to be blown away after it was talked up so much but it was just ok / good.   We had some noodles and a clay chicken pot with rice. Clay pot dish seemed a little dry and over cooked to me. Maybe we went too late but and it was the bottom of the barrel. It did take 15 min to prepare so it wasn&#39;t just thrown together. Anyway pretty good and no complaints but I don&#39;t think I&#39;d make the trek to a hawker market again. I&#39;d eat passing by. <br><br>Experience box checked.

text: Five-star Food Centre! The hardest decision starving myself so I can pack all the delicious offerings and still lament over what else I want to eat.<br><br>Disclaimer: No air-conditioning, noisy, crowded, and expect long lines or queues. If you can put aside these dining conditions, Old Airport Road is AMAZING! It is a Must-Eat Stop for me in SG.<br><br>Top of my list: <br>Seafood Soup with Minced Pork Balls Yan Ji Seafood Soup): This cloudy soup is slowed cooked with layers of flavor. There is hint of wokhei. Fried flat fish ground and added to the minced pork elevates the flavor. It is salty and I don&#39;t like cooked seafood usually, but I cannot got enough of this broth. I dream about this soup in the USA. I usually get the soup with just the meatballs, but everyone else gets fish. I hear the prawns are cooked perfectly, firm, succulent and sweet. Hint: the cheap standard fish they offer is good enough. Don&#39;t be put off the price. It is worth it. Drink lots of water after that. $6 up per bowl.<br><br>Rojak or Salad with Shrimp Paste: Jicama, guava, cucumber, pineapple, bean sprouts, crispy ew char kuay or fried dough sticks, Century eggs (fermented black eggs buried underground with ammonia) mixed with a sweet, nutty haekor or shrimp paste that has the consistency of molasses.<br><br>Gong Gong or boiled sea snails: It is an art to eat these delectable bad boys. Gingerly skewer the flesh beyond the foot. Slowly ease the flesh until the whole animal is out. Hold the morsel by the foot, dip into sambal belacan or chili paste with fermented shrimp with a generous squeeze of lime, hold foot, bite and remove foot. It is chewy near the foot, creamy entrails at the end, spicy and delicate gift from the sea.  $10 per plate.<br><br>Char siu pork and roast pork (sioh bak) from Roast Paradise: crispy deeply marinated char siu and salty, crunchy roast pork belly and crackling served with rice. Tasty dipping sauce and mustard for condiments. Ask for more cucumber.<br><br>Ice Kachang or shaved ice: Smooth shaved ice drizzled with colored stripes and sweet corn with syrup atop red beans, jellies and uptup chee, gelatinous sweetened seeds from a palm. They are generous, I found 4 yesterday!!! It is better when you share and fight for the uptup chee. Other delicious desserts are the green jellied Nonya Chendol shaved iced drizzled with gula Melaka palm sugar syrup , Cheng Tng dessert soup with lotus seeds, gingko nuts and dried longan.<br><br>There are so many other stalls I wanted to try, but I can&#39;t get past my favorites. I want to try at least one more dish each time but my stomach fails me.<br><br>If you are still peckish, try the Epok Epok or curry puff with egg, char kuay teow or rice noodles with black soy and cockles, plump oysters in a half shell (S$3 per oyster).

text: If you come to this food court, get the prawn mee at Albert Street Prawn Noodle. The line can get outrageously long, so maybe try getting here before the rush. Seriously though, the prawn mee is amazingly delicious- a really unique and complex mix of flavors in one broth. Also, get the Or Chein (oyster omelette) at Xing Li Cooked Food. And if you have a sweet tooth and want something to cool down with away from the heat and humidity, Nyona Chendol is good- I like the original, but adding red beans looks just as good. Everything here is cheap, relatively speaking. <br><br>Old Airport Road is popular and a bit more touristy, but also a little further away from town, so if you&#39;re a visitor, you should just call a taxi (MRT is always good, but not everyone has the time or patience to check routes and stops). If you&#39;re a tourist with little to no exposure to Singaporean and Malaysian food, most of the food here will probably seem to be delicious to you. More often than not, if there&#39;s a long line for one particular hawker, the food is good. But seriously, no trip Singapore would be complete without visiting a good ole food court.

Selera rasa', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Selera rasa'}]
text: Selera Rasa - If you have not heard of the now $3.50 briyani, you are missing out.<br>Used to get this back in my ns days when it was like $3 and was super stoked to find out the hawker was still around 4 years later. The macik is the best, she is super nice and used to remember our faces when we came over for lunch. That being said, I only remember her being opened till the mid afternoon. Never saw the place open for dinner.<br><br>But I digress. This is hands-down one of the best briyanis on the island. The rice is fragrant and goes super well with the curry they used. The fried chicken and it&#39;s little fried scraps are tasty and fresh. Be sure to ask for veg and the papadum as well, she was out of veg when I got there at 2pm.<br><br>Nevertheless, always worth the visit.<br>Selera Rasa is located in the corner of old airport road food center. The corner being the side closer to the hdb blocks, as opposed to the cross street.

text: Praise the lord for Hawker centers! With so many hawker centers in Singapore, it is hard to decide which one in my favourite. Old Airport Road Food Centre is definitely a stand out. It is highly accessible via multiple bus line. <br><br>With endless options such as prawn noodle, wonton noodles, fish balls, fresh juice, curry puffs, rojak, kopi and kaya toast available; this center is where food dreams are form. <br><br>Be sure to visit Old Airport Road Food Centre to eat till your heart is content!

This is one of the many hawker centers in Singapore and compared to some of the other big ones, this one is much less touristy. Our friend who lives in Singapore suggested that we meet here for lunch and it was a fantastic adventure.<br><br>We employed the long queue method for determining which stalls to purchase from. For a feast of 4 dishes and 5 drinks, we spent about $30 total. The best item we got by far was the BBQ meat. I&#39;m not sure which stall it was but this one is absolutely worth seeking out. <br><br>Happy eating!

text: Loved this hawker center! Tried so many different types of food for so cheap.<br><br>Hua Kee Hougang Famous Wonton Noodles (5/5) was definitely a favorite here. They nailed the wonton noodle dish - the perfect amount of chili sauce, dried shrimp, and meat to sauce to noodle ratio. <br><br>We also tried Hock Guan&#39;s rojak (5/5), which was delicious. I only had this once while in Singapore, so I can&#39;t compare it to other places.<br><br>We ordered some pork satay from Chuan Kee Satay (4/5). The flavor was amazing and the pork was tender, but it was definitely on the oily side.<br><br>Whampoa Soya Bean&#39;s (5/5) bean curd with red bean was sensational! I wish I buy an entire tub of this and eat it everyday :&#39;(

text: My dad and I came here for lunch during our last day in Singapore. We went to eat at Maxwell Hawker Food Centre twice already and decided to come here instead. To get here, you&#39;ll need to take the MRT to &#34;Dakota&#34; stop and it&#39;s along the Circle (YELLOW) Line. This place is pretty huge. The first floor are the hawker stalls and the 2nd floor are mainly shops selling goods.<br><br>Stalls that we tried:<br>-Roast Paradise [Stall #01-121]: They offer roasted pig and char siew dishes. Our meals costed 4 SGD each.<br>-Hong Hua Dessert [Stall #01-86]: They offer a variety of shaved iced desserts. We shared the &#34;Ice Kachang&#34; and it costed 1.50 SGD.<br>-We also got the sugar cane drink. But, I don&#39;t recall what stall it was.<br><br>Not bad overall. I wanted to try Chau Kee Satay [Stall #01-85], but they only open in the evenings. I also wanted to try Lao Ban Soya Beancurd [Stall #01-127] again, but I was already too full to eat anymore (Note: I tried their tofu dessert at Maxwell tho]. I&#39;ll come visit again whenever I&#39;m in Singapore.

I loved the hawker center here.  My cousin and her fiancee took us here as this was their favorite.  You can find a seat first, and then go to all of the different stands.  Let them know how many ppl are eating, they price the portions so you don&#39;t have to pay for more than you can eat. <br><br>They bring the food straight to your table number when it&#39;s ready.  Even when you pay for beer, they bring the bottles to your table too.  Absolutely great food and experience.

Roast Paradise #01-122<br>Charsiew with chicken rice - 4 stars<br>Not much meat and the meat has a layer of fat in each slice and is a bit too burnt on the edges which I don&#39;t quite like. But overall the meat is cooked really well - moist, juicy meat, not too sweet or salty.<br><br>BNR Coffee<br>Kopi C Kosong Bing - 4 stars<br>Rich good flavor even without sugar. Would get less ice the next time.<br><br>Park at the multistorey carpark! The lanes are nice and wide compared to most other HDB carparks.

text: must get the sugar cane juice! $2 <br><br>very refreshing and affordable drink, one of the stall the uncle and aunties will come to your table and ask if you want something to drink. they&#39;ll take your order and then bring it to you that&#39;s when you pay them the money.<br><br>We tried to try a lot of the stalls and almost everything that we got is very good, we got some recommendation on youtube channels. <br><br>my favorite was the Laska <br><br>P.S bring your own napkins :)

The hawker food options are limitless here!! There are so many hawker stalls to choose from and they all look so good! I can&#39;t pinpoint any single one, but I bet you won&#39;t be disappointed with any of these mom and pop shops.  <br><br>It&#39;s a little ways out of the main downtown area, but can easily be accessed via public transportation.

old airport road, known as the most popular Hawker in Singapore, offers a wide selection of food across different price points depending on what you eat. I love eating here, but it also makes my indecisiveness a problem haha. Some of the stalls will sell out and close early, to make sure you get to try everything, go in a group and go for lunch instead of dinner. I&#39;ve had a few times where I wanted to get roast meats there, but they sell out before dinner :(

Western Barbeque #53 Jogurtz#129 Lao Fu Zi Fried Kway Teow12 Xing Li Cooked Food28 Jia Long Mei Shi #55 Kah Ping Ri Ye Xiang #87', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Western Barbeque #53 Jogurtz#129 Lao Fu Zi Fried Kway Teow12 Xing Li Cooked Food28 Jia Long Mei Shi #55 Kah Ping Ri Ye Xiang #87'}]
text: Orchid Coffee Stall #11 (facing main road)<br>Sugar Cane Juice<br>The owner of the stall isn&#39;t very pushy but he will approach nearby tables if they want a drink. The sugar cane juice here is pretty decent and refreshing. $1.50 a cup. <br><br>Western Barbeque #53<br>Supposedly a famous stall, and they serve each plate with bun all wrapped up in plastic, very old school. We ordered, chicken, pork and lamb. All were tender and juicy. The sunny side up was perfect too.<br><br>Jogurtz #129<br>A newly opened froyo stall on the back row, serves small $3.50 or large $5 cups, to be honest, both small and large cups seems to have the same amount of froyo, just more toppings in the large cup. The small sized cup seems to be at least a medium sized Llao Llao cup. It&#39;s more icy and slightly more sour than other competitors but it is very refreshing to eat this after alot of bbq and greasy food.<br><br>Lao Fu Zi Fried Kway Teow 老夫子炒粿条 #12<br>Probably one of the most famous stalls in Old Airport Road, the queue grows quickly but the uncle also cooks quickly. The stall can be recognized by the music playing out of the boombox, and the auntie who takes orders very quickly. You can be the 10th person down the line and she&#39;s asking for your order! The kway teow was very wet and wasn&#39;t too oily, the flavour was there and I didn&#39;t eat chunks of lard but I could definitely taste the use of lard.<br><br>Xing Li Cooked Food 兴利熟食 #28<br>Fried Oyster<br>As mentioned by fellow yelper Dominic C, the fried egg is very gooey and isn&#39;t crispy, the cook definitely takes his own sweet time to cook the fried egg.<br><br>Jia Long Mei Shi #55<br>Chicken Wings<br>The chicken wings were juicy and good, the auntie was very friendly and there was no queue. Got the food quickly and ate it quickly as well! Not a bad choice for chicken wings!<br><br>Kah Ping Ri Ye Xiang #87<br>Rojak<br>Lots of big dough fritter pieces, all were crispy despite taking my time to slowly finish up the plate. The chilli can be quite spicy so beware. Lots of crushed peanut in every mouthful!<br><br>Ming Kee Fuzhou Fish Balls #109 (facing main road)<br>Fuzhou fish balls have meat embedded in the fish ball which is nice! The meatballs are soft and bouncy and very flavourful. The soup is slightly more bland and comes with a small seaweed. They are served in portions of 6.

I&#39;m so glad that my friend insisted I visit Singapore while doing my Winter Asia tour 2017. It&#39;s a pretty popular hawker (a term that means Chinatown complex) where you have two long rows of many different food options. FYI, it&#39;s hard to find napkins there so bring some with you. It was also hard for me to find trash bins so I found one attached to a juice stand and threw my trash there. I got scolded though since they could get fined for having random trash items in there. Very odd. <br><br>Anywho, I ordered some prawn noodles and dessert from two of the stands and left pretty full and satisfied. Another great eating place to come back for sure and try other stands!<br><br>They also have wifi there so that&#39;s a major plus!

text: Wow! I had such an amazing experience here while I was visiting Singapore. <br><br>I LOVED the fresh juices and smoothies along with the chicken rice. <br><br>If you&#39;re in Singapore, you need to check this place out because you won&#39;t be disappointed. There are so many different options for food, and you will find something tasty for everyone.
Amazing food court, BUT BEWARE - if you are not used to Asian food and are being experimental touring Singapore, this may not be the place for you, try something like Lau Pasat instead
