text: I know there are many good food stalls here but there are also many mediocre or average food stalls. So you do need to know where to go. <br><br>One such average food stall is #01-91 which sells congee or rice porridge. There are many varieties of porridge available and it does see a steady stream of customer who usually get it to go. <br><br>I like the options available for the century egg pork porridge. You could choose meatball or meat slices (I think). I had the meatball which was lovely. It came with a you tiao stick which was still crispy. <br><br>The dish not to order would be the raw fish salad. The small portion was miserable. One could hardly see the fish slices which were so thin they almost blended in with the disposable plate. I guess I am used to the versions served in Chinatown Food Center or even at Tekka Market Food Center which were more generous and cheaper too.

text: A solid hawker centre if you&#39;re looking for a legit Singapore eating experience.<br><br>My current faves include:<br><br>#01-02: Hua Kee Hougang Famous Wan Ton Mee<br>The $5 portion of the dumpling noodle fed this hungry preggo lady well! I could&#39;ve shied away from the chilli but I figured it wouldn&#39;t do the dish justice if I skipped it. The dumplings were stuffed to the brim and delicious. Throw in the copious amount of al dente noodles in a bowl and it is BEST.<br><br>#01-12: Lao Fu Zi Fried Kway Teow<br>I love Char Kway Teow and am not very particular with my stalls. Just know this one does the dish justice.<br><br>#01-51: Waan Waan<br>This is a Thai dessert spot that does coconut ice cream. Their dishes are quite refreshing in this Singapore heat; however they do try to upsell me sometimes even though I tell them straight up that I&#39;m not interested... not a fan of that.<br><br>Next time I want to try some of the curry puff stalls and the banana fritter stall in the back!

text: Plenty of stalls here to choose from. in fact if you have not make your mind up, you will be walking around for at least 30 minutes deciding what to eat.<br>One of the best wonton noodle is located here, and there are two stalls. Which one is better you have to decide.<br>There is a minced pork noodle soup, and it sells out fast. Get there after 2pm, the stall will be closed.<br>There are at least two prawn noodle stalls here, again you have to decide which one is your favourite.<br>Luckily there is only one rojak stall, get a queue number before you start your entree as the queue is super long.<br>Don&#39;t forget the char koay thoew as well as the carrot cake. Again several better stalls at this hawkers center.

text: As I was doing my research on which hawkers are the best and that I must visit, Old Airport Road was one of the highest rated one. As you get off the metro station, don&#39;t get the first food court area confused with the hawker which is right after. However, the food center opens earlier than the hawker. The hawker location had great food selection although this hawker was not my favorite just based on overall atmosphere.

text: Came 2x and tried :<br>Xin Xiang Lor Mee (4-1/2*)-- I&#39;m not a lor mee fan and has never had a good one. I had wanted to try Hokkien Mee or fried kway Teow but both were closed. This lor Mee had a very long line so I tried it. It was very very good, worth the wait. $5 good portion.<br><br>Came again and had Nam Seng Hokkien Mee (3-1/2*)--it&#39;s hard to find a good Hokkien Mee. It&#39;s okay and better than many places. $5 small. Not much wok hei.<br><br>Toa Payoh Rojak is passable.<br><br>Sesame Paste at another store is average, not fragrant.<br><br>Sugar cane juice--good as always.<br><br>I&#39;m happy to have found this place and will try others when I come another year.

text: Classic hawker center - known by locals to be one of SG&#39;s best. They serve a huge variety of food here with many good selections. Quite packed and a bit difficult to find seat for a large group but nonetheless a good place to visit to immerse in the true local experience<br><br>Reviews of some popular stalls I have been to per the below.<br>- Dong Ji Fried Kuay Teow - the stir-fried noodle here has a nice wok smell but the line is long and moves slowly so gotta be patient<br>- Lao Fu Zi Fried Kuay Teow - another fried kuay teow stall - this one has a stronger walk smell than Dong Ji but I personally prefer Dong Ji&#39;s seasoning of the noodle. A very good option nonetheless but super long slow line since they cook one dish at a time <br>- Wen Wen Prawn Mee - average - nothing particularly special<br>- Roast Paradise - really good BBQ pork - recommend<br>- Nam Sing Hokkien Mee - usually I&#39;m not a big fan of Hokkien Mee but this one is good - the noodle is not too soggy from the gravy and there&#39;s a hint of wok smell in the sauce. Long line.<br>- Chuan kee satay - Ok / despite its popularity, I have had better satay elsewhere<br>- Toa Payoh Rojak - personally not a Rojak fan but this is one of the better ones I have had - the ingredients were fresh and well-balanced. If you order with chili, it can indeed get spicy<br>- Hua Kee Wanton Meat - good / comforting wonton noodles - not mindblowing but a safe good bet<br>- 51 Soya Bean - a good place for traditional SG/Chinese dessert - try the tao huey (cold tofu pudding)<br>- Sugar Cane Juice - a classic SG refreshment for a hot day

Lots of stalls here and plenty of seats. I like the dry noodles stall that is on the outside corner of the center and also the fried bananas were yummy here. Definitely would visit again when in singapore.

text: Singapore hawker food or street food as the west called them.<br>Over hundreds of stalls selling local food fla ours.<br>Must try when in Singapore.<br><br>Certain stalls have lines stretching 20 men deep.<br>Take note there is no air-conditioning in the building.

text: Old Airport Road FC was my first experience of a hawker center in Singapore during my trip in November... and it surely did not disappoint.  My friends brought me here and basically said &#34;go!&#34; and I had absolutely no idea what to get.  It was so overwhelming since everything looked so damn good and there were new dishes that I wasn&#39;t accustomed to, being American and all.<br><br>We ate a variety of delights here, from the classic char kway teow to braised intestines (I love intestines... don&#39;t judge).  I also had my first Lao Ban dessert here - SO GOOD.  We also had oyster omelette - the oysters were fat and juicy and the omelette wasn&#39;t overly greasy or anything.  The only thing I wasn&#39;t too much of a fan of was the Hokkien noodles.... a little bit too ocean-tasting for me.  <br><br>Too bad I couldn&#39;t really tell you which stalls these things came from, but I don&#39;t think you can  go wrong with any of the food here.  Lots of soups, noodles, desserts, and drinks - enough to leave you in a food coma for the rest of the night.  I can&#39;t complain about a place that sells a bazillion types of food.... only thing I can complain about is that it&#39;s not in an air conditioned building (haha).

My first Hawker&#39;s center turned out to be my favorite and one of the highlights of my Asia trip. Great food and good layout.<br><br>Highlights:<br>- Chay kway teow: mixed type of noodles in a soy like sauce was a hit. 5 stars.<br>- Hor fun: wide rice noodles with gravy. 5 stars.<br>- Carrot cake: rice patties with egg and a brown sauce was one of my faves. 5 stars<br>- Meatball bao: soft bun and tasty big meatball hiding inside. 4.5 stars<br>- Black pepper puff: didn&#39;t care that much about the famous curry puff but loved the black pepper version inside of the thick flaky exterior. 4.5 stars<br>- Fresh juices: so good, I got 3. Blend the fruit with a bit of ice right there. 5 stars<br>- Tofu: silky and just a bit sweet of a dessert. Meant to eat a few spoonfuls but almost ate the whole container. 4.5 stars <br>- Noodles with minced meat: with and without soup with linguine type noodles were great. 4 stars<br>- Layout: 2 long aisles with seating in between and outside under umbrellas <br><br>Lowlights:<br>- Few stalls closed on Sunday<br>- Need coins to pay last for the toilet <br>- My friend wanted fresh fruit for his kid but couldn&#39;t find it anywhere <br><br>Got my 2 week trip off to an awesome start blissfully happy trying all of these dishes and would love to come back again.

My favourite hawker in Singapore in terms of choice (although Chinatown Complex has the craft beer stalls in its favour). Worth noting there is a covered path all the way there from Dakota MRT (but not Mountbatten). <br><br>I&#39;ll update the list over time. Best:<br>- Yi Ji vs Nam Sing (fried hokkien mee): both are worth trying. I personally prefer the fishier, sweeter Yi Ji and its pungent chilli. There&#39;s something fun about the brusk service as well. Nam Sing is an impressively professional operation and the prawns have a slight edge. <br>- Geylang Lor 20 banana fritters: looks unassuming but these are very sweet, soft bananas. Love it. I&#39;m not a fan of the larger, less ripe pisang goreng though.<br>- Lim Hin fruits/juice: the soursop juice (&#34;classic&#34;) is phenomenal. This stall is supposed to be quite picky with their fruit and it shows. Good soursop is one of the best things about living here. I never thought a simple soursop juice would make my &#34;top 10 meals of 2017&#34; list.<br><br>OK:<br>- Lao Fu Zi char kway teow (black): not as much wok hei as I&#39;d have imagined from the giant wok, perhaps because outside rush hour. Still, this CKT has good ingredients and is on the sweet side. Can&#39;t wait to try Dong Ji. <br>- Sin Thor Bak Koot Teh: a well executed, but not standout braised pig leg. I&#39;m biased due to the closure of the two BKT stalls near my home, meaning any BKT finds favour at the moment.

text: This hawker center is a bit out of the way, but worth the stop if you have time! After visiting a couple of other hawker centers, this one was your typical place of various food stalls and such. Do note, that if you need to go to the restroom, it will cost you ten cents to do so.<br><br>For most of the food here, the options vary from porridge to pasta to the typical dishes you see at hawker centers. I didn&#39;t know what to get so I conducted a small experiment. Instead of ordering whatever looks good to me, I simply chatted with some of the locals and ordered food based on their recommendations. Result? Everything I got was DELICIOUS. One of my favorite items was the Thai style noodle dish with wonton soup. The stall was located in a dark ish looking corner of the place. The wonton soup = yummylicious. The broth was perfectly seasoned and the wontons itself were savory and filling. For only $4, you get both the wonton soup + the noodles. Noodle dish was quite tasty, with the fresh cut BBQ pork and the seasonings on the dish wasn&#39;t too overwhelming. For other small dishes I tried, I really enjoyed the curry flavored puff and the fried dumpling. For the puff, the outside was nice and flaky while the inside tasted legitimately like good Thai yellow curry with its potatoes and chicken. As for the fried dumpling, this was surprisingly filling! The inside was mostly chicken, potatoes and small veggies and it had a nice spicy kick to it.<br><br>Overall, I really like the vibe of this place. You don&#39;t see too many tourists and the locals are friendly and nice to talk to. Not sure if it was the time we went (late afternoon), but there was hardly a long wait (except for one stall in particular) for most of the food stalls. Definitely a relaxing eating experience at this hawker center.

text: We ate here after hearing many great stories of the local food stalls within the hallowed portals of the Old Airport Road Food Centre. We were on the hunt for my new local favorite Singapore dish, Char Kway Teow and settled on unit#1 30. The stall was named Lucky and their specialty was spelled differently as Char Kuay Tiao. Minor details aside, we ordered two plates of Char Kway Teow with chili. The drink stall across the crowded way crammed with tables and people was playing Classic Rock and had Carlsberg on special offer. We also ordered a couple of drinks from the juice stall beside our Lucky stall. <br><br>The food was great. Great flavor of cockles, Chinese chives, bean sprouts and flat noodles all cooked in light and dark soy sauce. Just the right amount of spiciness and a good sized portion. What&#39;s not to love. Washed down with Carlsberg and Soursop and Plum juice listening to old Aerosmith and ACDC, our visit was a resounding success. Cannot wait to go back.

There are so many great food stalls in this Hawker.<br>My favorite would be the Lao Ban, the Fried Kway Teow, the claypot chicken rice and the little stall that does Popiah.<br>But no matter what local craving you have, this is the place to go to satisfy it!

text: A great friend from Thailand came for a visit and we decided to go for a good simple meal at this food center. There is incredible variety of food, but I&#39;m going to give a review specifically of Wen Wen pork rib prawn Mee stall 01-147. We had a steamboat of crab, prawns, clams, pork ribs, intestines and pig tails. The base stock was crazy good with intense flavors of prawn and pork. After the ingredients were eaten, the stock became extra rich with even more intense flavors, this time with crab and clams into the mix. The owner is Richard, a thoroughly nice guy. The place and ambience is well, hawker center. But here you can also bring your own stuff, vegetables, abalone or whatever and just throw into the pot. Richard won&#39;t charge you extra. Highly recommended and very affordable. One hint, better come before October 2017 as he will move to Kallang market.

text: Many good foods and is very crowded . Tried lor mee but is quite normal and over hyped. Toa payoh rojak is good now is not so crowded. Kueh chap is delicious <br>Fried prawn noodle is good. Fried Kway lau foo Che is a bit dry. Paste cheap and good. Beer is cheap. Bbq pork is delicious. Satay good.

One of my favourite Hawker Centres!<br><br>Do try:<br>Lao Fu Zi Char Kueh Teow - worth the long line!!<br>Lao Ban Dou Hua<br>Chee Cheong Fun<br>Sliced fish bee hoon<br>Lor Mee<br><br>At night, the satay, zi char, hokkien mee, rojak stall are all pretty decent. I must say, Old Airport Road is one of those hawker centres with the most stalls selling pretty decent local delicacies!

text: I came here first time today. It seems many good eating shops are there, but I tried my most favorite food in Singapore, Fried Hokken Prawn Mee. Very good!

This food centre seems a bit out of the way which is good because it wasn&#39;t too crowded on a Friday afternoon but bad because I need that crowd to know where to go. I feel so helpless if there are no lines of any sort to help me make the very important decision about what to eat. <br><br>I settled on some curry chicken and bread which was good.  Plenty of seating both inside and out.

text: I liked this place better than the other hawker spots!!<br><br>The noodles were tasty (pic posted), as were the toast and dragon fruit juice. Yummm! We got the noodles since it had the longest line there, hehe-sometimes following the crowd has its perks!

It is a better hawker centre in the day than at night. Most of the more popular stalls are actually closed at night.<br><br>As in most hawker centers in Singapore, you bring with you some patience and join any stall that has a line, that will be your best bet.<br><br>My personal favorites:<br>- Nan xing Hokkien fried noodles (because they do the version that I prefer that has more bee Hoon than yellow noodles)<br>- peanut pancake <br>- kway chap <br>- carrot cake/oyster omelette stall facing the front entrance

Went there at 10.45 am on a Sunday hoping to skip the lunch crowd but it&#39;s already bustling with lots of people. There is a 1 hour wait for the famous fried Hokkien Mee and so we went around looking for other alternatives instead. Guess it&#39;s the hot weather and the packed crowd, the porridge stall holder we went to that also make hand made Chee Cheong Fun with filling, is super grumpy. She even shouted at her mom who do the finishing touches before handing the food to the customers. <br><br>End of the trip, I&#39;ve decided not to visit this place again. Sadly it&#39;s not a place that I want to go and feel good.

text: Had the lor mee (#116) and fried kway teow (#12) - which also both had long queues.  The lor mee was excellent and much better than it looked!  But the kway teow ($4 portion) was only ok and the portions were tiny!  <br><br>You can add cilantro and chilis and black vinegar to the lor mee, which I highly recommend.

text: Best food court I&#39;ve tried so far. The wanton stall had an awesome pork and shrimp dumpling soup. Also had their spicy noodle on the side which was perfect. The tried a lime juice fresh from the cold drink stall. Also amazing! Totally refreshing and not too sour/tart.  Lastly grabbed a hot red paste bun from the only place selling hot buns in there which was so fluffy and perfectly hot and topped with sesame seeds, white and black.  I will definitely be back! All for the low low price of 4.90 for all of the above :)

text: It&#39;s a huge Hawker center, prices are reasonable and there&#39;s a LOT of choice, including novelty stalls such as western meat grill, cupcakes...<br><br>My favorite by far though is the Thai stall in the inner row, which makes a KILLER green curry. Don&#39;t miss it !

* My favourite hawker centre *<br><br>When in Singapore I&#39;m in hole in the wall heaven with all of the amazing inexpensive hawker centres.  This one is at the top of my list on every visit.  <br><br>Over the years some of my best meals in Singapore have been here.  Highlights are one of the absolute best black pepper crabs I have had in my life, a wonderful char keow teow that had that lovely wok hei as well as some of the most flavourful Chinese sausage I&#39;ve had, wonderful laksa, and a smooth fresh tofu that I can still taste.  <br><br>I passed on the crocodile foot soup that I saw on a past visit, and didn&#39;t see it again after that.  Darn!

I used to come here a lot when I was in Secondary school. So this place brings back lots of memories.<br>Seems like everyone is raving about the CKT.. so here&#39;s my take on two of them.<br>Let me start with Lucky Char Kway Teow. According to the owner, the stall has been in operation for seven years and they have various recommendations as seen plastered around the stallfront. The CKT here is less than saucy i.e. dry in a good way. I like that the lupcheong (chinese sausages) were given in ample amounts and the taste was strong and distinct from the rest of the noodles. The noodles were pleasant and would give it a 3.5-4 stars.<br>Opposite Lucky on the second last row of stalls on the west side of the hawker center is Laofuzi CKT(with a green sign). There&#39;s always a queue regardless of the time of the day and many have sworn by this CKT. I find wouldn&#39;t drive like hours to just eat this.. its just okay. The noodles are quite delicious when eaten hot, and the &#39;hum&#39;/ cockle just rounds off the taste. I love hums.<br><br>No trip to OARFC is complete without Laoban soya bean. There&#39;s 51 a competitor and much cheaper but the taste at Laoban is just superior. It has a strong bean taste that some may call &#39;plasticky?&#39; but i really like it. Choose the small cup ($1) of soy bean milk for a filling and wholesome thirst-quencher.

text: Ahhh, the hawker centre with the Hokkien mee stall that&#39;s more elusive than a French Laundry table. It&#39;s called Nam Sing, and it&#39;s store number #01-32 and you MUST call him first at +65 6440 5340 before coming. If the uncle doesn&#39;t pick up the phone, don&#39;t bother coming. If he picks up the phone, make sure you ask if there are still a lot of noodles left. I had the unfortunate experience when I made sure that they were open, but they were sold out by the time I got there!<br><br>Other than Nam Sing, there are several other famous stalls here such as:<br><br>- Xin Mei Xiang Lor Mee<br>- Lao Fu ZI Kway Teow<br>- Toa Payoh Rojak<br>- Lao Ban Soya Beancurd<br>Etc etc<br><br>But for me, I always go for the Hokkien mee. IMO the best in Singapore, where the noodles is very eggy and it&#39;s cooked like an al dente pasta.

text: A must go when visiting Singapore! I absolutely loved the vibe of the place, which is where you can go to see how the locals eat. Food is so inexpensive, at 2-3 USD a plate. Lines stretch over half an hour for the most popular stalls at peak times. Definitely try the famous Hougang Mee noodles, the Hougang Otah, Fatman Satay (only evenings), Fish Soup, Char Kway Teow and Fried Oyster Omelette stalls! Many of the stalls at this food center have been opened for over 30 years, although few retain their original owners to this date. The food is still super tasty!<br><br>Also, the crazy line at the back of the food center is probably for Lao Ban bean curd dessert and soy drinks, I&#39;ve seen more than 40 people lining up and their product is really different than other local versions. This one has an almond taste to it and a very custard texture, which is unlike the soy milk quality that their competitors produce. Beat the crowd by going at 11am or 530pm before the locals come eat! <br><br>Payment is always in cash and local currency, so leave your credit cards at home.

Fairly standard hawker center with a big selection of more Chinese and Singapore type flavors. I wish there were a few Indian options, but what is here is pretty good.  Good fish ball soup, seafood salad, prawns, and other seafood choices. Not many beer choices either. Make sure to bring your tissues to hold a table as it gets fairly crowded at meal times.

My favourite hawker centre of all time. Why does anybody go to Newton? This is THE shit. <br><br>There&#39;s everything here including great kway chap (Blanco Court), char kway teow (Lao Fu Zi), lor mee (Xin Mei Xiang) and Hokkien mee (Nam Sing). Also the now famous Lao Ban beancurd with its equally crazy queues. The only downside about eating at a food centre like this with so many all-stars: I can&#39;t think of any other food centre where you have to queue so much, no matter what you are ordering! On the bright side, even if you didn&#39;t want to queue for the &#39;famous&#39; stalls, the less famous stalls which offer the same types of food tend to be quite good too. Nothing really sucks, I think. Not sure if that&#39;s a safe proclamation to make.<br><br>My new favourite stall here is the under-rated Chuan Loo Bee Hokkien stall which is opposite the Lao Ban beancurd stall. It sells some of the best -- and cheapest -- seafood and zichar I have ever seen. I love the black pepper crabs, hotplate egg omelette and beancurd and pretty much everything they&#39;ve got. <br><br>Wash down the huge feast (any combination of things here, put together, necessarily constitutes a feast!) with a beer or sugar cane juice and mark it down as the quintessential Singapore experience. Do your tourist friends a favour and take them here, not Newton!

text: Lots of good eats within one place! I&#39;d always heard about the wonders of Old Airport Rd hawker centre but never traipsed over east-ish (it&#39;s actually not that far east, even) to try it out. But since a colleague from abroad was here visiting, we made the pilgrimage down! <br><br>1. Lao Fu Zi Fried Kway Teow #01-12 (2nd row of stalls, kind of in the middle) is certainly da bomb.. Deliciousness! $3 for a plate, not an overwhelming lot, but probably enough saturated fats to last for a while, unfortunately. Noodles were well fried and slid down your throat, with a suitable amount of sweetness from the sweet black soy. This stall has a combination of kway teow noodles (the flat rice noodles) and thick round yellow noodle (I can&#39;t figure out the name, unfortunately, this website calls it ), which isn&#39;t found everywhere. My two female colleagues baulked when they saw me approaching the table with 2 plates of $3 noodles (this, as recommended by an uncle standing in line in front of me when I asked for a $5 plate- he convinced me that 2 $3 plates was more worth it - I guess it&#39;s true! Didn&#39;t make the lady boss any happier, certainly). However, the six of us devoured almost all of it..<br><br>2. Mattar Seafood Barbecue #01-63 (3rd row of stalls, right at the back)<br>a. Chilli crab was not bad, colleagues liked it a lot and preferred it to Jumbo&#39;s. It is also cheaper, at $40/kg. We got 2 for $61, not too bad I guess! And yay for mantous.. 50cents each. Although still can&#39;t beat the Forture Seafood ones. Those are gigantic and fluffy and heaven on earth!<br>b. Stir fried greens with mushrooms ($8) was also pretty good - we just asked for whatever green veg they had and she supplied us with puay leng (chinese spinach) with mushrooms with a delicate light sauce! <br>c. Sambal stingray ($16) from them was unfortunately so-so, the stingray was okay but the sambal was somewhat lacklustre. Pity about that!<br><br>3. Guan Kee Seafood (#01-66) <br>a. Cereal prawns ($13  I think) were delicious! I forget how many prawns they gave us though.<br>b. Pork ribs king ($12) was not that great. Tender pieces, but not much flavour.

Oh the sinful memories. I used to work very near Old Airport Road and had lunch there almost everyday. I believe this should be stated as a major job perk if my office was hiring.<br><br>The place&#39;s divided into 3 rows. My colleagues and I always call it row 1 - facing the road, 2 or 3 - against the wall to differentiate the stalls.<br><br>There&#39;s a wonderfully juicy chicken chop at row 3, the chicken is succulent and never fails to emerge with glistering skin and an intoxicating grilled aroma. On the same row, there&#39;s a small stall that sells goreng pisang and fried nian gao (aka rice cake) and fried - get this - DURIAN. It is amazing. In row 1, there are two battling stalls of wanton mee, apparently each stall has their own loyal following - can tell from the queue.<br><br>The thing about hawker food is that everything&#39;s so affordable; every meal there can easily spiral out of control and become a little feast. Not that I&#39;m complaining.

Absolutely adore this place. All my favourite foods in a hawker centre-space just slightly larger than Maxwell Market, packed with the famous Hougang Wan Ton Mee, Lao Ban Tau Huey, delicious traditional Chinese desserts (like the pastes, chng tng, gingko barley soup), bak kut teh, tze char, Lor Mee (!!!), Chicken Rice, Pig Organ Soup (not my cup of tea but fans love the ones here!), complete with fruit juice &amp; drink vendors thrown in (and the occasional duplicate/bandwagon stores, which are totally legit and yummy as well!). <br><br>Easy to get to, Dakota/Mountbatten MRT, 20 minute bus ride from the city... envious of people who live in the vicinity and get to have all these local delicacies in their disposal till late in the night...

Old Airport Road Food Centre is where I bring my friends from overseas for a taste of local food. With a wide variety of stalls all housed under one roof, this place is home of my favourite hokkien mee, wan ton mee and hand made cheong fun. There is also the hugely popular Lao Ban tau huay alongside many traditional dessert stalls. The hokkien mee in the 3rd row, can&#39;t remember what it is called exactly, is absolutely divine! However, the wait for it can go up to 1.5 hours during busy periods!<br><br>It gets pretty crowded on weekends and finding a table and parking can be pretty difficult, so planning for an early dinner/lunch may help you avoid some of the crowd.

This place has an INSANE amount of choices, I am completely lost everytime I am here. At least count, there must be at least 5 stalls selling the same food - char kway teow, wanton noodles, western, etc. I don&#39;t come here enough even though my school used to be near.<br><br>Some picks: Satay vermicelli (you don&#39;t get this very often around anymore), wanton noodles, fried kway teow (don&#39;t bother queuing, go for the ones without), 51 beancurd and round off with a glass of sugarcane juice. My colleagues pick the cantonese porridge and Western food stall.<br><br>I&#39;m only ranking this a-ok because I think I need to explore this place more before I make my decision.

Old Airport Road Food Centre is the place to go for cheap and good food under 1 roof. The huge compound holds more than a hundred stalls ranging from savory to sweet, small snacks to hearty meals, local to western cuisine.<br><br>Some hot favorites are the 2 competing wanton mee stores at the left end of the complex. Cho Kee and another stall. They even have their electronic queue display.<br><br>There is a hand made chee cheong fun stall (i&#39;m not sure what&#39;s its name). It&#39;s in the second block, the second row from the main road. There&#39;s always a long queue for this one. Melt in your mouth rice rolls with char siew or prawns or scallops and topped with a light soy and shallots. Yums.<br><br>Other great stuff includes lor mee, Lao Ban beancurd, Albert Street Prawn mee and more. Char Kway teow is apparently very popular too.

Mention &#34;old airport road&#34; and everybody will know that you are referring to the legendary hawker food centre near Katong which has probably one of the highest concentration of good local food. It is also very huge - spanning 3 rows of stalls in a space that is probably the size of a football field or bigger.<br><br>Seating will be a challenge most times especially on weekends. However this is when group work comes in. One can sit, the others can start to queue to buy the food.<br><br>Of course the famous Lao Ban beancurd will come to mind since they originated here. However there are also other notable stalls such as Lao Fu Zi fried kway teow and Whitley Road Big Prawn noodles. The TPY Rojak and Hokee Wanton Noodles are also very good. The Western BBQ stall also has great chicken chops.<br><br>If you are unsure of what to eat, just join the stall with a queue and you can&#39;t be wrong.

Old Airport Road is probably the coolest hawker centre I&#39;ve been to in Singapore. If you&#39;re looking to do it right, go for dinner, eat as little as possible beforehand (I know, near impossible if you&#39;re visiting Singapore), and buy as many things as possible here. If you&#39;re a tourist, it&#39;s about a 10 minute walk from the MRT.

text: Great set menu items. Laksa, drink and toast for $6.80. The only negative is cramped eating area and the plastic tray has a really musty smell to it. Food and drink was very good.
Worst coffee i have tasted, TWICE.<br>Avoid this branch like a plague; other branches appear fine eg. Harbourfront <br>Sorry but the 1star is negative

Crepe &amp; Varhona cakes paired with green apple soda &amp; vanilla latte', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Crepe & Varhona cakes paired with green apple soda & vanilla latte'}]
text: Came back here to try their cakes (coincidentally they were having a 1-for-1) and we were not disappointed! The crepe cake was really good, so soft and fluffy, each layer subtly building onto the next. It was my first time trying varhola and it was heavenly - this coming from someone who isn&#39;t really fond of chocolate cakes. <br><br>We also had the smores waffle. My husband, resident smores enthusiast, feels that it wasn&#39;t overly sweet, and the marshmallows were nice, but it could have used more whipped cream and/or chocolate sauce because it was a little dry. <br><br>It was still incredibly noisy (had to lose a star for that, sorry) I&#39;ve noticed that people tend to come in groups of 5 or more, and since the tables are really close together, along with the fact that the entire cafe is relatively small, laughter and conversations are amplified and can be quite vexing to others. It would be good if there were signs around to ask people to not be so loud, or maybe the staff could come by and quieten their rowdy patrons occasionally.

The pandan ice cream tasted a bit artificial but generally positive experiences. I&#39;ve been to twenty Grammes at least 10 times over the last 3-4 years. They have a wider variety of cakes now.

The Charcoal Waffle with Salted Egg Sauce and homemade ice cream', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'The Charcoal Waffle with Salted Egg Sauce and homemade ice cream'}]
text: In my first trip to Singapore I knew I had to explore Arab Street. So I met up with a few pals and they took us to Twenty Grammes. It was a very young, hipster-y cafe with equally hipster food offerings. My friend called their design aesthetic Scandinavian, probably because the interiors looked like they came out of the Ikea catalogue. I&#39;ve heard great things about their Charcoal Waffle with Salted Egg Sauce, so  we had to try it! The warmth of the waffle and the salty egg sauce perfectly went well with a scoop of their house made vanilla ice cream. Definitely a good place to chill on Arab Street when you visit!

Rum and raisin', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Rum and raisin'}]
text: I love ice cream, gelato, sorbets, sherbets, milk shakes, and all the other brethren and cousins twice removed in the icy family tree. Imagine my pleasant surprise when it&#39;s closing time, and my sad puppy eyes yield the last scoops of gelato for the day. Score! I get hit up with a decadent scoop of rum and raisin - heady rum, boozy raisins, and that airy, almost fluffy poofy chewy texture of gelato that I haven&#39;t experienced in years. I&#39;m a texture person, and most places don&#39;t do it right. Either it&#39;s too creamy, too milky, too hard, too dense, too icy, or too pedestrian. This, my friends, was revelatory. <br><br>Price point is fair, throw in good conversation over which flavour to pick, and a toss up between strawberry cheesecake or Baileys Irish Cream. I&#39;ll be back, and next time.. I&#39;ll be getting a tub of each, and one more scoop of that rum and raisin for the road.

text: I know you must be thinking, who doesn&#39;t know about Starbucks. But what&#39;s special about this Starbucks is its location. Most branches are situated in crowded or popular areas like shopping malls or famed shopping streets like Orchard Road or Bugis Street. Not this one. The outlet is hidden in an office building at Buona Vista, which means that its usually quite empty on a weekday morning or afternoon. <br><br>It is extremely accessible, just a short walk away from a few bus stops and the soon-to-come One North MRT station on the circle line. Do take note that it is also near to several schools like ACJC and Fairfield Secondary School, and may oget a little packed after school hours or during examination periods. If you plan to visit on a weekend, come early to secure a good seat, especially if you need a powerpoint. <br><br>It is one of the perfect spots to spend a quiet day alone regardless if it is to read a book, write, study or just watch the world go by. The staff is also extremely friendly and willing to go the extra mile to make your day. I&#39;ve seen on various accounts whereby staff members ask around for those willing to share a seat to help other customers that are looking for a seat to enjoy their beverage or food. Customer requests are also taken seriously, like heating up a muffin for only 5 seconds. These little acts are an excellent show of professional service levels, another reason why I keep coming back.

text: Great place for breakfast. A very personal store, with lovely staff.

Great place to wait for people at One-North. You&#39;ll be surprised but it is really a bustle with tons of people here in the morning having breakfast, expat wives having a cuppa after their gym session upstairs and businessmen having meetings. You may actually have difficulty finding seats here in the morning. But I especially enjoy the armchairs outside the outlet itself - airconditioned but not confined to the noise of the outlet itself. At the same time you have a good view of whoever you are meeting coming your way, especially if they are late. I&#39;m not a fan of starbucks but there are a few like this one, that really jumps out as a perfect meeting point.

text: A place that I would hangout on weekends. It can get pretty crowded and the seats are not many. Plus, never understood the way the seating arrangements are done in all Toastbox Outlet. Kinda crampy with tables that are hard to slide both your legs underneath. Maybe it&#39;s my size, my legs hardly have space below the table and I need to seat like a crab!<br><br>But, I still like their Kopi-c. Fragrant and not too sweet, which is the opposite of Ya Kun version. And they offer many different accompaniment for that cuppa. Yam Cake, Thick Toast and Otah Toast and many more. Just next to it is their bread store with different selections and you may just buy from there and sear down to have your bread with a cuppa if the main menu doesn&#39;t please your palate.<br><br>This always will be my good cup of coffee apart from my favorite Starbucks.

text: This is the only Herbal Tea stall that I like. Auntie sells a total of two type of Herbal Tea. Bitter and Sweet. I can only take the sweet one. Natural sweetener is added for health purpose. Sweetness is just the right amount and no taste of bitter herbal tea.<br><br>As for the bitter one, my advise is you need to have some courage to try. It cost $1 more than the sweet one probably become of the additional chinese herbs added. The one and last chance I had trying the bitter one was cause someone told me bitter one if more effective. I choked on the first mouth due to the very very very bitter taste. And for some time, the taste just doesn&#39;t leave your mouth. That is when I deduct by my own logic that Herbal tea no matter sweet or bitter, the effect is the same.<br><br>The bitter herbal tea was also use to play this game of drinking without changing your expression. I always lose making the ugliest face expression. But boyfriend doesn&#39;t stop amuse me when there wasn&#39;t a slight change in his expression.<br><br>I will still get from this stall everytime I am at Old Airport Road.

text: is singapore really the most expensive city in the world?<br>the jury is still out.<br><br>but if, for any reason, you are feeling the money crunch, do drop by duke bakery.<br>cheap is good but free is better!<br>their free sampling, that is.<br>very, very generous indeed!<br>no dirty looks whatsoever from their staff and constantly refilled.<br>just sample all you want, leave empty handed, if you want but mostly full bellied!<br><br>but, i am sure, you will be unable to resist picking up something.<br>i mean, just check out their wide selection of freshly baked artisan bread throughout the day, see posted schedule within for precise timings of the day.<br>there is definitely something for everyone, be it sweet or savoury, they have it.<br>unique tastes, innovative combos, mostly light yet classic bakes.<br><br>having just celebrated their first anniversary and with a new outlet opening in thomson plaza, it looks like their formula works.<br><br>do look out for their free lifetime membership, that entitles you to a 10% discount,  currently being given out at their new thomson outlet.<br><br>for $5 or less or none at all, this is a cheap, sometimes free but definitely good dukedom to maintain!

The shop has very generous samplings which might fill up many hungry stomatch by just trying them arpund by 1 round. The breads are chewy and delicous, a bit big in terms of size compared to those in other bread stores but believe me, you will keep eating piece by piece until you finish the bread all (like me). My favorites are the cheese chocolate bread and okinawa brown bread.

The Chocola Cheese bread was delicious! it was soft and chewy and i couldn&#39;t stop myself from wanting more. Ingredients are Wheat Levain, Grape ferment, coffee extract, black bean, chocolate, cocoa powder and cream cheese. wonderfully crafted loaf of bread.

Coftea + Vegetarian = my fav combination!', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Coftea + Vegetarian = my fav combination!'}]
text: While one might argue that it takes the simple kopi-0 romance of a coffee shop away from a market, Coftea cleverly caters to the young and growing white collar crowd who still want their kopi fix in a genuine setting, while offering the option of flavoured coffee and tea, soy options and more. And what&#39;s great about Coftea is that is gives you the same hazlent or vanilla taste that Starbuck of Coffee Bean might offer without the overpriced mass-marketed prices and packaging. <br><br>Enjoy a Hazlenut Coffee for just $1.70 or a straight up Soya Bean Milk for a dollar. It&#39;s got that touch of class without diverting too far from the kopitiam scene! <br><br>Also, watch out for frequent arguements between the Coftea lady and the Vegetarian stall uncle right night door. It&#39;s a love-hate relationship that&#39;s lovely to watch while your enjoying your vanilla coffee or a nice cup of tea. <br><br>They open early and all through lunch so if you&#39;re in the area at any time, stop by for some not-so-fancy fancy coffee. Starbucks is across the street but you&#39;re far better off here. :)

text: Tucked in the corner of an apparel shop (In good company), Plain Vanilla in ion is a good place for respite from the busy streets of orchard-a good place to rest your legs after a shopping spree or a nice quiet place to spend a weekday afternoon.<br><br>Known for their cupcakes, plain vanilla&#39;s earl grey lavender does not disappoint. While some may find the frosting a tad too sweet, I personally feel that it is nicely balanced by the soft sponge cake.<br><br>The coffee, which uses beans from Papa Palheta was smooth and fragrant when I ordered the flat white ($5). Couldn&#39;t taste the precise notes but it was decent enough. <br><br>Update: Visited on Christmas Eve and the cupcakes were lacking the usual fluffiness with the earl grey lavender being a bit too dense. The Christmas special was not bad but the coffee failed to meet expectations as well.

text: One must be a huge fan of the Plain Vanilla brand to come to this café. It is hidden in the back of a local apparel shop. What&#39;s on offer is eclectic: cupcakes and tarts (their main products), a few sandwiches, 3 salads, coffee and tea. The food looks fresh. I had two salads. The supersalad is good; the chicken and saffron rice salad is too dry. Unless you want to have a quiet bite, you&#39;d be better off at a real coffee shop or salad bar.

text: Cute little cafe in the back of one of ION&#39;s retail stores called &#39;In Good Company&#39;. Their array of sweets on display is tantalising, and from the expressions of other customers around, the pasta&#39;s pretty good too! I only got a coffee, which was a little cool for my liking (I never enjoy a lukewarm latte) so that brought them down a notch in my eyes, but the staff were friendly and the latte art was cute :)

I loved this place! It&#39;s not really a restaurant setting, it&#39;s like a cafe inside a retail shop. Interesting. Anyway I&#39;m here to review the pasta and cupcake. I had a somewhat spicy spaghetti with tomato sauce and it was spicy but delicious. And then I wanted coffee with my cupcake (yes I was very hungry that day) and I had an iced latte with a white chocolate strawberry cupcake or something like that, and it was amazing!!! I just wished it were closer to where I lived or worked so I can just come over any time. I&#39;m keen to check the other vanilla bakeries/shops. And I also wish they had more items on the menu. Recently became allergic to mushrooms over the past 3 years, learned it the hard way 3 times, always ending up at the doctors office, so it would be good if they offered other none mushrooms options for pastas and sandwiches. But anyway I love tomatoes and tomato sauce. As long as they have more variety it would be even better. So 4.5 stars for me, and rounding up :)

The spread was awesome, great varieties. Chicken rice was superb given that this was a buffet. Chili crab was meh, chilled prawns were great, grilled scallops were da bomb, Peking duck was okay.<br><br>Service was great, very attentive, friendly, polite, what American servers should aspire to.<br><br>If you have Amex with Far Card benefits - dine here immediately. Such an amazing deal, 50% off for two person dining. I paid $70 (ten bucks for tax and service charge) for two for a lunch catch up with a buddy.<br><br>I do have a suggestion - change your name! Asian Market Cafe sounds so blah... I know you&#39;re not fine dining but come on, I&#39;m sure there&#39;s a better name you could&#39;ve adopted.

text: I was going to give it 3 stars but decided to give it 4 stars. It doesn&#39;t have a 4-star feel in terms of decor. It&#39;s very ordinary. But I liked the wait staff. They were friendly and were armed with a smile. That upgrades it for me, in a country with a dearth of good restaurant service. <br><br>Now, I was here for a business lunch so I had to refrain from looking too much like a glutton. Haha. So I only went three rounds at this local dishes buffet, of which the last round was desserts. <br><br>The good - I liked the laksa (you had to cook it yourself, so fun!) and the Indian and Malay dishes. I particularly loved their spicy tiger prawns! Aiyoh sedap!!!!!! <br><br>The Average - the desserts weren&#39;t too amazing. There was a good array but they were just okay. Not terrible. But not great. The only thing I liked was the kueh salat. <br><br>It&#39;s a not-too-bad place for a lunch buffet. Just don&#39;t expect it to be glam. But be uplifted by cheerful service.

Sunday dinner buffet spread ($72++) - 2 stars<br>This was the sumptuous crab spread. We wouldn&#39;t have come if not for the voucher and card which made the total around $100 for 3 people. Even then I find it hard to say it was worth it. Might&#39;ve been better off going to an Italian place with $30 mains. I tried the cold crab, cold prawn, black pepper crab and salted yolk crab. Flavors were good but the meat was overcooked and dry. The cold oysters were always out. The sushi tasted like your standard supermarket sushis, maybe worse since the rice was cold and hard. I enjoyed the Indian daal, briyani rice and butter chicken. But the rest of the spread - salads, local food - didn&#39;t look appetizing enough for me to try much. The desserts were substandard - had the green tea chestnut cake, chocolate praline cake and a mango cake (labeled yuzu cheesecake but there was no cheese in it to be tasted). The base cakes were moist but the flavors weren&#39;t strong and there was too much cream. The bo bo cha cha only had sweet potatoes and yam. No tapioca flour balls! Disappointed. Bandung was too sweet and the mango juice tasted like concentrate. There isn&#39;t much variety to begin with and what&#39;s there isn&#39;t great. Wouldn&#39;t go back even with a voucher.

text: We&#39;re not normally buffet fans, but had hope to try some new dishes and cuisines. Although the ambiance was fine, and the food selection wide and varied, this was an expensive but forgettable dinner.<br><br>Having eaten at other restaurants in the Fairmont, we had high hope. Though the food was tasty, it was mostly cold, and served on cold buffet plates. Not terrible, but with so many alternatives, not recommended.

Probably my favourite TCC outlet  - staff are friendly, price is reasonable and opens til late so it is suitable for those who work late. <br>I come here because it is convenient and the drinks are good.<br>The food quality here is reasonable and I actually prefer it to Cedele.<br>Their best selling iced peach tea is refreshing and delicious.... be sure to give it a try. <br>The menu is updated frequently and so someone who comes here often (like me) am always greeted with different things, which is another plus.<br>I like all their salads - tuna, tataki and tofu are my top 3 picks. <br>Their seafood alio olio pasta is another dish I would recommend.<br><br>If you&#39;re a member you get 15% discount and earn points that you can rebate, so per person it costs around $30 to dine here (food and drink).

text: Ok so I&#39;ve walked by these many times, finally went in the one at great world city.  Had the pasta that wasn&#39;t bad, nothing special though.  This seems to be more suited for coffee or some 10, 000 calorie beverage and desert, so I believe the food receives less attention.  Don&#39;t order the chicken wings.  Being from the south I&#39;m not known to walk away from fried yard bird (chicken) but I did this time.  It seem that it had re fried a couple of times.

Iced Matcha Tea', 'width': 180, 'height': 180, 'caption': 'Iced Matcha Tea'}]
text: The tiny cafe used to be called Niche Boulangerie. It is located at the old mature estate in Toa Payoh. Recently it has been reopended after a period of upgrading. It has expanded to the next door unit and renamed Niche Savouraeuse. The cafe has since became bigger in area with more dine in area. Besides its well known cakes and pastries, the menu has expanded to main courses dishes.<br><br>Its counter was filled with delicious looking cakes.<br><br>The place was decorated in a niche and cute way with model plane on top.<br><br>Menu was a simple single page. The drink menu was handwritten on the board on the wall. As there was no GST and service charge here, order will be taken at counter with only cash and NETS payment. Remember to help yourself to the water and cutlery at the counter.<br><br>Iced Matcha Tea ($4.80)<br>I was quite disappointed with the drink as it lacked of the sweetness and flavour of the tea. It tasted quite bland and not sweet as all.<br><br>Black Truffle Carbonara ($14.90)<br>Black truffle infused fresh cream, parmesan, mixed mushroom and bacon<br>Currently the most expansive item on the menu. It really smelt very fragrant of the truffle when served. I was quite surprised to find thinly sliced truffle on the pasta dish. The sauce was very rich and creamy, full of the truffle taste.<br><br>Orange Chiffon Cake ($2.50)<br>Made with Fresh Zesty Oranges<br>It was very light and fluffy cake, with hints of orange taste.<br><br>Traditional Kueh Salat ($4.90)<br>The kueh was made by the boss&#39;s mother who took about 6 hours to make it. She shared that there was once a customer came continuously for 3 days just to buy this kueh. It was one of the hottest item in this cafe. The blue coloring was made naturally from flowers. Made with fresh coconut milk and traditional methods, the simple kueh was a memory down the lane. One may bark at its price but it really tasted very old school, which was difficult to find these days.<br><br>Overall the food was delicious, except for the drink. The service was great. I was served by the boss himself at the counter. Food was served by the boss&#39;s mother who also asked about the food when clearing the table. Quite an unique find under the HDB flats.

text: Delicious and good-looking sweets, I felt like I went overboard buying 2 log cakes, 1 whole large tart and gingerbread man cookies, but they were all so good - no regrets! Can taste quality ingredients in the bakes. Owners are a delight to talk to and are passionate about their food. Staff very helpful and friendly too but require more training, I had to wait quite a bit for them to sort out boxes and prices.

text: Melvin, the owner, did not reply to my enquiry when asking for the price of a customized cake. He only replied when I gave a low rating. He assumed that I will not order from his cafe as I did not do so after making some enquiries previously. Let&#39;s see how far would his short-sightedness and arrogance go.

tl;dr reasonable prices and great quality pastries and tarts (famous for their original egg tart), will definitely come back!<br><br>Disclaimer: I&#39;m an American expat in SG and came here on the recommendation of a local friend<br><br>I am a huge fan of Chinese baked goods, and after hearing great things about Tai Cheong Bakery and its proximity to my residence, I had to come, and I&#39;m glad I did! The egg tart (1.90 SGD ~1.40 USD) was delicious: the crust was dense and buttery, unlike the flaky crumbly ones of egg tarts I have in the states. The chiffon cake was also wonderful, and really hit my mild sweet tooth.<br><br>They do have indoor seating (AC, of course), but I just stopped by on my way back home - it&#39;s very close to the Holland Village MRT station, so you really have no excuses not to visit! Photos to come next time I&#39;m there :)

text: Thanks Tai Cheong, for making me unable to enjoy any other egg tarts ever. If you haven&#39;t tried these, wake up early, beat the line and buy enough to last (because they still taste just as bomb the next day). When I was in sg, I would have to take orders from my friends whenever I went because no one wanted to miss out. Take advantage and come here while you can, because no egg tarts have come close since and I still think about these often.

Egg tart ($1.90) - 3.75 stars<br>Good, but the shortcrust pastry (think a lemon tart) was too crumbly so I couldn&#39;t actually hold the tart and tasted too cooked (a bit burnt) for my taste. It reminded me of the egg tart I&#39;d get in JC - and I liked that one better.

text: they used to be on the ground floor until the whole building started renovating.<br>now they are relocated on the cinema floor and aptly renamed.<br><br>previously, this was my go to breakfast joint on a sun morning.<br><br>after the move, there was a staff reshuffling and the new staff here just don&#39;t strike the same rapport with us.<br><br>the coffee machine was broken and they were all fixated in getting it fixed.<br>even though we were all queuing at the counter after opening time which is 9.30am.<br>why cant they just get on with business, then simply and apologetically inform each patron who orders coffee that it is not available yet?<br><br>they finally took our orders and i asked for my coffee to be served whenever they are ready.<br>i guess it was a mistake.<br>the coffee today was bad, way too acidic.<br>drowned it in milk and still undrinkable.<br>not sure if it had anything to do with the machine being broken initially.<br><br>asian breakfast @ $7.<br>western breakfast @ $8.<br>both with your choice of coffee or tea.<br><br>the nasi lemak comes with crispy ikan bilis, mid wing of chicken, fish cake, sunny side up egg and nice sambal chilli.<br>the nonya laksa was just so so.<br>the carrot cake was well fried but the supposed XO sauce seems exactly like the sambal chilli.<br>the pancakes looked spotty from unevenly heated frying surface but tasted ok.<br>the accompanying cumberland sausage however was way too porky.<br><br>there&#39;s definitely value in their price point but they are no longer my go to joint for breakfast.

Level 1 of SMU&#39;s school of law is a place houses this coffee and tidbits store in which students gravitate to during the beak. They serve coffee, teh, ice honey lemon, milo etc hot and cold. Small cups cost 1.30 while a larger cup costs 1.50. The consistency is thick for the drinks and the coffee is a great morning wake up tool. If you want can drinks, these are availablen too. Most cost about $1.<br><br>Tidbits wise they serve sandwiches, salads, crispy seaweed chicken, paus and more most under $2. Recently, they have taken to sell brown rice salads which are healthy and filling. Very convenient food on the go indeed. A place where you can get your stomach fix.

text: Passed by this new cafe bar around my neighbourhood after work two evenings ago with the boyfriend... what a pleasant experience at this cosy cafe! Not only was the yummy food affordably priced... the service was tip top excellent too especially from this cute chubby service crew! The BF love lambs and tried their Herb Crusted Lamb Rack while I had the recommended MOB Burger. We both gave these 2 mains the thumbs up! They serve 5 different types of Brewerkz beer on tap and also a select range of bottled craft beer... this is very good news for drinkers like us in the Balestier neighbourhood! No longer have to travel to Clarke Quay for our beers! Their current promo is a FREE 6-inch thin crust with every 3 pints of beers ordered and of cos we went for that! We chose Meat Lover as our choice of the Free pizza! Came with a generous dose of toppings and just the right size for sharing after our mains! Will definately come back to try their other mains and bar munchies again! Thank you MOB Cafe for being in my neighbourhood! Feeling damn atas now... got Brewerkz in Balestier too!!! :)

text: MOB Cafe is a (very) new brewery cafe that has just opened up on Kim Keat Road, and conveniently under the apartment complex I live in.<br><br>The concept is intriguing- casual eatery serving beer, coffee, food, etc, yet they still have some growing pains. My one visit there during a lunch hour on a weekday showed a mobbed place (pun intended) with only one waitress. Getting her attention to just order drinks took more than 10 minutes and then another 10-15 for the drinks to actually be served. The beers are from brewerkz, so no complaints there!<br><br>While the slow service should have been an immediate red flag, we were too starving to find another place to eat, so opted to stay and take a chance to order the fish and chips, wings, and mozzarella sticks- all good and satisfying, but nothing to write home about.<br><br>They do not accept credit cards at the moment, so be sure to bring enough cash.<br><br>Mob Cafe has promise- can only hope the service improves and their menu options expands.

text: This place is a place with good intentions, but is often a hit and miss. <br><br>The decor is simple and comfortable, but the service isn&#39;t as refined. I absolutely LOVED the curry baked rice - I finished pretty much every grain in it, but my husband&#39;s tacos were lacking in flavour. The beer is good, of course, but the chicken leg was slightly underwhelming. <br><br>That said, however, the menu is priced very affordably, and we&#39;ve definitely put this on the list for a quick meal after work on very busy days, or a lazy weekend lunch.

text: Being a Joo Chiat local this little gem is a treat whenever guests come to town. I say a treat, because it can be spendy-per-pax if you choose the good dishes.<br><br>Having said that, I&#39;ve been a handful of times this year, and each visit has left me smiling and satisfied.<br><br>The servings come in small, medium and large, and they are quite large, so unless you are a big eater you&#39;ll want to curb your enthusiasm and select small and medium dishes - especially if you plan on trying a lot.<br><br>Stick to what Sin Hoi Sai excel in - Baby Kailan, Sambal Stingray, and the secret menu Red Wine Pork Ribs - all washed down with a longneck of Heineken or Tiger.<br><br>You may be tempted to smash up the Marmite Chicken or Guinness Pork Ribs, but although interesting and quirky, they aren&#39;t fantastic so I&#39;d suggest going the small portion for these.

text: Woken up at 2:30 am in the morning by the room next door blasting effing Selena Gomez and Rihanna.  Ooh na na, what&#39;s my name...?  I have a few names in mind for you...<br><br>Anyway, rather than kicking their door down, I decided that my energy would be better spent searching for some grubs, since I had roughly 5~6 hours to go until proper breakfast time.  <br><br>Sin Hoi Sai was one of the few places that open past 3:30 am in this quiet little area of Singapore, and as far as I could tell, Selena/Rihanna haters were welcomed.<br><br>Menu selection were listed on the lighted boards above the restaurant.  I went with the Indonesia chicken and baby Gai Lan since I recalled that both of those had pretty solid mentions.<br><br>The veggie came first, and it was solid with a nice garlic flavor.  Texture was crunchy and that slight bitterness that I like in Gai Lan really came through.  The Indonesian chicken came with a bit too much breading for my preference.  The taste was also a bit too salty for me.  <br><br>When I looked at all the menu selection again, I realized that pretty much of the chicken options were pretty much breaded...  They had shrimp and fish available that appear to have no breading, perhaps those would have fared better...<br><br>Well, next time I get woken up by RiRi, I will certainly keep that in mind...

text: Visit Sin Hoi Sai eating house for amazing Chinese food!!!! Highly recommend getting their fried prawns and fish!!!! Both the prawns and fish are fried to perfection and seasoned so well!!! The chilies also add an extra kick and more flavour to the prawns!!!! This place is known for seafood but also serves amazing meat dishes as well!!! Their fried chicken is delicious and the tofu with minced pork is extremely flavourful!!!! Their Chinese food is amazing, authentic and definitely worth trying!!!!!! They also serve the very popular Singapore drink iced jelly, which is also worth a try!!!!

I recently went to Singapore for vacation and one of my family friends invited us to eat here. He said that the food was much better than more well-known seafood restaurants in Singapore and it was much more affordable.<br><br>The ambiance was very similar to a restaurant in Vietnam, where most of the seats are outside and the chairs are plastic (if I recall correctly), and the exterior seems a little dingy. Don&#39;t let that fool you though, because the food is actually really good.<br><br>I didn&#39;t order the food so I can&#39;t recall everything, but I really enjoyed all of the vegetables we ordered and the Indonesian chicken! We also got the famed chili crabs and pepper crabs, and while they were good, I&#39;m not the biggest fan of crab so I didn&#39;t enjoy them as much as everyone else in my party did. The chrysanthemum tea was also really yummy! <br><br>I&#39;ll admit I&#39;m not a huge fan of seafood restaurants (though I love sushi and sashimi) and I had food poisoning whilst i was in Asia, but even I could tell that this is a really decent restaurant. If you want to save money but want to enjoy good seafood, definitely come here instead of the other famous restaurants. You&#39;ll basically get the same quality of food. If I come back to Singapore, I would definitely come back here as well. Perhaps I&#39;ll be healthier and be able to enjoy the food more next time!

text: This place is fine, but pricier than I would have liked. We paid about $270 for 11 people. The food tends to be a tad salty. My biggest gripe about this place was that they charged $2 per person for tea, and never once changed the leaves in the pot. This means, we paid $22 for one pot of chrysanthemum tea--that&#39;s outrageous and disgusting. Had it been 2 or 3 pots of tea, fine. But one pot of tea that gets topped up with only water? $22 is way way way too much! We ordered everything sized large, but some of the dishes were impressively small for a &#39;large size&#39;.<br><br>We ordered:<br>Chaipo Tofu--OK. Tofu quite soft. Chaipo not crispy though.<br>Guinness Pork Ribs--Very small portion. There was not enough pork ribs for everyone to have a single piece on their own. Tastes very good though, but portions were too small. Not worth it!<br>Cereal Prawn--The prawns were a little overcooked and dry. Cereal topping was not bad, but there were not that much cereal topping.<br>Salted Egg Squid--Very good! Squid was overcook and slightly chewy.<br>Yam Ring--OK. A bit salty.<br>Har Cheong Gai--Good and crispy!<br>Thai Style Chicken--Good! Folks liked this dish.<br>Sambal Kangkong--Very salty.<br>Garlic Huang Di Cai--Very salty.<br>Stir Fried Lala--Not as good as it was touted to be. Lots of shells that didn&#39;t have any meat in them.<br>Sun Moon Hor Fun--Very impressive with raw egg on top, but taste like regular horfun or pad see ew. Not very special.<br>Sap Gam Hor Fun--Not bad, but not that much wokhei flavor.<br>Mee Goreng--Too spicy for a lot of us.

text: I was in Singapore and my friends who lives here brought me out to this place. They did the ordering so I can&#39;t recall the names of everything ordered. I know we had the chili crabs, gailan, baby clams, eggplants, and fried chicken. Everything tasted really good! I felt like an insider eating here.

Sin Hoi Sai Eating House - If I lived anywhere closer to the East, I am guessing I would be here a lot more than I&#39;d be willing to admit. In a tight group of 8 friends, 7 of them live pretty close to Sin Hoi, and these 7 congregate here for dinner at least 2-3 times a week.<br><br>On the few occassions I&#39;ve been here, service has been excellent, also in part due to the fact that my friends are regulars. They swiftly take your order for beverages, leave, bring them to your table and collect your food orders while they are at it. On weekends this place does get crowded, so avoid peak dinner timings, or be prepared to wait for a table and for your food orders to be served.<br><br>We have a few favourites, I&#39;ll list them out - do be certain to give them a try! We love going for their sambal char siew fried rice, prepared with an adequate amount of spice and served in a portion good for 1 person. We swear by their Indonesian chicken dish, a slightly tangy crispy chicken dish where the fried chicken is glazed with a light, spicy gravy and onions. Being chicken fans, we almost always have to have their hot plate chilli ginger chicken as well - a bowl of it dropped right on to the hot plate at your table so it&#39;s sizzling and all the more enjoyable when had with the fried rice. The few other favourites include their baby kailan in oyster sauce, crispy noodles, fried salad you tiao, sambal kang kong and prawn paste chicken. <br><br>Their menu is expansive, and I wouldn&#39;t say that the food here is inexpensive, but given it&#39;s prime location and good quality, you pay for what you get. (I spend an average of $10 - 15 here including soft drinks and food shared with about 4-5 friends). I would definitely have to come back here many more times to try everything else on their menu. Lucky I have friends who are regulars.

text: standard tze char. nothing fancy. Pricing is a little high, I thought,  but then this is Katong.<br><br>I love san-lou horfun. This place&#39;s not bad, but still lacking that elusive wok-hei flavor.<br><br>The marmite chicken - I had better marmite dishes. I love marmite and the salty-bitterness of it all. The marmite flavor is not enough for me. (then again, for people who doesn&#39;t quite like the taste of marmite, they like this dish as it is more subtle). Also didn&#39;t like that the portion came mainly with chicken breast pieces only. <br><br>I will eat there if I am around the neighborhood. but nothing to hike the distance for.

My mum is in love with this eating house, and then she made us all fall in love with the awesome hor fun and sambal kangkong. There is a charred fried flavour that the chinese call &#34;wok hey&#34; with the hor fun and they have concocted a really solid sambal  for their vegetables. Prices are really reasonable, for a family dinner with 4-5 dishes, we would probbly pay $60- $70.<br><br> It can get really crowded and noisy over the weekends. So if you&#39;re starving maybe it&#39;s not so good an option to go for dinner on a weekend.

Known for its seafood and extensive ways in which fried rice and noodles can be served, Sin Hoi Sai is a secret gem for vegetarians too. It isn&#39;t on the menu, but there are a number of dishes cooked with mock meat that you can choose from, as well as customisable options from the regular menu. Just ask! <br><br>Highly recommended is the Indonesian Chicken. which always manages to fool even the most meaty of meat-eaters. It goes great with fried rice, which you can ask for with only veggies (instead of meat) and tofu (instead of egg, if you&#39;re vegan). <br><br>Go green with Garlic Kang Kong, a veg-friendly alternative to Sin Hoi Sai&#39;s Sambal Kang Kong. Just those 3 dishes and you&#39;re set; that&#39;s pretty much all I order every time I&#39;m there, which is pretty often :) <br><br>It&#39;s also cool for enjoying some beer before or after a big night out partying!

Having supper here is always the best way to cap a night of partying off. The explosion of tastes from the awesome Sambal Beef Fried Rice is always a good way to wake yourself up from that drunken night that almost ended with you in an alcohol coma. A plate of prawn paste chicken on the side should help with that burnt tongue from the sambal. Yup, do beware. It&#39;s spicy!<br><br>The operating hours are from 5pm to 4am however, they do start washing the place at about 345am so try to get there and place your orders by 330am. There are lots of parking lots within walking distance at Chapel Road, Chapel Close, Cheow Keng Road or Lor Stangee however, it can get quite busy at dinner time because of the many restaurants in the vicinity. Late nights, are never a problem.<br><br>I&#39;m there at least 3 times a week and I really hope to bump into you folk soon. See ya!

text: For a neighborhood coffeeshop, this one feels decidedly more &#39;atas&#39; (classy). On their wall, they proudly announce they provide &#34;a taste of Authentic Local Cuisine&#34;. Hahaha or something to that effect lah (my memory ain&#39;t so good anymore). <br><br>But truly, many dishes are well done. <br><br>I like their prawn paste chicken, beancurd on hot plate, and black pepper beef on hot plate. My parents (esp Mummy Dearest) give their stamp of approval for the beef dish, declaring it as very good. Hahaha yay. <br><br>I recall their sweet and sour pork being delish too. <br><br>All in all, even their toilets are nice. Mum said &#34;Wah. Their toilet so spacious, and dry, and well-maintained&#34;. If my mother can use the toilet at a neighborhood coffeeshop, you know it&#39;s passed the highest levels of quality control. I jest, but you get the drift. <br><br>With a 55inch (60 inch) TV for the old fogies, this place ain&#39;t too shabby for affordable local dishes. <br><br>Perfect supper place too. Me likey.

text: They&#39;ve completely remodeled and the food also tastes better than I remember. Either that or I&#39;ve acclimated to local tastes. A good spot for a late night meal (or any time really, I just find myself here late at night when other spots in the neighborhood are closed).

text: REAL GOOD PETS<br><br>This tiny bakery produces phenomenal egg tarts or as I call them Portuguese egg tarts (PETs), but here they&#39;re uniquely square shaped. They&#39;re right up there in quality with Golden Gate Bakery of San Francisco Chinatown. <br><br>Rich sweet creamy egg custard filling in a flaky dainty crust. Its a luxury indulgence given that two PETs will buy you a nice complete lunch @Maxwell Food Centre a few blocks away.   Across the street from Buddah Tooth Relic Temple &amp; Museum.

text: We visited the Chinatown Heritage Centre the day before, where one of the exhibits mentioned Tong Heng and their famous egg tarts. I love egg tarts so I made it a point to check this place out.<br><br>Conclusion - solid egg tart but nothing special. There are no advantages of making the egg tart in a diamond shape versus the regular circular base. Not worth going out of your way to try.

text: DOUBLE THUMBS UP for their egg tarts!! <br><br>Tong Heng is a real timeless institution that has been around for at least 80 years. They are well-known among the locals for having the best egg tart in Singapore. And when they are that famous, I just had to check it out for myself! <br><br>The store lies at the heart of Chinatown, just along South Beach Road.  The shop itself is petite in space, but interior is very bright and proper. They also have quite an arrays of delicacies that are displayed inside the glass cabinet and of course, coffee/drink to go along with the sweets. <br><br>The diamond shaped egg tart is truly unique, the shells have thick layers of crisp pastry almost like it was deep fried. And the custard filling is so smooth, wobbly and a bliss in each bite. Each tart cost around $1.90. Small price to pay for one-of-a-kind sweet indulgence.

text: Authentic bakery in Chinatown! <br><br>Food/Drink: the coconut egg tart was something else! We&#39;ve never had one before and this is just one of the many places around Singapore to get it. A perk is you can get a box full of a dozen pretty easily. <br><br>Price: only 2.20 SGD for one egg tart. <br><br>Atmosphere: We came in in the middle of the day when it was very hot, there was a seating area where you could enjoy your treats that was air conditioned and it was a perfect break from the sweltering heat in chinatown.<br><br>Tips: They sell a variety of baked goods other than egg tarts!

text: They are now $2 a pop. Still a long queue during this COVID pandemic period. New ordering system is quick and efficient.

It&#39;s funny to squeeze in this tiny shop usually to a crowd of grandmas buying boxes or some guy with a video camera zooming in on the little pig pastries. The cashiers are really efficient and the space is small but clean and brightly lit, with all the pastries nicely displayed. I keep bringing friends here and really recommend their egg tarts. Tong Heng mastered the recipe with fresh flaky crust and soft custard filling. I actually love the COCONUT egg tart more than the original as you get more texture and sweetness from the shredded coconut. I&#39;ll always make Tong Heng a stop when I&#39;m in town :)

text: I decided to go to Tong Heng for their diamond shaped egg tarts due to their long family history in the business from watching a food bloggers video. The egg tarts were alright, maybe because I&#39;m a fan of the flaky crust, I didn&#39;t enjoy it as much. It is definitely not terrible, above average, but it just didn&#39;t meet my expectations.
Nice egg tart, wasn&#39;t sure I&#39;d like it but it was delicious. Nice clean store and helpful employees

text: Came here in mid-morning for some famous rectangular dan ta, after a morning of exploring Chinatown nearby.<br><br>The cashier lady was an older obasan who was extremely patient and kind with us as we scoured the display window for a avoid-the-sun snack. We decided on dan ta&#39;s each, their powdered bread...which I totally forgot the name! The baked goods weren&#39;t spectacular, but that&#39;s because we&#39;re spoiled with delicious California baked goods and cheap/fresh Taiwanese bakery bread when we travel.<br><br>Their dan ta has a crunchier and thinner (not flaky) crust and sweeter egg in the center. It was pretty good, just made differently and just as fresh. Their powdered bread was not the business. We felt like it was just bread with powdered sugar on top...nothing special. Looking around, we saw that they also offered other baked sweets as well as more &#34;kitchen-made&#34; orders like soups and porridges. <br><br>It&#39;s great to get a dan ta if you&#39;re in the Ann Siang Hill/Chinatown area, but it&#39;s not some place I would say is a &#34;distinguishing&#34; part of Singaporean local eats.

text: Just get the egg tarts. Forget about the rest. <br><br>The coffee is terrible but they do warn you it is from a sachet mix. <br><br>The egg tart is usually warm so it is best to eat it right there and then. The custard is wobbly soft and the crust is a bit crumbly when you bite into it. Have it cool and the shape holds better but it also means it is slightly firmer. It is sweet but not overly so it does make a good tea time (or any time) snack. <br><br>It is a nice treat to have once in a while.
The steamed egg is too sweet. But the egg tart is the best I&#39;ve had in Singapore. Sooooo good!!!

text: My expectations were high for what I&#39;ve been told are the best egg tarts EVER. Perhaps that was the problem. <br><br>These bad boys are diamond shaped with a light and wobbly custard. I just didn&#39;t really like the crust. It was too buttery and very crumbly which just wasn&#39;t my cup of tea. I also like my custard sweeter but again this is probably just down to personal preferences. <br><br>I actually preferred their char siew pastry puffs which was petite but packed with flavour. <br><br>Best ever? Hmm, debatable. Definitely worth a pick-up if I&#39;m in the area though.

text: Service/ Ive seen comments on good service but maybe it was an off day but they were not very welcoming/nice <br>Food/ egg tart and moon cake was good. <br>Atmosphere/ overall fine. <br>Price/ $1.70/egg tart<br><br>Diamond shaped egg tarts was a first. I feel like the ratio of crust to egg was different.<br><br>Because it&#39;s a seemingly pretty popular place it seemed like their egg tarts had a decent turn over so getting fresh warmer ones may be the norm. The custard is not too thick and it is silky which is nice. I tried the normal one not the coconut. <br><br>The moon cake with lotus paste was also good. <br><br>Not overly wow-ed by the place. If I was in the area and craving egg tarts maybe I&#39;d return, but at this point I wouldn&#39;t go out of my way to do so.

text: Came here in mid-morning for some famous rectangular dan ta, after a morning of exploring Chinatown nearby.<br><br>The cashier lady was an older obasan who was extremely patient and kind with us as we scoured the display window for a avoid-the-sun snack. We decided on dan ta&#39;s each, their powdered bread...which I totally forgot the name! The baked goods weren&#39;t spectacular, but that&#39;s because we&#39;re spoiled with delicious California baked goods and cheap/fresh Taiwanese bakery bread when we travel.<br><br>Their dan ta has a crunchier and thinner (not flaky) crust and sweeter egg in the center. It was pretty good, just made differently and just as fresh. Their powdered bread was not the business. We felt like it was just bread with powdered sugar on top...nothing special. Looking around, we saw that they also offered other baked sweets as well as more &#34;kitchen-made&#34; orders like soups and porridges. <br><br>It&#39;s great to get a dan ta if you&#39;re in the Ann Siang Hill/Chinatown area, but it&#39;s not some place I would say is a &#34;distinguishing&#34; part of Singaporean local eats.

text: I can&#39;t believe I completely forgot to write a review for Tong Heng!  It&#39;s been nearly a month since I&#39;ve had these and...I&#39;m still dreaming about them.  I happened to be in the area and stopped by to pick up a couple tarts (I&#39;m kicking myself for not getting more!) and char siew pastry puffs for the family and they were definitely pleasantly surprised.  I didn&#39;t get a chance to sit down at Tong Heng&#39;s to have them fresh, but trust me, heat them up a little when you get home and I can bet they&#39;re as good as they are fresh.  If not, then I&#39;m really missing out.  The egg tarts are lightly sweet and just egg-y enough and the pastry is a little different being crumbly rather than flaky.  And I love it.  The char siew pastry puffs are just as good, in my opinion, sweet and flaky, but with the right amount of savory to do the char siew justice.  So it&#39;s whatever you&#39;re in the mood for.  Or have them both!
