text: Located near Maxwell Food Centre and in the vicinity of Chinatown, you find this shop opposite a Taoist Temple along South Bridge Road. I usually recommend this confectionary shop to my foreign friends as they sell decent egg tarts and other pastries. Good for our taste bug, but bad for our stomach! <br><br>Eat the egg tarts warm as you get the best out of this delicious snack, the others are average - nothing to shout about but it&#39;s worth giving them a try. I would recommend buying a few and head elsewhere to enjoy it. Like Carolyn - the other reviewer had mentioned, the coffee is mediocre.<br><br>So if you are nearby Maxwell Food Centre or<br>Chinatown, remember to head down! Best is to leave some space for some egg tarts after a meal, you will probably feel very satisfied. Enjoy!

text: Just get the egg tarts. Forget about the rest. <br><br>The coffee is terrible but they do warn you it is from a sachet mix. <br><br>The egg tart is usually warm so it is best to eat it right there and then. The custard is wobbly soft and the crust is a bit crumbly when you bite into it. Have it cool and the shape holds better but it also means it is slightly firmer. It is sweet but not overly so it does make a good tea time (or any time) snack. <br><br>It is a nice treat to have once in a while.

text: My expectations were high for what I&#39;ve been told are the best egg tarts EVER. Perhaps that was the problem. <br><br>These bad boys are diamond shaped with a light and wobbly custard. I just didn&#39;t really like the crust. It was too buttery and very crumbly which just wasn&#39;t my cup of tea. I also like my custard sweeter but again this is probably just down to personal preferences. <br><br>I actually preferred their char siew pastry puffs which was petite but packed with flavour. <br><br>Best ever? Hmm, debatable. Definitely worth a pick-up if I&#39;m in the area though.

Tong Heng French Toast! *Slurp*', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Tong Heng French Toast! *Slurp*'}]
text: Everybody LOVES the Egg tart at Tong Heng!<br>Why? Cos it&#39;s simply AWESOME and in my humble opinion, NO other egg tarts in SG can ever be compared to this diamond-shaped egg tart.<br><br>Many people have come and bought egg tarts here but to enjoy Tong Heng to the fullest, there are some things at Tong Heng you gotta know.<br><br>1. If you are buying Egg Tarts to-go, kindly note that boxes will only be used to put your egg tarts if you purchase more than 5 egg tarts. Preferably buy in multiples of 5 so that you can ensure all your egg tarts will be safe in box with comfortable space to keep the egg tarts intact.<br><br>2. Cant finish the awesome tarts and dont know what to do with them? Store them in the refrigerator! You&#39;ll be surprised that the Cold Egg tarts actually taste pretty good too. (I personally like it very much :P ) If refrigerated egg tarts are not your thing, you can still keep them in the fridge but just heat the tarts up slightly and they&#39;ll still taste marvelous.<br><br>3. A well kept secret in Tong Heng is a dish that only the INSIDERs will know. They dont have it on their menu perhaps cos it takes a lot of effort to make it but if you have the time for a good sinful afternoon tea snack, you gotta order the Tong Heng French Toast. <br><br>&#34;What? French Toast?&#34; you ask.<br><br>Yes, I kid you not. Their french toast is not the typical &#34;ang moh&#34; toast soaked and fried in egg only, it actually comes slabbed with a layer of delicious KAYA too!<br><br>The portion of the French Toast is pretty huge so do bring a friend or 2 to enjoy this delectable treat together. (Dont be selfish ya!) Be warned though, that it can be pretty oily and greasy. But for a once a blue moon indulgence, I&#39;m willing to accept all the calories that its worth. <br><br>All this writing is making me salivate thinking about the egg tarts and the french toast...GOSH!!! Time to make a trip down Tong Heng again SOON!

Based on what I ordered which was the lotus bread w salted egg. I wanted to try something other than what everyone was ordering. The bread had very little filling,after 2 bites all the fillings were gone but i still had the bread left. So i just tossed it.

text: I am rather particular with my egg tarts.  Call me an egg tart connoisseur, if you will.<br><br>Golden Gate Bakery in SF, mediocre at best.  Never understood the long lines.<br><br>Tai Cheong in HK.  The creme de la creme of egg tarts.  Well worth the long lines.<br><br>Tong Heng in SG.  Among the best.  Try to get them when they are fresh from the oven.  Egg tart orgasm guaranteed, from the crust to the creamy egg filling.  And perfectly sweet.

text: The egg tarts are unique, not just in shape but also in the way they are made. The crust is not the traditional cookie or flaky crust. Instead it&#39;s like a very thin pie crust. The custard itself is also lighter than the typical ones you get from HK or other parts of the world, kinda like soya beancurd. It&#39;s a nice change. I wish they came piping hot from oven, though.<br><br>JONASAPPROVED!

text: I can&#39;t believe I completely forgot to write a review for Tong Heng!  It&#39;s been nearly a month since I&#39;ve had these and...I&#39;m still dreaming about them.  I happened to be in the area and stopped by to pick up a couple tarts (I&#39;m kicking myself for not getting more!) and char siew pastry puffs for the family and they were definitely pleasantly surprised.  I didn&#39;t get a chance to sit down at Tong Heng&#39;s to have them fresh, but trust me, heat them up a little when you get home and I can bet they&#39;re as good as they are fresh.  If not, then I&#39;m really missing out.  The egg tarts are lightly sweet and just egg-y enough and the pastry is a little different being crumbly rather than flaky.  And I love it.  The char siew pastry puffs are just as good, in my opinion, sweet and flaky, but with the right amount of savory to do the char siew justice.  So it&#39;s whatever you&#39;re in the mood for.  Or have them both!
The steamed egg is too sweet. But the egg tart is the best I&#39;ve had in Singapore. Sooooo good!!!

text: This place has killed all other egg tarts for me. I&#39;ve been coming here since I was a tot, and seen various outlets appear in malls and then die a torturous death. Whenever I pass by, I have to pick up some. It&#39;s not me, it&#39;s the the siren song of these tarty things. The auntie will always ask &#34;How many you want?&#34; and I&#39;ll go &#34;However many can go into a box. Squeezy also never mind&#34;. <br><br>Prices have gone up significantly over the years but the standard is just as good. Tip for the uninitiated - these babies aren&#39;t meant to be kept overnight, else the eggy bits will get a little watery and the crust soggy. Also, when you open the box in the morning, you&#39;ll find that the eggy part has an earthquake like split down the middle, not sure why. Either that or some have gone missing, and your pesky little brother will vehemently deny all knowledge of the incident, all the while wiping crumbs off his face.

text: I very rarely like egg tarts but I&#39;ll make an exception for Tong Heng&#39;s diamond shaped ones! Eating is a bit of a challenge though - you need a large enough plate and a hungry stomach to gobble it all up at once - when eaten warm, the custard bit is soft and oozy while the pastry is flaky and yummy.<br><br>One tart is pretty sizeable and makes a great way to cap off a meal!

text: You can probably get the best egg tarts in Singapore here. <br><br>The go-to place for egg tarts and &#39;Lou Por Bang&#39; aka Wife Biscuits, Tong Heng has been churning out these delactable treats for more than 80 years, and judging by the queues you see everyday, you know you wont be let down. <br><br>The egg custard they produce is soft and amazingly smooth. Especially when it&#39;s served warm and made even more delicious when coupled with an equally well-executed, flaky pastry base.

Egg tarts are segregated into two leagues: there are egg tarts, and then there are godly egg tarts. <br><br>Tong Heng&#39;s egg tarts belong firmly in the latter category.<br><br>The custard filling is slightly wobbly, not too much, just enough to titillate but still solid enough to require biting through. There I was half slurping the eggy custard held in its incredibly crisp and fluffy tart cup, not being able to get over the fact that I only found out about Singapore&#39;s best egg tart quarter of a century later.<br><br>Tong Heng also sells gai zai beng (very rarely found in Singapore anymore) and some other confectionaries which I didn&#39;t pay attention to.

The first bite into a piece of egg tart from Tong Heng and already an impression was created for us. Traditionally, Chinese egg tarts are made with shortcrust pastry and many true old school bakeries still make them this way. Over the years, many bakeries gradually started making egg tarts with puff pastry. The diamond-shaped Chinese egg tarts at Tong Heng look like they are made with shortcrust pastry. Take a bite into the pastry and there&#39;s an element of surprise there. The pastry is made up of thin, flaky and crisp layers that make up the shell of the tart. It&#39;s a perfect balance between shortcrust and flaky puff pastry. The crust is what makes Tong Heng stand out. Truly, these egg tarts are one of the best we will probably have in a while. At only $1.60 for each egg tart, the more reason you should eat more than one.

text: Tong Heng is the perfect treat after a tiring shopping day in Chinatown, around afternoon tea time.<br><br>Egg tart is a must! The best egg tarts in Singapore! If I da bao it, the more likely I&#39;ll get fined for eating in the MRT hahaha :D

text: Went to this bakery since I read the review about the egg tart. It&#39;s different than the other egg tart: boxy shape, thicker and non-flaky crust, filling is less sweet and thicker compared to the regular egg tart. I still prefer the Portuguese style flaky egg tart, but this isn&#39;t bad. I&#39;ll be back to try the other pastries that looks good too.

I don&#39;t profess to be an egg tart expert, but the diamond shaped tarts here are pretty damn good. Shuffle in amongst the crowd, speak up and have your money at the ready. Before long you&#39;ll be stuffing a squidgy, warm-centred, egg tart in your face out the front.

After eating our Hokkien style noodles at food stall #7, we back tracked through the hustle and bustle of Chinatown to get dessert since our stomachs were still not full from the late lunch and well starvation on a Jetstar plane ride can do crazies to your mind and stomach. So back we went to Tong Heng as I pointed it out initially saying...&#34;Hey, Tong Heng. Isn&#39;t that the place where in our guide book it said it had the best egg tarts?&#34; Well that&#39;s already a mighty fine statement when saying best egg tarts. Back in San Francisco, the Golden Gate Bakery totally states that they have the best egg tarts and makes patrons wait from their loooooong vacation to finally get them (I won&#39;t go into that story as there were about 3-5 times throughout a calendar year where we went to the store and they were on vacation). So the boyfriend and I crossed the street to Tong Heng and saw two different types of egg tarts. More curious is that the shape is something we&#39;ve never encountered in your typical eggy tart. Diamond shaped? That&#39;s just weird. Well not to discriminate with shape, we bought one of the regular egg tarts and one with coconut. Came out to $2.90 (Coconut one was $1.50 and regular was $1.40).<br><br>Now, I&#39;m not a big fan of egg tarts in general, but I&#39;ll eat them regardless. Food is food and if it&#39;s supposed to be good, then heck I&#39;ll eat it. So I took a bite out of the normal one. Just wasn&#39;t what I was expecting. A bit runny and missing something. Just not sure what but it didn&#39;t blow me away. I decided to take on the coconut one. Super runny and liquid-like. Maybe it&#39;s supposed to be that way, but I&#39;m used to something different.<br><br>I&#39;ll stick to the ones back in California, especially the Portuguese style ones.
Yummy egg tarts and char sew sou. <br>the crisps are alright, but a tad too pricey.<br><br>ps. the closest parking lot is the maxwell food court open carpark.
Eggs tarts!!!!!!!! My favorite! I haven&#39;t been here yet or even in Singapore lol but the looks of it is very eye catching so maybe one day!!! On my Bucket list

Great egg tarts are hard to come by these days. Although they are pretty much sold everywhere in Singapore, most are nothing like Tong Heng&#39;s. I love the custard filling as it is wobbly and smooth. When eaten warm, having the custard slide down your throat is like a piece of heaven. The tart is buttery, giving it a luxurious taste. It crumbles just enough, yet holds the eggy custard together well. <br><br>While the egg tarts I have had at tong heng have been consistently good over the years, the service has slowly deteriorated. It almost seems as if there is some sort of double-standard going on where tourists get better quality of service whereas locals are treated impatiently. I guess it doesn&#39;t really bother me too much as I tend to dash in and out of the store pretty quickly, getting my share of egg tarts but if you are going to stand there and deliberate over what to get, be prepared for annoyed looks and somewhat rude service.

Came here twice during my mini trip to Singapore. It was right by my hotel in the Chinatown area and the egg tarts were delish. The filling was gooey and smooth (YUMMM!). Second time I came during the evening to pick up some morning snacks on my flight back and there was a line out the shop. Definitely recommend coming here in the afternoon to avoid the crowds.

text: Unknown to many, Cafe Galilee makes it&#39;s presence known in many national libraries and also, catering services in many government events. I was at a public service event whereby I noticed the food was catering from this company.<br><br>Most of the snacks were very light, not gerlat. Even the brownie was very light, I usually fear brownies from caterers, as they&#39;re usually the commercially produced, super hard and dense/frozen for a long time, brownies. <br><br>The cheesecake was a cube of cream cheese, over a light cake sponge, no biscuit, graham cracker based. I actually liked the cake base, another modification which helps make these snacks &#34;lighter&#34;. <br><br>The chicken pastry, which is the halal version of the char siew soh/seremban siew pau-style, tasted a bit strange. The pastry smelt and tasted very buttery and the chicken was cooked to taste like char siew.<br><br>Still, reasonably okay food caterer, for tea snacks for any occasion.

Situated within Ang Mo Kio library, this is actually one of the more comfortable Cafe Galilee branches I&#39;ve visited. <br><br>Don&#39;t expect much from the food. Other than deep fried finger food (which can&#39;t really go wrong) such as fries, potato wedges, and chicken nuggets, it isn&#39;t that great. The pasta and other stuff fill up your stomach in a pinch, but unless you have no choice there&#39;s no way you should go for the food when there are so many other good kopitiams nearby.<br><br>The coffee situation is slightly better. The hot chocolate is not bad, although the coffees such as latte is nothing to shout about. It&#39;s nice to sit with a nice book or with some friends, but there are much better places to go in the vicinity if you don&#39;t have to be at the library.

text: I would commit murder for one of these heavenly tarts. Having tasted a whole range of cheese tarts from Pablo to KFC (which was surprisingly decent), Bake trumps its rivals by a large margin. The buttery crust is firm and manages to hold together throughout the plate-to-mouth journey. Cheese filling is the right balance of sweet &amp; savory, which produces the most divine flavor burst in one&#39;s mouth. Breaks my heart to drop $3.50 on just ONE tart, but sometimes this indulgence is necessary! <br><br>Protip: if you&#39;re getting it to-go, microwave for 3 minutes to get the cheese filling gooey again!

It is a bit on the pricy side. Think I should&#39;ve warmed it up first to get the full effect since it wasn&#39;t warm or gooey as I was eating mine as others have mentioned.

text: Full of hype? Check.<br>Lives up to its hype? Check.<br><br>I was lucky to be at ion at 11am on a Wednesday morning and there were only 3 people in line. I joined the line hoping to try this famous cheese tart.<br><br>Every customer is only allowed to buy 12, and I ended up getting a dozen, because well, I&#39;m already in line so why not?? <br><br>The tarts are super delicious when they are fresh out of the oven. Sinfully rich but not too much that it makes you sick. They are pretty pricey at $3.50 per tart, but well, I&#39;m only here once a year.

Oh my dear Bake.. why oh why, can&#39;t you come to the US??? I&#39;ve tried the impersonators and it&#39;s just NOT the same. Last time I visited I had to wait in a long line to try these tasty treats but luckily this time I was able to walk up and get my favorite treat. SO delicious - if you haven&#39;t tried &#39;em you seriously need to ASAP! :)

text: At $3.50 a tart, I feel like a baller for ordering 8 tarts. There is only one item in their menu, which is the yellow tart that you see in the pictures. The tart reminds me of cheesecake filling that has been accidentally put inside the microwave.I refrigerated the tart overnight and it tasted like cheesecake. In the website, it also suggested to freeze the tart for an ice-cream like texture. Pretty cute concept.  The tart shell was buttery and holds up to its molten filling well. The shell was not at all soggy. <br><br>Overall, this is a good tart, but it was not mind blowing. I would not queue more than 10 minutes to buy this. The start of the queue starts some distance from the store. It is under the escalator near the Royce chocolate shop. They hand you a number after you have reached the head of the queue, you walk to the store and pass your number to the person in the store and then place your order.

text: Before I came to singapore, I heard there are many places selling cheese tarts. One of the cheese tart place was close to my hotel. Bake Cheese Tart from Hokkaido, have a crumbly exterior, fluffy inner texture, and cheesy warm soft filling!! I heard it has up to 3-hour long waiting lines. When I got there, I saw a long line outside of the bakery. But I only waited 15-20mins. If I could, I wanted to buy more but I had to be satisfied with one dozen. It is SD 3.50 per piece.<br>It is just the most heavenly cheese tarts. One of the best cheese tart I&#39;ve ever tasted. If it could last long, I would have bought several boxes to bring home. It&#39;s freshly baked, just so soft and melts in your mouth. I couldn&#39;t stop eating them. Sometimes I still dream about the delicious tarts!

text: I was lucky to have my cousin queue for me once so I didn&#39;t have to. Tried one of the tarts right away and instantly fell in love with it! I&#39;m usually not a fan of something related to cheese but this is stupendous. Literally the only kind of tart I&#39;d eat again and again in my life. It&#39;s just soooo goooood.<br><br>The tarts are really yummy but the price is a bit on a high side (@$3.5) but I guess that&#39;s fine considering the tarts are flown in from Hokkaido and the rental in Ion.<br>Now that I have tried, I really love it and crave it every moment but I wouldn&#39;t queue more than 15 minutes. I&#39;ll repurchase IF I was in the area, and no sign of long queue.

Your review helps others learn about great local businesses.Baked Cheese Tarts are the new in thing people! Especially with the famous Japanese BAKE Inc. (BAKE) leading the trend come 29 Apr 2016 with their first S.E.A flagship in Singapore! Located at ION Orchard, the Singapore store will be BAKE CHEESE TART&#39;s flagship store for Southeast Asia. YAY. <br><br>For those not in the know yet, BAKE hails from Hokkaido, Japan, and that ensures the creamiest and smoothest cream cheese mousse in the snappiest shortcrust tart. The cheese mousse is created by blending three different types of cream cheese together - two from Hokkaido and one from France. The pastry goes through a two-step process which leaves it with a distinct crunchy yet fluffy texture. Absolutely gorgeous i tell you.  <br><br>To ensure the highest quality, the cheese tarts are actually produced in Hokkaido and flown over to Singapore! Baking is done here so that we can piping hot, creamy and flowy cheese tarts. Such dedication to excellence i say. We can certainly expect the same flavor and quality from BAKE and it&#39;s even fresher than if you beg a friend to bring it back for you.<br><br>For $3.50 a pop, you can dig into one of these rich creamy babies. I can&#39;t imagine why anyone would stop at 1 though! Get a box of 6 for $19.50 and share the love (WITH ME PLEASE)!

text: I happen to be in the Orchard area on a Monday morning and my first thought was &#34;Cheese Tart for Breakfast!&#34;  BAKE opens at 10am and I arrived less than 10 minutes before opening.  No one was at the queue, so I roamed to the store front to check things out.  The tarts are baking in the oven and one of the staff waved at me to ask me to queue.  When I got to the queue, there were three ladies waiting.  5 more minutes until opening and about 15 more people are in queue.  A staff came out to the queue right at 10am sharp to hand out confirmation cards to the first two people.  10:03am and it was my turn!  The staff looked at my baby and I and asked how many I was getting. When I said a dozen, she was like &#34;oh, only 12, ok, here is your card&#34; as if she was expecting me to buy more with a baby in tow. Thank you for acknowledging my baby as a person!  The cashier was very friendly and informed me that the tarts can be refrigerated up to 4 days, or kept frozen for up to one month! Don&#39;t microwave.  Reheat in toaster, oven or air fryer at 200C for 30 seconds to a minute.  Got it!  Out the door we go to try these babies.  By now my 20 month old is screaming &#34;Chee taat Chee taat.&#34;  I carefully peeled the sticker off to open the box.  I really appreciate BAKE&#39;s thoughtfulness in designing their boxes.  Each tart has it own &#34;compartment&#34; so they don&#39;t bump into each other and become mush.  First bite into the freshly baked tart is the crunchy crust that snaps off, then comes the warm fluffy, light and whipped cream like cheese filing that&#39;s has a hint of tartness.  The contrast of the crunchy shell and of fluffy cheese filling is heavenly.  I slurped the cheese filling down like one would with whipped cream, and finished off the crunchy crust with the next few bites.  15 mins late, after I settled by baby down for a drink, the cheese tart shells are getting softer and losing its crunchiness.  Now it has become more of a soft cookie texture.  When I got home, put some in the fridge, and a couple in the freezer to try the different ways of eating these babies.  The refrigerated ones tasted just ok.  It&#39;s sort of like an over beaten cheesecake, nothing like ice cream.  While the filing is soft, it has a lot of air bubbles, so it&#39;s not creamy.  The frozen ones were more like frozen cheesecake, hard and crumbly.   Hubby and my children tried it and no one care for the frozen ones.  <br><br>So my conclusion is that the BAKE cheese tarts are best eaten right after you buy them.  Enjoy the contrast of crunchy cookie shell and the fluffy whipped filling.  <br><br>Are they worth 1-3 hr wait? Nope!  If I need a cheese tart fix, the bakery across has lava cheese tarts, while not as fluffy and whipped cream like, those were creamier, cheaper, and no queue.

text: This place is also known as the Lorong Ah Soo market. The ground level is the wet market where you need to come early to get the freshest fish and meat and vegetables. It gets very crowded especially on weekends when many people do their weekly marketing. I didn&#39;t realize people living in Hougang (those nearer buangkok or seng kang area) and Tai Keng Gardens and Serangoon will also travel all the way here to get their grocery too. Apparently it is fresher here. I don&#39;t think you can get beef here though. <br><br>There are also the sundry shops here as well as stalls selling fruits, herbs and flowers. <br><br>The upper level is the food center. It is also crowded on weekend mornings. The well known Lorong Ah Soo lor mee stall is here. <br><br>There is only one Malay stall which has pretty good lontong. <br><br>The bcm, prawn noodle soup, fried carrot cake and nasi lemak are also nice. Follow the queues. <br><br>There is also a stall that sells the fried carrot cake fingers which is not so commonly found now. <br><br>The best part is you can still get local coffee for 90 cents. <br><br>Oh and there are escalators and elevators. Perfect to get around with your heavy shopping cart or bag.

text: One of my favourite hawker food centre for lunch in Singapore! <br><br>My top 4 recommended food stalls are:<br>(1) Cantonese Delights wanton noodle, located at the 2nd floor at the corner with long queue daily. The owners are very friendly, the char siew so far the best I&#39;ve tried in this market and full of a variety of choices such as curry gravy, chicken cutlets, yong tao fu and etc.<br>(2) Jin Hua 金華 Fish Head Bee Hoon (2nd flr), I like the very thick milky soup which is more indulgent and creamier.<br>(3) An Kee Braised Duck Rice (2nd flr), cheap and nice. The duck meat was braised nicely with flavour, and the &#39;herbal&#39; soup is my favourite overall.<br>(4) Fragrant Hong Kong Pork Rib Rice (2nd flr), I used to eat the steamed rice with chicken / pork rib, it&#39;s soft and juicy!<br><br>There&#39;re more nice foods like Koay Chap, Mixed soup / Seafood soup, Malays food and etc which I couldn&#39;t remember their name :D Free free to explore over there!

text: Singapore is a wonderful place for food lovers of all type - including food hawkers. Today, we were particularly craving for some rustic street food. That&#39;s why our morning was spent roaming around Hong Lim Food Center. Hong Lim Food Center is located right in the heart of Chinatown. Therefore, this place can be seen as one of the most rustic street food places in Singapore. Offering authentic Chinese dishes with added twists of the Singaporeans, foods here are out of the world!<br><br>We tried fried Kway Teow Mee, which in our opinion, is a superb dish. This wok dish is not too oily, yet smoky and very flavorful, thanks to the secret mixture of soy sauce and fish sauce. It&#39;s evenly coated in beaten egg, creating a semi-wet &#34;Pad Thai-like&#34; dish. The smoke flavor come from the hot wok really makes this dish especially memorizing for us.<br><br>Recommendation: Kway Teow Mee (stall 02-17)<br><br>For more review, visit us at: <a href="/redir?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.thecoupleeats.com%2Fsingapore-food-diary-7-places-eat-first-time-visitors%2F&amp;s=b318345faa43f47c2cc5838f381314be08d4dc396a1749d7fcc6aec9a2c56019" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">thecoupleeats.com/singap…</a>

text: Not bad for early morning shops <br>There&#39;s a second floor too so don&#39;t forget to drop by <br>We came on Friday at 7a to catch some good food before our flight<br>There&#39;s not much must eat food here based on trip advisor or Yelp<br>We tried the kway teo mee which was ok<br>Also got a great sour soup drink though at a nearby stand !

HL didn&#39;t really stand out to me as a tourist, when I went to hawker fares.<br><br>I had lunch here and a cup of fresh juice, and prices were just average. I found that juice was cheaper in Chinatown! Surprise surprise. AND just as good. I had a fish soup with noodles, and it seemed pretty slow that lunch time even with all the students and business people eating there. The vendor had to take out some fish cuts from his plastic tupperware underneath the stand and put it into the soup to make my meal. That&#39;s how slow it was!<br><br>Anyhow, the place isn&#39;t too dirty which is a plus. And shoutout to the REAL MVP&#39;s of the food centre...the old ladies and men who wear bright green/orange and pick up after your dirty tables! They&#39;re the ones who are tirelessly working hard to clean tables so the next round of customers can have a place to eat. There wasn&#39;t a diverse selection in my opinion, but I did notice that it was pretty accessible between our itinerary as we walked around Ann Siang Hill, Clarke Quay, Chinatown, and even parts of Maxwell Centre. Good location, basic stalls.
Good choice! Awesome food -noodles and rice. My local friends recommended me to go there.
Back for the street food legends, just follow the lines!<br><br>Fried noodles, pork noodles, more!

One of the highest concentration of good hawker fare in SG - of particular note for those that I go to whenever I&#39;m nearby - dumpling, minced meat noodle, crayfish hor fun, fried kway tiao, curry chicken mee, etc. Would be 5 stars if the dining environment is nicer
A good, but not great Hawker center.  Not as good as I was expecting based on reviews and recommendations from locals, but had a nice kaya toast with softboiled eggs breakfast here.

text: Well, it was my first day in Singapore and I was looking for some place to eat (not actually knowing all that much about the place mind you) so I decided to check out Chinatown, suspecting that I would find some really authentic restaurants down there. Anyway, my first discovery when I steps out of the MRT station was your standard shopping mall with standard shopping mall cafes, however when I walked outside I suddenly found myself in this place - my first experience of a Singapore Hawker&#39;s Market. I must say that I was instantly impressed. Okay, it is nowhere near as large as the Chinatown Complex, but I hadn&#39;t discovered that at this stage, so I spent some time wandering up and down the stalls. The juice stall that I came across was amazing, especially since they offered drinks that would never exist in Australia. Here I had a dragonfruit and mango juice, but I also down many, many watermelon juices in my time here. All I can say is that if you are in Singapore and are looking for a place to eat, the hawker&#39;s markets are the place to go.

text: This is the food center to eat at while in Singapore. But get there early as the lines are long at most stalls. This place is filled with hawker legends. You&#39;ll be spoiled for choices.<br><br>Avoid Newton Food Center, come here.

One of those old school hawker centers that I wish would have fewer people!<br><br>At peak lunch hour, the lines are just crazily long. I usually try to go late which also means that you risk having your favorite stall running out.<br><br>I know i know....my nonsensical first world problem dilemma.

A hawker center filled with great food at prices that don&#39;t hurt the wallet at all! My recommendations are:<br><br>Crayfish Hor Fun<br>Ji Ji Wanton Mee<br>Tai Wah Pork Noodle (long queues during lunch hour)<br>Cantonese Delights

Hong Lim Complex has been known for its selection of delectable local foods for decades, with owners honing their craft with pride and finesse. From more well-known foods like Bak Kut Teh and Fish Soup, to rarer finds like Crayfish Hor Fun and even Shark Meat, Hong Lim Complex holds not only some of the best local foods in one place, but also a lesson or two into the food culture of Singapore both past and present.

This hawker centre is filled with great finds. One of the hawker centre that my family and I frequent.  <br><br>Many of stalls have stood the test of time. They have been there before and after the renovation. The food is still good and the queues for many are usually long.<br><br>Here are some of the recommendations that you can check out when you are here.<br>Ah Heng Curry Chicken Bee Hoon Mee<br>Ah Kow Mushroom Minced Pork Mee<br>Heng Kee Curry Chicken Mee<br>Outram Park Fried Kway Teow Mee<br>Tai Wah Pork Noodle<br>The Old Stall Hokkien Prawn Mee<br>Tuck Kee Sah (Ipoh) Hor Fun<br><br>You need to have a little patience eating here but you will definitely go home satisfied.

text: Awesome service by the staff here. I was looking for the Starbucks keycharm (out of stock at several outlets I went to) and the staff offered to take my contact details and call me once the stock arrive (targeted to be a few hours later). She did call me the same evening letting me know it has arrived. Kudos to that. <br><br>The place is spacious and gets crowded often. The drinks and food are usual Starbucks standard.

text: 3.5 stars<br><br>浅野屋 Asanoya Boulangerie is a famed Japanese bakery founded in Karuizawa in Negano Japan in the year 1933. Singapore was the first international location outside of Japan. <br><br>Past by the store at Paragon (Asanoya Boulangerie has three locations in Singapore), decided to pick up a few bread items. <br><br>There were so many kind of bread to choose from, pretty overwhelming. What made it worse was the chaos around. Patrons were rushing and fighting for the attention of the few staffs so they could place their orders. I did not like people being &#34;pushy&#34; around me. <br><br>I bought a melon pan and a seal bread (bread shaped as a seal). The male staff told me &#34;Buy 3 get 1 free!!&#34; I like &#34;Oh, I wanted to get another melon pan.&#34; Clearly the last thing on my mind was any free item. <br><br>The conversation went on like this: <br><br>The staff:  &#34;Buy 3 get 1 free!!&#34; <br><br>Me: &#34;Huh? Oh never mind.&#34;<br><br>The staff:  &#34;ok I would give you a free bread item.&#34; <br><br>Me: &#34;oh? Thank you!!&#34;<br><br>Lol!! I clearly did not get what the &#34;Buy 3 get 1 free&#34; means. Is it &#34;buy any 3 and get 1 free&#34; or &#34;buy 3 of the same&#34;? I know I should not overthink or make things too complicated, hahaha!!<br><br>Anyway, thank you for the staff for being so patient with me. I would come back and update the review after I try out the bread.

Cozy cafe with friendly staffs and a nice deco. Food are consistent with other Baker and Cook outlet which means exceptional! Sitting area is a bit small through and can only sit around 15 ppl. Make sure you get there early during peak hours and weekends. Nice addition to the Clementi Park neighbor.

text: The cheese tarts here are really good! If you like cheesecake or any type of cheese frosting, this place is for you. I tried both types of cheese tarts, the original and the salty egg yolk one. Both were good, salty egg yolk one has more flavor. But both are a must- try.

text: Very fresh - you can smell the yeast breads wafting through the store!<br>I like the creative, european inspiration that takes traditional pastries like pain au chocolat and adds little creative touches like pistachio crumbs or chocolate drizzle.<br><br>They do offer savory snacks like the new cheese sticks, but I prefer the classic sweets!  It&#39;s a great afternoon snack.

text: Bought more cheese tarts today and I have to say, after trying the long queue cheese tarts from across the hall, I much prefer the original lava cheese tarts from Bread Society! They raised the price to $2.40 per tart or buy 5 get 1 free, which works out to be $12 for 6, which is a great deal.  <br><br>The lava cheese filling is velvety smooth, very creamy and rich.  I think they tweaked the cookie crust recipe a little, because the cookie tart shells are still crunchy two hours later from when we got home.  My eldest son loves to eat them semi frozen with a firmer center.  <br><br>No queue, reasonably priced and delicious!

text: I stayed at the Hilton Singapore and discovered Bread Society by walking through the maze of shops and stores. This store attracted me by the artful pastries on display. Loved the fresh juices as well. It made for a quick snack/breakfast so I could do more shopping!

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/qYLex7DMz5P_bvu3AF775g/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/bread-society-singapore-2?reviewid=FOjeKB_23Iyyvt_XuH1qfg&select=qYLex7DMz5P_bvu3AF775g', 'altText': 'Photo of Bread Society - Singapore, Singapore', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': None}]
text: Very reasonably priced European style bakery. Grab a tray and your own set of tongs and help yourself. Focus is on croissants, breads and rolls, no cream tortes here. The goods are as fresh as it gets- you can actually see the staff bake through a giant glass window. <br>Credit cards accepted.

Opened by the BreadTalk group, Bread Society is set to be a posher version of the usual breadtalk chain store. While their offerings do look impressive, incorporating european influences with japanese flavours, getting a good bun here is sort of like a lucky draw. While they have interesting flavours, texture of their bread and buns are rather inconsistent. <br><br>I would recommend their chocolate croissants as those are the only products from bread society that has not failed to disappoint time and time again. Their blueberry bread is not bad too but once again, I&#39;ve had good and bad experiences with it. Their cakes did not impress on the 3 accounts, so if you are looking for quality cakes, go elsewhere.

text: Bread Society is a more upscale version of Bread Talk. They have some of the same breads here, but they also have more pastries and high end breads. Its located between Ion and Wheelock Place. <br><br>Some of their pastries and cakes are pretty good, but if you are really looking for quality, Id say its best to go to an actual pasty shop or bakery. Try the sliced and freshly baked breads here.

text: I love Paul when I was traveling to London and Paris. There were many outlets in London and I loved buying pastries from there when I was visiting my brother who was working there. Paul in Paris was magnifique too! These were all before Singapore has its own Paul located at Ngee Ann City. <br><br>The ambience at Paul Singapore is entirely different than those in Europe. I like the warm cozy feelings I had experienced at Paul in London or Paris which unfortunately did not happened here. It was not bad here, just different. <br><br>Few weeks back I had breakfast at Paul with my friend whom I used to go to school with. I opted the Petit déjeuner chocolat set ($9.50) and I chose to have a Au pain du chocolat and a cup of chocolat viennois. Both were really good. Finally I got to have a decent hot chocolate beverage after having a bad one here at Starbucks in Singapore. <br><br>Service was good too. <br><br>I just wish more thoughts to be placed in the design of the menu. A bit cheap looking to me.

Decided to try ... but not impressed<br>Slow to seat- a bit condescending <br>Took an order. - served one and told other that were out of crabs <br>Should have known when order was taken - anyway, instead of expediting burger ordered in its place, took ages and follow up for it to come<br>By that time one had finished and each had to watch the other eating <br>Iced tea was like warm

Slow service. Restaurant appears to be understaffed, I only saw 3 employees covering the whole restaurant. Shame, this chain is excellent in Paris &amp; London. Singapore needs to step it up with their service. 2 Stars for the pastries only.

text: Heard so much about this place for quite a while now and finally decided to try it this afternoon (was at Ngee Ann City &amp; feeling very hungry in the late afternoon). Got a window seat which is good.<br><br>Ordered a Crepe D&#39;orange &amp; a beetroot juice:<br><br>- Service was alright. Quite attentive, asking whether I want warm or cold water, &amp; whether I want ice cubes with my juice. <br><br>- Beetroot juice was ok though pricey. Guess it comes with the territory as Paul Bakery is situated  strategically at one of the most prominent shopping malls in SG.<br><br>- Crepe D&#39;orange is no ordinary crepe as its the most sorry looking crepe I have eaten in my life .. Just 1 strawberry split into quarters. I was utterly shocked that they served it in this manner. The crepe itself was quite tasty, so in a way, it redeemed itself a bit.<br><br>All in all, I&#39;m disappointed with the eatery, and will think twice to go back there again. Maybe, just maybe, I may try their breads to see whether they are any good.

text: The repertoire of 26 new dishes include hearty salads like the Salad de la Mer ($20.90++), a seafood salad that would make an ideal satisfying light lunch option with plump shrimps, mussels, octopus and creamy avocados. The zesty grapefruit and in house french dressing lends the greens a bright zesty flavour that resonates with me. <br><br>Both main courses reflected the simplicity of French cooking and natural flavours of fresh, seasonal ingredients. The Longe de thon ($29.90++) was essentially a long steak of seared tuna whose core remained pinkish and tender, adorned with white sesame seeds. Magnificent in its own right, the fish fell out of sync with the sweet cranberry sauce and the side of tangy roasted seasonal vegetables, which were so appetizing that they could possibly steal the limelight of the plate. <br><br>On the other hand, the Confit de Canard ($28.90++) may be an old-fashioned French classic but never fails to please the palates. Rubbed with herbs and cured in duck fat for one day before slow-roasted for 4 hours, the unctuous duck meat, albeit tad salty, streaked off the bones in strands.<br><br>It might be quite a distinct version from most of the crispy-skinned versions here but the duck is fragrantly meaty and not greasy. The same side dish of roasted vegetables did complement the duck but perhaps pairing it with some chestnut velouté with mushrooms may inject some variety? <br><br>New iced teas like the Rosemary lime or Lemongrass Ginger were great options to refresh the palates and get one ready for desserts. However what piqued my curiosity was the beguiling Macaron Drink ($9.50++) shown below. Available also in Raspberry, Vanilla and Chocolate, I opted for the Pistachio flavour. Predictably a sweet maestro of pistachio macarons speedily whizzed to gritty bits with milk, it turned out to be less sugary than the original macarons, tempered to a balanced creaminess with a characteristic texture. <br><br>Leaning gingerly against one another, the golden Waffles ($13.90++), as sturdy as the Pyramids of Egypt, were understandably more similar to the light crunchy Brussels waffles than the dense, chewy Liege waffles. Yet too much of a good thing may warrant a concern to oral pleasure as these square parcels were rather rigid inside-out.   <br><br>Above all, I am heartened that Paul stays true to its boulangerie roots and delivers the promised quality in their forte areas, the bread. Out of all the new dishes I&#39;ve tried, the Tartine Boeuf ($19.90++) secured a special place in my heart. A touch of herb cream cheese, hints of tart balsamic vinegar and a smattering of soft caramelized onions on succulent sirloin steak is all it takes to bring the humble countryside bread a whole new level. Even the starter basket of crusty baguette (below) sprung to life with just a slight dollop of its creamy unsalted artisan French butter.

text: I have been to this bakery bistro twice now and I have to say that I have not been impressed. They always say to give the good feedback first, so here goes - the ambiance is quite nice with its Parisian feel and decor. The service is passable but lacks any warmth. Now, my biggest complaint is the poor quality of coffee and pastry. After a hectic day of shopping, I just wanted to sit down and get a nice hit of caffeine. But I really can&#39;t get pass the weak coffee that tastes so diluted. Tried the blueberry and chocolate tarts - crust is too thick and hard and the filling is nothing to write home about. All in all, I don&#39;t think I will be making a third trip back.

text: it was dessert vs. real food and the real food won because i was just too hungry. i opted for the Salmon Croque-monsieur. if you are a cheese lover you will love this one for sure. the cheese was fried to a crisp and the salmon compliments it so well. I believe I will order this same dish again when I do visit Paul again. <br><br>The waffle dessert at the next table caught my eye. I must return to give that a try. I would say all their desserts are well priced and especially delicious looking.

Thank you<br><br>UPDATES:<br><br>the young Indian guy just keeps hanging around the cashier doing nothing on a Sunday .  To the boss, you&#39;re making a loss hiring him. And to the other Indian waiter with beard, your smug attitude won&#39;t get you anywhere in life.<br><br>Only managed to take a pic of the smug waiter, not the younger one.

text: Nice place and decor. Relaxed atmosphere. However, staff is not very attentive - no cutleries, courses including ice-cream was served at the same time as main course, food was served before drinks, ice-water served only upon request. Quality of food - 6/10. Croissant served cold - not warmed up. Staff rather inexperience but polite. Politeness: 7/10.

This place was such a let down. It may look pretty on the outside but the food was wayy overpriced in my opinion and it honestly wasn&#39;t anything spectacular. <br><br>I had the scrambled eggs with sausages and mushroom breakfast thingy for $9.80 and a cup of hot chocolate. Hot chocolate was bitter and disappointing. The eggs were alright. They didn&#39;t have any sandwiches when I was there (11am ish) and I was pretty disappointed by that. Furthermore, the staff were really unfriendly.

text: I honestly wished I have nicer things to say about Paul Bakery.<br><br>For starters, I loved most part of the service I got at Paul&#39;s. Had a delightful lady and gentleman serving and they looked like the genuinely loved what they&#39;re doing which -always- make for a nice touch. I just wished I got their names! <br><br>Paul is constantly loaded with people so be prepared for a bit of a wait, try not to let that dent your mood. Also try not to go with too much of an expectation.<br><br>My friend got a breakfast set while I had the crepes. They were nothing to write home to and with the choices you get in SG now, I hardly think just doing the basic works. Also, I hardly feel that way, but the quality of the food made me feel that it was really overpriced.<br><br>I was genuinely looking forward to trying the desserts since Paul is famed for their bakes. Am a little disappointed to report that both options I picked - lemon meringue tart and another pastry - were lacklustre. <br><br>Moral of the story - listen to your foodie friends when they tell you not to bother with a place.

text: Pretty overrated. Service in particular very poor.  Staff very skilled at looking off in the distance - past customers trying to get service.  I ordered tartine boeuf.  They brought tartine poulet.  When I pointed this out the waiter insisted it was beef then ran away.  I had to pull out the photo menu to make the case to his colleague once I was able to get her attention that it was chicken.  Maybe short staffed on the eve before Chinese new year?  Maybe the staff here are disgruntled they are having to work?  My food finally came only after the rest of my family had finished theirs.  At that only after I asked for help from the manager.  Who produced my plate and then scuttled away.  Two stars only because the tartine was good.  Otherwise a solidly one star experience.

I love Paul ...at Tanglin Mall! <br><br>This location here in Takashimaya has the worst staff. Ever!  There is a line, when inside half of the tables are empty. When you call to place you order, it looks like they are making you a favor.  And good luck if are with a stroller!  Two star instead if one, because the good is still great. Won&#39;t be back.

The lovely takeaway area, many tasty delights for a next day&#39;s breakfast.', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': "The lovely takeaway area, many tasty delights for a next day's breakfast."}]
text: Hmm, the food is good, the atmosphere is nice, even the &#34;outdoor&#34; seating, but the service and policies really bring it down, I&#39;d give this 2.5 stars if I could.<br><br>This a popular restaurant and the long queue waiting to get seated shows that, it also calls out for a better managed system, maybe a waiting list and SMS when there is an available table, something better. There is also a take away counter, like a traditional bakery with many tasty items calling out to be taken home. This take away counter presents another odd policy/system that should be better thought out. There are items at the take away counter that aren&#39;t on the menu, and you can&#39;t order them if you are dining in. This is such an odd decision, it is the same restaurant/kitchen the food is already prepared, sell the item for a dollar more and laugh all the way to the bank; yet they would not serve it. Speaking of serving items, our drinks arrived much after our food, and many follow up requests, even a freshly baked waffle came before Ice Lemon Tea. Even the second round of tea took so long to arrive, very disappointing.

text: After shopping, dining, and striking out somewhere else for dessert, we decided on Paul.<br><br>What was defintitely more difficult was deciding exactly what to have from their extensive menu of sweets.<br><br>The staff was friendly and helpful.  The room is quaint with a touch of old world charm.<br><br>Finally, after much deliberation, we settled on our choices. <br><br>Strawberry Tart for her<br><br><a href="/redir?url=http%3A%2F%2Ftinyurl.com%2F93aqdwg&amp;s=3ce78f8da862127097e2b98b891a5e8a7cbc411e83cefcc4a0be86e94b64a823" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">tinyurl.com/93aqdwg</a><br><br>Chocolate Sundae for me<br><br><a href="/redir?url=http%3A%2F%2Ftinyurl.com%2F8hty8a4&amp;s=c1eaa2d206f276f70e4a51725b4ac16d8f740de3ea8e63e3a06b49d082607d56" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">tinyurl.com/8hty8a4</a><br><br>Both desserts were fantastic and both were eagerly engulfed.<br><br>I would not hesitate to have dessert here again.

text: We arrived with 2 kids, so needed a table of four.  We walked past an empty table that&#39;s just near the outside takeaway section and proceeded to queue up.<br><br>Told the person we needed a table for four, and she smiled - good sign.  And we waited patiently, assuming that empty table must have been reserved.<br><br>Time passed and Sok. The front staff cane back to ask how many seats we needed - the same one we told we needed a table for four, sigh.  My wife had had enough by now and just plainly asked if we can sit at the empty table.  The front staff looked a little confused, checked and then came told us it was available!  Wonder how long we would have waited if we weren&#39;t proactive.  <br><br>Food was average.  Took an extremely long time to arrive.<br><br>But worst was the service.  Staff were polite but doesn&#39;t work to make the dining experience a worthwhile one.<br><br>I wouldn&#39;t recommend coming to dine in.  Perhaps take away, but save some heartache  and skip the dine in experience :-(

text: Hailing all the way from mainland France, Paul is a traditional bakery, which opened with much fanfare. But it&#39;s easy to see why it&#39;s usually packed with customers all day. <br><br>It serves freshly baked produce like croissants, tarts, pies, breads and éclairs. For those who hate mornings but enjoy breakfast, Paul&#39;s Bakery has all day breakfasts too, among other savory bites. The usual teas and coffees are also available to accompany your meal.<br><br>The price can be on the steep side, so do be prepared to fork out a hefty sum, if you plan on having a feast.

text: My friend hates it that I affectionately call it LAO PAUL. She thinks it&#39;s undeserving of one of the most famous bakeries in Paris. Sigh. How else to express my love?<br><br>If you&#39;ve been to Ngee Ann City in the past few months, or have frequented Kinokuniya, Paul is impossible to miss. The eye-catching artisan decor stands out from the modern lines of Takashimaya. According to their spokesperson, &#34;Everything from the breads to the decor is authentic to the standards set in other Paul bakeries worldwide.&#34;<br><br>The food was reasonably tasty, most of their pastries (Millefeuille nature especially) were crusty and not overly sweet. I liked their mini macaroons, so *powerpuff* and noms. If you like pastries with a tinge of sourness, try the fruit tarts. Price is a little steep but within expectations. There are promotional sets such as ALL-DAY-BREAKFAST sets, baker&#39;s basket; mostly priced below $10 to make it worth your while. <br><br>I&#39;ve been there a few times, service has been good. Once, there was an enthusiastic waiter whom we inquired with on closing hours.<br><br>Him: It&#39;s 10 officially but we stay on till the last customer leaves.<br>Me: What if the customer doesn&#39;t leave?! <br>Him: We have our methods.<br><br>LOL.<br><br>It&#39;s easy to emulate the tai-tai life sitting at Paul&#39;s, sipping on chamomile tea. Pretty nice respite in the middle of Orchard Road.

Very Slow Service!!!<br><br>Because I can go to many other places to find food similar to what I get here, I&#39;m rating this fully on service.<br>One thing I can&#39;t stand is my glass being empty. I had to ask while flagging a waitress down to get another drink after my glass had been empty for quite some time. To make it worse, I had to remind her much later that I hadn&#39;t gotten my drink yet.<br><br>If you have nothing else on your agenda for the day, then I would say go here. The menu is great.  However, the service is slow and spotty.

I hope they&#39;ll work to improve the quality of service.  After seeing long queues on previous visits to the mall, we were happy to be seated immediately.  As other reviewers have noted, the service here is spotty.  <br><br>My friend and I each ordered an entree.  His Salade Nicoise arrived immediately but there was an additional 12 min wait for my Tartine Boeuf to be delivered.  This type of delay is a common problem in lower quality Singapore restaurants and there&#39;s no excuse for it other than managers who do not train their staffs to western standards.  In western cultures, it&#39;s rude to begin eating until everyone has been served.  All western style restaurants in Singapore need to institute a system in which no entrees are delivered to a table until all entrees are ready in the kitchen.   Then all entrees are delivered at the same time.  This is not a difficult system to implement.<br><br>This is the result of service by committee when one waiter is not assigned to a table.  The committee of servers are not insuring the overall guest experience - instead they are blindly taking orders and then delivering the food when it appears in the kitchen window.  No one takes ownership of the table.<br><br>While waiting for my food, servers tried to give me 3 other entrees which belonged to nearby tables.  US restaurants use a numbering system that assigns each table and seat a number.   When the item leaves the kitchen the server knows to precisely deliver it to Table 12, Position 2.  This eliminates the need for the waiter to &#34;auction&#34; the plate at the table.  For me, this is the clear separating line between the amateurs and the professionally run restaurants.<br><br>My Tartine Boeuf was delicious, but I can&#39;t make sense of the $7.50 lemon ice tea that was nothing special.  Usually when you pay so much for an iced tea, there is a simple syrup offered for sweetening.  My friend says his Salade Nicoise was bland with not enough dressing.  (I had 12 minutes to look at it and it looked bland) <br><br>The Good:  My Tartine Boef was delicious.  The two take away bakery items (chocolate torte and elclair) were also good.<br><br>The Bad:  <br>1. Servers who don&#39;t know the correct pronunciations of the french dishes, <br><br>2. A system that does not guarantee that all entrees are delivered to a table at the same time.  Of course a salad takes less time to prepare.  Don&#39;t deliver it until the longer prep items are ready.  Managers - this is not rocket science!!<br><br>3 Servers who &#34;auction&#34; the wrong entrees to you unsure of who the food belongs to.  Again, this is easily resolved with a numbering system - using both the table and seat number.  An international clientele in a restaurant that offers a supposedly &#34;upscale&#34; experience deserves better.<br><br>4. Some tables are so close together that you feel like you&#39;re dining with strangers.<br><br>5.Bland salad, $7.50 iced tea??!!  No syrup.<br><br>Total for 2 entrees and 2 beverages: $60+<br><br>The Verdict: The 10 min+ wait between entrees being delivered is the deal breaker. The prices are too high for such amateur service.  Will not be returning

text: Had dinner here Saturday because the other sit down restaurants had long waits. Located in Takashiyama Mall 3rd level.  Reviews gave food good ratings but a lot of complaints about poor service. FYI  waiters are not assigned to specific tables so you have to flag anyone you see to get service.  This is basically how it&#39;s done in Hong Kong.  Anyway, I ordered fish and chips and my wife had spicy seafood pasta, which contained large prawns and baby clams. Both entrees were very good except my fries (chips) which were not hot the way good frites should be.  We had cappuccino and double Expresso and shared a very good raspberry tarte.  I would eat here again because of the food and fair prices

text: The food and setting is ok , but quite frankly the service is disgraceful. The staff are rude. Would never go back

surprised to see such negative reviews here.<br><br>managed to try a number of items ranging from meringues, lemon tarts,pasta, some egg dish in a group.<br><br>Yes, its pricey but the standard is there. the pasta was light and fluffy, with great great seasoning. Times like this, I really feel the urge to hug the chef and thank him or her for doing things so impeccably awesome.<br><br>the lemon tart wasn&#39;t overly acidic and had a sweet sour curd that brought a high end to my meal

text: The worst cafeshop which somehow has been extemely overated more than it deserves. From the service to the food quality, there is no reason why this cafe still exists.. Even in a prime location such as Nge Ann City/Takashimaya at Orchard??! It is such an embarrassement to French cuisine which highly values its cooking quality with long heritage.<br><br>We ordered a simple baquette sandwich which came with a mushroom soup. The sandwich was plain and lack of freshness while the soup was salty, like it just came out from an instant soup packet, and the accompanied bun was like a 1-week old bread which was hard like a rock. Goodness, that was really injustice considering the price we had to pay for such a below quality. For the sake of culinary world, do something about the food! Improve and stop serving less-thought and low-quality of food to the hungry shoppers.

text: The great baked goods doesn&#39;t overshadow the garbage service at this place.   <br>&#34;Sorry sir that section is closed&#34; when I asked if it would open in five minutes I was given the laugh and shrug, sure enough it was open.  <br><br>The baked goods are delicious but the other cooked food is ok, and the service is pretty garbage.  After months of being open, they can&#39;t seem to be flexible enough to seat a party over 2 people in under 10 minutes-even when there are tables open.  <br>All the small details you expect with your order, fresh butter and jam, are left in the kitchen with any smiles from the waitstaff  Try going earlier and the service is just as bad, but not as crowded.  Lunchtime-I imagine if the owners knew how much business they turned off or turned away they would actually invest in training their waitstaff.  Everyone working there seems pretty miserable.  Next time, I&#39;ll pass - I heard the new french bakery in Wisma is nice.

I used to go to Paul, when I lived in Dubai and occasionally craved a boulangerie (the other options were terrible). It was okay, there.<br><br>Here, it&#39;s also okay. But not as good as it can be. I suppose when things get this commercialized, you lose the charm and personality that you once had. There&#39;s not that much to shout about.

text: Nice food but terrible service verging on rude.  We were told at the counter we could sit down at the restaurant and they would bring us the counter food we wanted to eat.  Unfortunately for us we missed the sign asking us to wait to be seated and went in taking a seat close to the food counter.  No welcome from the waitress who instead took her time coming to serve us and then muttered under her breath that we should go back and queue up at the entry - despite there being many free tables and no-one waiting outside (inflexible protocol?).  She finally relented to serve us although didn&#39;t know what a ginger beer was (her unhelpful reply was that they don&#39;t serve alcohol - rather than to explain what they did have).  The baguette we ordered came out and as we started to eat they started trying to take the plate away saying they weren&#39;t allowed to serve it that way!  We finally understood that it was supposed to come with a side salad but by then we were so annoyed we said we&#39;d eat it as is.  The baguette was good - similar to the ones we know from Paul&#39;s in Paris but the service was so disappointing we wouldn&#39;t be back.

text: Have you been caught in the &#34;waiting&#34; glitch? And when I mentioned Paul Bakery, what is the first thing that comes to mind? Nope, not the fresh loaves loved by some, nor the bewitching patisseries they offer. It is the less celebrated service standards experienced by many. Not sure if I was in luck, I have had enjoyed good hospitality which I have reviewed earlier. While many were overjoyed at its opening, Paul was plagued by unhappy voices. <br><br>They have been drawing big crowds since the day they opened, which I have never doubt. Despite the lapsed in service, I am still seeing people making beeline at its entrance after peak hours. The main dining hall was bustling with high tea enthusiasts - conversations echoing the room. J suggested we take one of the tables outside the restaurant for a quieter time, much to what I agreed. We managed to get one with the help of a waiter - polite (checked). Without spilt seconds, another waiter came with 2 sets of menu and giving us ample time to decide (checked).<br><br>I hold the menu in my hand with great anticipation. Unmistakably, it was given a face-lift with a range of newer creation - still the French classics but now, some with a local twist. New faces includes specialty sandwiches: Pan Bagnat Club (S$16.90); open sandwiches: Salade Crevettes Mangue (S$19.90), Croque Truffade (S$19.90) - a simple toast topped with cheddar cheese, Béchamel sauce, truffles &amp; mushrooms which most suits anyone with a less complicated desire. Then comes the Haute dishes: Hachis Parmentier (S$23.90) - a dish of minced beef/chicken mixed in buttery pureed potatoes and tossed with onions &amp; herbs. <br><br>This time, a young lady dropped by to see if we are ready to order which I requested she check on us after a minute which she did so accordingly (checked). During the wait for the meal, glasses of water are served and refilled automatically (checked).<br><br>I am most curious to examine this new open sandwich to see if it is capable of spicing up my day. Having learned that the concoction took the team months to perfect, I am hoping that it passed the mark remarkably. Served with a handful of crisp seasonal side greens, this Tartine Poulet Curry (S$17.90) comes with a unique flavor rarely seen in a French bistro. Making a bold change to the regular Poulet Citron in the previous menu; this one has a nice but mild spicy marination. Though I find the coarsely chopped chicken meat a bit chewy and dry, the spices did distract my attention from the less attractive bird. The curry jelled quite well with the cheddar along with the crunchy diced zucchini and tomato, of which, the mass emits a strong and lingering flavor in each mouthful. Overall, the combination is a success for its balanced flavor, without a fierce domination. I was told that it has been well-received by many non-locals for its subtle curry taste. While it tasted good, I feel that the Campagne bread needs less toasting time, to avoid having a hard and edgy crust that bruised my gums. If you ever spotted me tearing - the underlying cause is not the curry, sure thing. But what warms me, is the hospitality that comes from the heart. This has never occurred nor I heard from others who have dined at Paul in the past, but today, I am having waitress coming up to me, asking if the food tastes good (checked).<br><br>J was seen enjoying the Pan Bagnat Niçoise (S$16.90) - a specialty sandwich made with Pain de Mie bread using tuna mayonnaise topped with rings of red onion, tomatoes and piling up high with fresh salad leaves and slices of boiled eggs. The burger appeared in its clean defining look, not a messy setup like a drenched American version. Accordingly, it pleases J who is won over by its fresh texture and natural taste, less obscuring. We selfishly eat our own dish, each singing in approval. We have nothing to complain about, if anything, it has to be the dessert.<br><br>Prominently pictured under the dessert section, I refused to flip the page, trying to nail down one Pandan treats. J gave a good laugh and left me with the decision rights. Should I point to my left or allow it to swift to the right, my eye ball swinging in pendulum. I had wanted a Pandan eclair but wish badly for the Pandan Millefeuille. J saved me from that ripping agony, chose the French puff pastry on my behalf. In less 5 minute, the Napoleon dessert arrived. My first impression - terrified. I felt intimidated by its unnatural green hue, the icing fondant has been awkwardly fabricated - simply a vanilla glaze. It left me wondering if the dish descriptions in the newspaper are reported correctly - the recipe has a Pandan-infused paste? Erm, we didn&#39;t taste any Pandan flavor throughout, but a stronger gula melaka (palm sugar) custard cream, much to our enjoyment. I liked the puff pastry for its light, crumbly texture though not ultra flaky and stacked up with a thick layer of creamy paste in the middle. The cream is smooth but slightly over-candied and a bit weighed down.

Tried two of their famous pastries (the millefueille and one of the chocolate cake) as recommended by the waitress and they are both too sweet. <br><br>The coffee is also too weak for my liking.<br><br>Wasn&#39;t worth the wait, wasn&#39;t worth the price, wasn&#39;t worth the hype.

text: I&#39;m not sure what the hype is all about<br>1) Service was terrible. They were so disorganized getting ppl seated. Ppl were standing in line for 30-45 mins for no apparent reason- there were plenty of open tables at any one time. I almost sat myself<br>2) Macarons were OK. In a country where ppl are avid travelers and have dined in Paris/ France/ Europe on authenitic macarons, i&#39;m not sure why they&#39;re passing off these good but not great cookies as macarons<br>3) Over-priced.
This place is overrated.. Expensive bread, you can get the same or even better ones at stores in the basement.

Having tried the famous and amazing Paul patisserie in Paris, I was elated about the news of the opening of Paul Bakery at Ngee Ann City. Sipping a hot cup of coffee and biting into a warm butter croissant on a chilly winter day in Paris was the most memorable experience and I thought I could relive it here in Singapore at Paul Bakery.<br> <br>Although the seating was really cramped, the interior of Paul did remind me of Parisian patisseries. The chandeliers, French paintings and even the waitresses in white chef hats really simulate the setting of French restaurants.<br> <br>Food-wise, there were a few hits and misses. The highly recommended Chocolate Mellefeuille was a let down because the pastry was not crispy but limp instead. The chocolate flavor was good though, rich and not overly-sweet. The Praline Macaron was great, crusty on the outside and filled with creamy rich praline. The Caneles have a really good texture as well.<br> <br>The service was slow, probably because they were short of staff. It was difficult getting the attention of the waitstaff and the food took pretty long to arrive.

text: This is a review on the takeaway counter of Paul. I havent actually had a sit down lunch/dinner/breakfast at Paul but i have frequented their take away counter on numerous occasions. <br><br>First of all the staff is really friendly. There are very knowedgeable and accomdating and are always smiling. The best thing here are the crossaints. Especially when they are still warm and out of the oven. Incomparable to a place like Delifrance, they are flaky, chewy and super buttery. I like the mini crossaints and pastries that they have. <br><br>They also have beautiful french pastries and sandwhiches. I had a crossaint from the Paul at the Paris airport, and i honestly thought the crossaints in the Singapore Paul were way better!
How dare they not have a chausson au pommes? They are good though, especially the berry tartes.

text: Just sat down for coffee and desserts, service is horrible. Had to wait for 30minutes for coffee and macaroon. No matter how good the food is, will never come back to this branch.

go there for the mini croissants (or big plain croissants), and palmierre. <br>everything else is quite terrible.<br><br>the listing here says they open at 8:30 am. is that right? i&#39;ve been there at 10 am where they had no croissants yet.<br><br>the service over the take-away counter was pretty good ...i went there and they forgot to give me an &#34;apple donut&#34; that i already paid for. i went back in the evening, and they gave it to me, no questions asked...even though i didn&#39;t have my receipt, and i was dealing with an entirely different staff. kudos to the staff for that.

The world renowned bakery from France has finally made in-roads into our local scene with a 3,000sq ft restaurant and bakery that is set to whet appetites. At this point of time though, with the number of visits I&#39;ve made, the standard of the breads are not really consistent as compared to the ones at Maison Kayser. However, on their good days, the croissants and baguettes are simply a delight to have. One of the must try items at the restaurant are the breakfast sets which many people don&#39;t know about. While they seem simple, Paul does it supremely well and at a far more affordable price compared to other places.
